<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietTrucks     07-20 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Trucks,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Soviet Auto Export to US Will be Truck</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Avtoexport in 2nd graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's first automotive export to the
United States will be a heavy-duty dump truck used in mining, and
could be shipped to customers within three months, a Soviet export
official said.
   Boris Hubaev, first deputy general director of Avtoexport, the
Soviet Union's export agency, said Tuesday he will negotiate for
two days later this week in New York with Global Technology Group,
a U.S. company that will help find a distributor for the product
and set up a parts and service network.
   Global Technology Group deals with various types of exported
consumer goods, and the Soviets hope to find a distributor for
their trucks ``as soon as possible,'' Hubaev said.
   The U.S.S.R. produces about 2,500 of the specialized heavy-duty
trucks a year, Hubaev said. The vehicles already are sold in Peru.
   Hubaev said Avtoexport would consider pricing its trucks
somewhat lower than other vehicles in the U.S. heavy-duty truck
market, which accounts for about 140,000 vehicle sales a year. He
said the Soviet Union produces heavy-duty trucks capable of
carrying loads up to 180 tons.
   The Soviet Union, however, has no plans to expand its annual
production of about 900,000 trucks, including buses, Hubaev said.
He said the Soviets are aiming to double passenger car production
within the next six to seven years.
   Hubaev was scheduled today to address the Automotive News World
Congress, a trade journal-sponsored gathering of auto industry
executives, suppliers and analysts.
</TEXT>
