<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatalWreck     07-20 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Wreck,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Killed, Three Injured in Car-Tanker Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ELLENTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker truck sliced through a car
carrying nine family members Tuesday, killing seven people and
critically injuring three others, police said.
   The collision ruptured the truck's 5,000-gallon tank, spilling
an unidentified substance onto the roadway and forcing residents
within a half-mile of the accident scene to leave their homes for
nearly four hours.
   The wreck took the lives of a 35-year-old New Ellenton man and
six of his relatives ranging in age from 3 to 18. Three other
people, including the truck driver, were listed in critical
condition at the Medical College of Georgia Hospital in nearby
Augusta late Tuesday.
   ``This is the worst I've experienced,'' said Aiken County
Coroner Sue Townsend.
   Details of the accident were still sketchy, but bystanders said
the car had just pulled onto highway U.S. 278 south of New Ellenton
about 4 p.m. and appeared to be turning around in the road when the
truck hit it. The truck sliced through the vehicle, and the impact
of the collision tore loose a set of wheels from the truck, police
said.
   Fire Chief Melvin Flippen said officials could not identify the
chemical spilled during the acacident, but treated it as if it were
toxic. The area covered by the evacuation order is sparsely
populated.
   One firefighter was treated for heat exhaustion and released.
   The dead were identified as Eddie Harrison Jr., 35; his nieces,
Monica Renee Harrison, 18, and Venessa Nicole Williamson, 6; his
son Evon, 15; daughters Azarene, 8, and Angel, 7; and his grandson,
Jamal Harrison, 3.
</TEXT>
