<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Quality     07-20 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Quality,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Creates New Bureau To Oversee Quality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has set up a new state bureau to oversee
efforts to reduce the number of shoddy, substandard goods on the
market and make Chinese products more competitive on world markets,
an official daily said today.
   In announcing creation of the State Bureau of Technical
Supervision, State Councillor Song Jian said substandard products
remain a serious problem, the China Daily said.
   It said a spot check of industrial products earlier this year
found that only 20 percent fully satisfied national standards.
   The paper said the new bureau will strengthen supervision over
technology and establish an authoritative system of standardization
and measurement.
   Song was quoted as saying Tuesday said that since China
initiated its economic reforms and open-door policy in 1979, it has
put into effect more than 11,000 state standards and 500
measurement regulations.
</TEXT>
