<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz-Asia Bjt   07-20 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Asia, Bjt,0931</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Tries to Project U.S. Power, Scores Some Successes</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over the past two weeks, Washington has been
sending two strong messages to Asia: the United States is not a
declining economic power and it has no intention of pulling its
forces from the eastern Pacific rim.
   The messenger is George P. Shultz, making his last and longest
trip to Asia since becoming U.S. secretary of state in 1982.
   Starting July 6, Shultz visited Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia,
the Philippines, Hong Kong, China, South Korea and Japan. By and
large, it was a successful farewell.
   Addressing nations whose economic well-being would be
jeopardized if America goes into a downward spin, Shultz maintained
that despite the world's largest trade deficit, the United States
enjoys a ``stronger economy today than ever before in its history.''
   Despite recent anti-American demonstrations in South Korea and
the Philippines, virtually all the region's leaders reportedly told
Shultz they want a substantial U.S. presence in Asia _ military,
economic and political.
   If any anxiety was expressed it was over perceived American
political wavering, growing protectionism and isolationist trends
that Asian leaders fear could leave the Asian field fallow for the
Soviet Union _ and eventually for China and Japan, said U.S.
officials who took part in the talks.
   ``That was the message (to us) all over. The United States has
great responsibilities and you have to assume those
responsibilities,'' Gaston Sigur, the department's top Asian
official, said in an interview. ``Nobody is asking us to come out
here to be dictators, but you have to be involved and I don't see
any intention on our part not to be involved.''
   In the Philippines, Shultz' talks with President Corazon Aquino,
who has become a personal friend, and with other leaders apparently
helped hurdle problems in assessing U.S. naval and air bases in
that country.
   Manila is pressing for more than the $180 million a year the
U.S. now pays for the bases. Shultz appeared willing to make some
compromises, but has refused to regard the compensation merely as
rent due an ally.
   The treaty covering America's largest bases outside its mainland
is up for renewal in 1991. Shultz stressed that the United States
would relocate the facilities elsewhere in the Asia-Pacific area if
the anti-base movement succeeds.
   In South Korea, he pledged America's 42,000 troops will help
ward off any attack if North Korea opts to disrupt the Olympic
Games in Seoul. And U.S. officials expressed satisfaction that
security arrangements with Japan, where 60,000 American troops are
stationed, remain solid.
   ``America's resolve to help our Korean ally ... repel aggression
from the North is as firm now as when we signed our mutual defense
treaty in 1953,'' Shultz said in a speech in Seoul. Radicals have
been demanding that all American forces leave the divided peninsula.
   Sigur, the department's assistant secretary for East Asian and
Pacific affairs, said Manila and Seoul were not moving away from
security ties with the United States but toward redefining how
close they should be.
   ``They want to have more of a say in defining it. That's fine,''
Sigur said. ``It may cause us a bit of heartburn here and there but
it's a good, healthy attitude.''
   China and non-Communist Southeast Asian nations, Sigur said,
similarly signaled their desire for a U.S. counterbalance, given
unsettled Chinese-Soviet relations, the conflict in Cambodia and a
potential threat from the big Soviet military base at Cam Ranh Bay
in Vietnam.
   In Beijing, Shultz acknowledged that he was unable to dissuade
Chinese leaders from selling ballistic missiles in the Middle East.
But he emphasized that the two countries have forged mature
relations across a broad spectrum, and the Chinese agreed.
   The two sides appeared to reach broad agreement on a political
settlement in Cambodia, although it remains unclear how China will
deal with the Khmer Rouge, whom they currently supply with weapons.
   Shultz called for the withdrawal of all Vietnamese forces from
Cambodia, voiced strong support for Cambodian resistance leader
Prince Norodom Sihanouk and expressed American abhorrence of the
Khmer Rouge.
   The Khmer Rouge, now in a three-party rebel alliance, killed
millions of Cambodians during its rule from 1975 until the
Vietnamese invaded in 1978.
   On almost every stop, Shultz, a former economics professor,
lauded free trade and linked economic successes in Asia to the
unhindered flow of goods and ideas.
   In a rare moment of public combativeness, Shultz lashed out at
South Korea for keeping its doors shut to American exports.
   ``If my statement causes anti-Americanism, so be it,'' he said.
   Shultz cited a host of statistics to show how tightly the
American and Asian economies are enmeshed.
   The United States, for example, is market for more than 50
percent of manufactured exports from non-communist Southeast Asia.
Exports to the United States have fueled South Korea's dramatic
growth and helped to sustain Japan's at a combined cost to the U.S.
of about $70 billion in trade deficits.
   But while this reliance on the American market has reaped big
rewards for Asia, it has also spawned anxiety. Asian leaders
attacked pending U.S. legislation that would restrict imports, and
free-trader Shultz shared their displeasure.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Denis D. Gray, chief of the AP's bureau in
Bangkok, has been covering the Far East since the mid-1970s and
traveled with Shultz on his Asian tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
