<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Protest 3rdLd-Writethru a0832 07-20 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Protest, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0832,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 134 At Anti-Abortion Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts graf on 12 other arrests after 3rd pvs bgng ``Other
groups'' and subs 9th pvs bgng ``Two Municipal'' with 2 grafs on
some protesters held overnight.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 134 hymn-singing abortion
opponents blocking a medical clinic Tuesday, while at the official
convention protest site a mock trial convicted House Speaker Jim
Wright of ethics violations.
   As temperatures climbed above 90 once again, demonstrators of
every stripe took to the streets to bid for attention from
delegates and reporters on the second day of the Democratic
National Convention.
   Other groups that took their turn on the stage of a two-acre
parking lot near The Omni convention site included the American
Indian Movement, protesting the treatment of native Americans, and
No Business as Usual, which denounced the ``Star Wars'' defense
plan as a step toward World War III. The stage and equipment were
provided by the city, which has scheduled protests throughout the
convention at two-hour intervals.
   Twelve other protesters were arrested at various sites around
the city, according to convention security spokeswoman Myrna May.
She said four were spray-painting anti-war slogans on a government
building, four were blocking a sidewalk near the Carter
Presidential Center and four were obstructing police at a building.
   The day began with mass arrests three miles north of the
convention zone outside the Atlanta SurgiCenter, a medical clinic
which performs abortions and other outpatient surgery. Abortion
opponents singing hymns sat or lay across the steps and in front of
the door, blocking access to the plain brick building.
   Police moved in at about 7 a.m., arresting 134 protesters, at
the request of the clinic.
   ``We did not have any kinds of abuse. They simply would not
move,'' said Police Maj. Ken Burnette.
   The protesters, part of a group called Operation Rescue Atlanta,
did not interfere with any patients, said a clinic employee who
declined to be identified: ``It's so early in the morning that we
really did not have patients scheduled.''
   Charges included criminal trespassing, unlawful assembly and
interfering with a police officer, Burnette said. Those arrested
were taken to the city's Lakewood Fairgrounds, where buildings are
equipped to house and process people arrested during the convention.
   Two Municipal Court judges processed the protesters at a
warehouse on the fairgrounds and set bond at $500 to $600 for each.
   Nine who gave police their names were allowed to post bond, but
the remaining 125 were taken to the city correction center because
they would only identify themselves as ``Baby Jane Doe'' or ``Baby
John Doe.''
   Meanwhile, a group called Public Advocates of the U.S. staged a
``trial'' of Wright complete with a ``judge'' in black robes. The
mock court found Wright guilty of ethics violations before a small
``jury'' of early-morning onlookers.
   Wright, the convention chairman, is under investigation by the
House Ethics Committee because of allegations that he made unduly
large royalties on a book he wrote. The book was printed by a
longtime campaign contractor for the Texas congressman and edited
by a member of Wright's congressional staff.
   Also under investigation are charges that Wright improperly
intervened with federal regulators on behalf of Texas businesses.
   Outside the Carter Presidential Center, four anti-war protesters
were arrested on charges of disorderly conduct-impeding traffic and
taken to the city jail, said Jackie Barrett, spokeswoman for the
DNC Command Center.
   And at a downtown hotel, police scuffled with demonstrators
supporting Tawana Brawley after New York Democratic officials
refused to let them into a meeting of the state's delegation. There
were no apparent injuries no arrests.
   Miss Brawley, a black 16-year-old, has alleged that she was
attacked by six white men last November in Dutchess County, N.Y.,
one of whom flashed a badge like a police officer's. Her advisers
have persuaded her not to cooperate with a special state
investigation of the incident being conducted by state officials,
who they insist are racists bent on covering up the truth.
   Red Cross volunteers were on duty again Tuesday, giving out cold
water to overheated demonstrators, onlookers and journalists, and
assisting those suffering in the heat _ estimated to be even higher
in the blacktop parking lot than elsewhere.
   On Monday, between 40 and 50 people were treated for heat
exhaustion, said Bill Saye, captain of the Red Cross team. They
included a half-dozen members of the Guardian Angels anti-crime
group, who ``dropped like flies'' while standing at parade rest,
Saye said.
   ``I told them to get some liquids in them, but they wouldn't
listen,'' he said, adding that two of the Angels, both from
Chicago, were taken to a hospital with severe heat exhaustion.
   Also on hand Tuesday afternoon in the demonstration area were
advocates for the mothers of Atlanta's ``missing and murdered
children,'' slain during 1979-81. Wayne B. Williams was convicted
of two of the killings, and subsequently blamed for 22 more _
although he was never charged in those cases. The demonstrators are
seeking legal help for the mothers who still wonder who really
killed their children, said spokeswoman Betty Youmans.
   Elsewhere, a Business Roundtable reception for Sens. Bob Graham
of Florida and Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia was canceled when
members of the Service Employees International Union set up an
informational picket line outside the Marriott Marquis Hotel. The
union represents janitors at the hotel who are in the midst of a
labor dispute with the hotel's owner, Atlanta architect-developer
John Portman Jr.
</TEXT>
