<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Navy-SpyCase     07-20 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy-Spy Case,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Probes Defection of Former Navy Man Who Worked With Spy
Photos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials are conducting a ``serious
investigation'' into the defection to the Soviet Union of a former
Navy enlisted man and reservist who had access to valuable
satellite intelligence data.
   ``We are quite concerned about what he might have given the
Soviets,'' a Navy source said after Glenn Michael Souther, 31,
appeared on Soviet television Tuesday.
   Souther disappeared in May 1986 after he was confronted by
federal agents in an espionage investigation.
   During his TV appearance, Souther said the FBI had hounded him
out of the country. The Soviet government newspaper Izvestia
reported Sunday that he had been granted asylum in that country.
   Souther had access to classified information while assigned to
Europe and later while on reserve duty in Norfolk, Va., said the
Navy official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   Among the duties that Souther had in the Navy was analyzing data
collected by satellites. Access to that sort of information would
tell the Soviets what capabilities the United States has to
photograph their installations and intercept their communications
using satellites, and also what areas U.S. intelligence was
monitoring.
   ``An investigation is under way,'' Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard
told reporters. ``It is a serious investigation.''
   Souther enlisted in the Navy in January 1976, then left active
duty in 1982 after being denied entrance into officer candidate
school, according to Navy sources.
   While on active duty, he served aboard the aircraft carrier USS
Nimitz from July 1976 to November 1978, and was assigned to the 6th
Fleet command in Naples, Italy, in April 1979, where Navy sources
said he would have had access to some intelligence data involving
Soviet military activities in Europe.
   Following an honorable discharge in October 1982, Souther
remained in the reserves as an intelligence specialist.
   On weekends, he worked at the headquarters of the 2nd Fleet
command in Norfolk, Va., a position that may have given him access
to classified information, sources said.
   After leaving active service, Souther enrolled in Old Dominion
University, in Norfolk, where he majored in Russian language.
   Soviet reports of the defection did not indicate when Souther
had arrived in the Soviet Union, whether he had spied for the
Soviet Union before he left the United States, or whether he was
cooperating presently with Soviet intelligence.
   During his appearance on Soviet television, Souther said he
found himself ``confronted with a fateful decision. I had to leave
my country, my family, close friends and relatives.
   ``My guilt is that I regarded my convictions and interests as my
natural rights. But the FBI thought otherwise. I was persecuted and
my freedom was threatened,'' he said.
   An announcer on the main Soviet television news evening program
``Vremya'' said a special broadcast would be made Wednesday night
to better acquaint viewers with Souther's case.
   In November 1986, William Webster, then director of the FBI,
told reporters that Souther was the target of an espionage
investigation.
   FBI officials said Sunday that Souther had been under
surveillance before his disappearance in May 1986, but declined to
give further details of the case.
   Souther disappeared after visiting his mother in the Midwest,
and telling friends that he was going to visit a child he had by
his former wife, an Italian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     07-20 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge Frustrated With Attorneys' Disputes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: PMs top planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal judge handling the Iran-Contra
case is expressing frustration at having to mediate frequent
pre-trial disputes between lawyers for the government and the
defense.
   ``Why is it that the most simple things can't be talked out
among counsel?'' Judge Gerhard A. Gesell asked at a hearing Tuesday
on several motions. ``Why does it have to come to me?
   ``We've got to some way act like human beings to get this case
started.''
   Gesell complained of receiving a number of motions from both
sides seeking information from one another, routine matters on
which attorneys normally reach agreement during conferences.
   ``I hope to some extent you will work these things out,'' he
said.
   In one instance, Barry Simon, an attorney for retired Marine Lt.
Col Oliver North, sought documents prepared by the Israeli
government and given to the independent counsel's office. At the
hearing, prosecutors agreed to provide the defense with classified
documents setting out a chonology of events involving Israeli
officials and citizens in the secret sale of arms to Iran.
   That was when Gesell asked why such matters couldn't be worked
out without his involvement.
   Gesell also was taken aback when Simon announced that he planned
to seek a delay in the start of North's trial, scheduled to begin
Sept. 20.
   ``When are you going to file that motion?'' he asked.
   Simon promised to file the motion today, adding that it would
contain his reasons for seeking the delay.
   ``And I suppose you will want to file a reply,'' Gesell then
said to independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, who answered in the
affirmative.
   The judge scheduled a hearing for next Wednesday on the proposed
delay in the start of North's trial.
   Gesell also made a preliminary decision to have another judge
handle the trial of another of the four defendants in the case,
former national security adviser John Poindexter, to protect his
right to a speedy trial.
   With all four defendants to be tried separately, Walsh earlier
had announced his intention to present the case against North
first, a strategy which could delay Poindexter's trial for months.
   Gesell said if he were convinced that a delay in North's trial
was essential, he might decide to proceed with Poindexter's trial
first rather than having another judge take that case.
   Earlier, Gesell had told Poindexter's lawyers, ``If Mr.
Poindexter wants a judge assigned to him and to go to trial right
away, I'll arrange it.''
   Despite objections from Walsh, Gesell said, ``I do feel that if
someone wants a trial I don't want to stand in their way. It's the
right of the defendant to have a speedy trial. ... I don't
understand that I have any authority to defer a trial of a man who
wants one.''
   As pre-trial jockeying continued, Richard Beckler, Poindexter's
defense attorney, said he is readying 10 to 15 different motions on
behalf of his client.
   Defense and prosecution lawyers agreed during the hearing to
work out a procedure for obtaining handwriting samples from the
defendants, a step Walsh has said is essential to his case.
   But Gesell balked at a prosecution request to have new
photographs made of North, Poindexter and the two other defendants,
Richard Secord and Albert Hakim, calling such a step ``very
unusual.''
   North and the other defendants are facing trial on a variety of
charges, including conspiracy to defraud the government by
illegally diverting the proceeds of the sale of U.S. arms to the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
</TEXT>
