<2ND_LINE>AM-Clements Hospitalized, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0900,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas' Gov. Clements Admitted To Hospital for `Slight Stroke'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with hospital listing governor in good
condition, lieutenant governor's status, other detail. CORRECTS
spelling of neurologist in penultimate graf pvs to Tindel sted
Tindall. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements was admitted to a
hospital Tuesday after suffering a mild stroke, and was described
later as wide awake and ``absolutely normal,'' his aides said.
   ``Gov. Clements has had a slight stroke that had affected his
vision,'' spokesman Reggie Bashur, said Tuesday night.
   ``His vision right now is almost all back to normal. There are
no other difficulties or symptoms,'' Bashur said.
   Clements, 71, checked in to Seton Medical Center at about 6:30
p.m., walking in on his own, said M.A. Bengston, a hospital
spokeswoman. He was accompanied by his usual Department of Public
Safety escorts.
   He was listed in good condition, she said.
   Clements, a Republican, served a term as governor from 1979 to
1983 and was elected to a second term in 1986. He is the first
Republican governor of Texas since Reconstruction.
   Bashur said the governor ate a full dinner at the hospital and
seemed in good health. ``He is walking around,'' he said. ``He's
smiling. He feels fine.''
   George Bayoud, Clements' chief of staff, said Clements told him
Tuesday afternoon and said he was not feeling well and was going to
see his doctor.
   But ``if you saw him right now ... he looks absolutely normal,''
Bayoud said Tuesday evening.
   Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby, at the Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta as a delegate, was aware of the situation but would not be
returning to Texas early because he is not needed, Bayoud said.
   Bashur said the governor was expected to remain at the hospital
for two to three days for observation.
   The only medication being administered to Clements was aspirin,
said Bashur, who talked with Seton neurologist Dr. Jerry Tindel.
   Clements' wife, Rita, also was at the hospital, the spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
