<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate Finances,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voinovich Outspending Metzenbaum in Senate Race So Far</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Howard Metzenbaum and
Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich were virtually dead even in the
past few months in fund-raising for their Senate battle in Ohio,
campaign finance reports show.
   The candidates' reports, made public this week, show that from
April 14 through June 30, Republican Voinovich raised $1.5 million
compared with $1.4 million for Metzenbaum.
   Voinovich, who is challenging Metzenbaum for the Senate, spent
$1.1 million over the 2{-month period compared, while Metzenbaum
spent $455,000, according to the reports.
   Metzenbaum's campaign warchest grew to about $4.9 million, while
Voinovich's cash reserves as of June 30 were $1.3 million.
   Over the first six months of 1988, Voinovich led Metzenbaum in
both contributions and expenditures. Voinovich raised $2.9 million
and spent $2.3 million, while Metzenbaum raised $2.1 million and
spent $1.3 million.
   Voinovich also led Metzenbaum in contributions from political
action and other political participation committees.
   Voinovich received $348,402 from the PACs in the latest
reporting period, pushing his 1988 PAC total to $667,102.
Metzenbaum received $205,440, for a 1988 total of $246,541.
