<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nicaragua-Claim     07-20 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Claim,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Court Rejects Nicaraguan Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist government of Nicaragua has no right
to claim almost $900,000 held in the United States for a Nicaraguan
steel company that was confiscated by the government, a federal
appeals court ruled Tuesday.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit said the money
should be distributed to the company's original shareholders,
principally a family that fled Nicaragua in 1979 when the
Sandinistas were overthrowing the Somoza government.
   The court rejected Nicaragua's contention that the disputed
money should be turned over to the present government there.
   The unanimous decision by the three-judge panel was written by
Judge Irving R. Kaufman, who emphasized that Nicaragua had seized
the company without compensating the original owners.
   Nicaragua is considering whether to appeal to the U.S. Supreme
Court, said Michael Krinsky, a lawyer representing the Nicaraguan
government's representatives here.
   In the ruling, Kaufman noted that Industria Nacional de Clavos y
Alambres de Puas, which produced and distributed steel products,
was founded by Salvador Bandes. The Bandes family, ``along with
numerous other associates of the tottering Somoza regime,'' fled
the country in June 1979, the ruling said.
   Shortly thereafter, the new Sandinista government took over the
company. The Bandes family sought a refund of $420,000 that the
steel concern had paid to a Connecticut company for a shipment that
was never completed.
   Harlow & Jones Inc., the U.S. company, agreed to send the refund
to the Bandes family. But the Nicaraguan government intervened on
the grounds that it now operated the company and should get the
refund instead.
   With interest, the disputed amount now totals nearly $900,000.
   Tuesday's decision affirmed a ruling early this year by U.S.
District Judge Richard Owen that the money should be distributed to
the shareholders who owned the company before it was confiscated.
Two former generals of the Somoza regime are among the other
shareholders.
   Kaufman said the ``act of state doctrine,'' which usually bars
U.S. courts from questioning the validity of acts carried out by a
foreign government in its own territory, does not apply to property
held in the United States.
</TEXT>
