<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     07-20 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Ballet of Canada Dances Deep `Onegin'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cast of the National Ballet of Canada's
``Onegin'' _ with Natalia Makarova as guest artist _ danced with
breathtaking technique and plumbed the depths of the characters and
story on Tuesday night.
   It was the second program of the company's week at the
Metropolitan Opera.
   John Cranko choreographed ``Onegin,'' using the Pushkin story
and Tchaikovsky music, in rich and varied ballet language for his
company, the Stuttgart Ballet, in 1965. This company first produced
it in 1984.
   The Canadian dancers treat it the way fine classical actors
treat Shakespeare, searching to portray more and deeper humanity.
   Miss Makarova can scarcely be overpraised. Her Tatiana felt
everything deeply. She is tremulous when she meets the poet Eugene
Onegin. She blossoms when he dances with her. Later they do a
passionate, chaste, romantic duet in her imagination. She is
crushed when, in reality, he rejects her love letter.
   Miss Makarova rose to still greater heights in the last act,
dancing in understanding and affection with her elderly husband
(Serge Lavoie) then dancing with Onegin again. That dance begins
stiffly because of their memories, then they thrill to be together
again. When Tatiana rejects Onegin at the end of it, Miss Makarova
makes it understood that she hasn't been leading Onegin on, for
revenge. She stands, finally, in love, despair and fortitude at
doing the right thing.
   Ivan Liska was a handsome Onegin, a fascinating man of the world
bored by simple country folk, sometimes capable of feeling. Jeremy
Ransom danced Lensky, the friend Onegin kills in a duel. Ransom has
strong stage presence, at times looking like Rudolf Nureyev.
   Cynthia Lucas also made her dancing and portrayal crystal clear.
As Tatiana's sister Olga, she was in love with Lensky but found it
great fun to dance with the tall stranger, Onegin.
   The corps de ballet was admirable, in the rural ball and later
in the ball at St. Petersburg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
