<HEAD>Butkus Tackles `NFL Today' As Snyder Replacement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Chicago Bears star Dick Butkus will
attempt to tackle Jimmy ``The Greek'' Snyder's old job on CBS'
``NFL Today'' show, the network announced.
   Butkus, 45, will be joined in the studio by ``NFL Today''
veterans Brent Musburger, Irv Cross and Will McDonough, the network
announced Tuesday.
   Snyder was dismissed in January after making controversial
remarks about black athletes during a television interview.
   Butkus, who played nine seasons with the Bears, retired from
football in 1973 because of a severe knee injury. He was inducted
into the pro football Hall of Fame in 1979.
   Three other former NFL players _ Jack Youngblood, Gary Fencik
and Lyle Alzado _ auditioned for the television job, according to
CBS.
   After leaving football, Butkus became an actor. He appeared in
the television series ``Blue Thunder'' and otehr television shows,
movies and commercials, including a long-running series for a beer
company.
   For the past four years, Butkus has been a commentator on Bears
games for a Chicago radio station. Last season, he was also a guest
analyst on one of ESPN's prime-time NFL telecasts.
   Snyder, who had worked on ``NFL Today'' for 12 years, was fired
after saying blacks were bred to be better athletes and were taking
over the profession. He later apologized for the remarks, which
triggered a storm of protest after they aired on a Washington
television station.
