<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN-SealedConvention 3rdLd-Writethru a04lionprovisionforhealthcarebenefitsforretiredemployees
07-20 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Sealed Convention, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0412,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seal Omni Before Jackson Speech</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf bgng ``Among those'' with Nunn's aides saying
he had not intended to return to hall.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police sealed all entrances to the Democratic
National Convention shortly before the long-awaited speech by Jesse
Jackson on Tuesday night, blaming overcrowding in the arena.
   Tempers flared as a crowd of about 1,000 delegates, guests and
reporters pressed against police lines trying in vain to enter The
Omni.
   ``This is unbelievable,'' said Stanley Watkins, a Jackson
delegate from Chicago and an at-large member of the Democratic
National Committee. ``They should have known this was going to
happen. I think they should have had it in a bigger hall.''
   Among those in the crowd outside the arena was Sen. Sam Nunn of
Georgia, who had addressed the convention a short time earlier.
Asked whether he was upset at apparently being excluded from the
hall, he replied, ``I won't comment.'' But aides said later Nunn
had intended all along to return to his hotel after his speech.
   At first, police ordered everyone outside the convention hall to
head across the street to the World Congress Center, where the
proceedings were being televised on a large screen in an auditorium.
   No one moved.
   About a half-hour later, the hall was opened briefly, and about
35 delegates were allowed in. But other delegates were still
waiting outside when the hall was closed again.
   The Omni is a basketball arena normally seating 16,237 people,
but that capacity was cut to about 11,000 when the hall was
remodeled to accommodate the convention.
   A city ordinance says people can be prevented from entering a
building once it has reached ``standing room only,'' said Benjamin
Sims, a spokesman for the Atlanta Department of Public Safety.
   More than 5,300 delegates and alternates were to attend the
convention. Other seats in the hall were filled by guests and
reporters.
   The guests and reporters were much on the mind of Richard Koster
of Panama, co-chairman of the tiny delegation representing
Democrats Abroad who was among those stuck outside the hall.
   ``You guys we need, but you're not crucial,'' Koster said to a
reporter. ``Fat cats are great, but they're not crucial.''
   Many delegates were sent from gate to gate, each time being told
they could get in through the next gate. Some formed a human log
jam in front of the police line. Others elbowed their way through
the crowd, yelling ``delegate, delegate'' as they made their way
toward the police line. There were shouts of ``Let me in'' and
``This is America buddy.''
   Marie Jackson held a guest pass from the Louisiana delegation
and waved it in the air. ``I think this is ridiculous. We don't
want these things for souvenirs,'' she said. ``If I don't get to
hear Jesse it's going to turn me off from this election.''
   ``It's really a heartbreak when you drive 487 miles and you
can't get in,'' said Huiet Joseph, her grandson, who had a
messenger pass from the Louisiana delegation.
   By the time Jackson's speech was under way, the crowd had
dwindled to a few hundred.
   Jim McDonald of the convention security staff said access to The
Omni was halted at 10 p.m. when officials with the Atlanta Fire
Department determined it was filled beyond safe capacity.
   ``It was overcrowded,'' McDonald said. ``I'm not going to get
into numbers. But it's already over the number they originally gave
us. It's enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Whistle-Blower     07-20 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whistle-Blower,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Ordered To Reinstate Fired GSA Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal employee who was fired after
he warned that major government buildings had deteriorated into
hazardous condition has been ordered reinstated with back pay and
legal fees.
   The Merit Systems Protection Board ordered that Bertrand G.
Berube, who lost his job five years ago, be returned to his post at
the General Services Administration, the government's housekeeping
agency.
   ``I'm really pleased at the way it came out,'' Berube said
Tuesday. ``I feel fully vindicated after five years. ... I'm all
ready to go back to work.''
   The award of back pay and legal fees could total as much as
$750,000.
   ``If indeed it goes into effect, it will be the largest award of
this type in the history of the civil service,'' said Louis Clark,
one of Berube's attorneys and director of the Government
Accountability Project, a non-profit group that seeks to assist
whistle-blowers.
   Clark said he hopes the Berube case will have broad
implications. ``I hope it sends a signal to agencies that the Merit
Systems Protection Board is not going to rubber stamp their
terminations of people like Bert Berube,'' he said.
   He added that in view of the large amount of publicity generated
by the Berube case, ``I believe this result will encourage other
whistle-blowers to fight on against their agency despite the
immense odds they may face.''
   At the time of his firing in 1983, Berube was regional
administrator of the GSA's national capital region, overseeing
7,000 people and a budget of $2 billion. He was in charge of
maintaining virtually every government building in Washington, from
the White House to the Pentagon.
   Then-GSA Administrator Gerald P. Carmen dismissed Berube after
he alleged that many federal buildings in Washington posed serious
fire and health hazards. Berube said GSA officials were routinely
deferring needed building repairs so they could claim budget
savings.
   The board's ruling calling for Berube's reinstatement can be
appealed to the courts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0035 </DOCNO>
