<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--JacksonScene     07-20 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Jackson Scene,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>An Emotional Night For Jackson Supporters: `He Taught Me a Lesson'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Leonard Tate, a two-time Jesse Jackson
delegate who paraded about the convention floor with his
candidate's photo, placard, and cap, the moment he awaited so long
for took him by surprise.
   He expected fire from Jackson; he saw warmth. He expected anger;
he heard peace.
   And when Jackson finished his Tuesday night address to the
Democratic National Convention, Tate said he learned something new.
   ``He taught me a lesson. I hadn't gotten over my bitterness
(over the vice presidential selection), and I was going to write in
Jesse's name in November,'' Tate said. ``He showed us you've got to
rise above pettiness and revenge and keep your eye on the prize.''
   The speech Jackson delegates had so eagerly awaited turned into
an emotional Sunday sermon for many of them. It began with a flurry
of confetti and ended with a few tears. There were the usual
outbursts that turned the Omni into a sign-waving swirl of red, but
also some personal moments.
   ``It had a lot of heart, a lot of emotion,'' said Bill Gibson of
Greenville, S.C., a delegate and hometown friend of Jackson. ``As a
civil rights activist myself, I see this as a beginning.''
   Jackson retraced the history of the civil rights movement,
repeated some regular campaign themes, talked about his own
background and aspirations and urged his supporters to join with
the majority Dukakis delegates.
   ``The only time we win is when we come together,'' he said.
   Although there was no specific endorsement of the Massachusetts
governor, whose supporters had been instructed to keep their signs
down and let the Jackson followers have center stage, the Jackson
delegates said they got the message.
   ``He kept it upbeat and I think most of the delegates at this
point are ready to pull together. They have got the word from
Jesse,'' said supporter Marva Smalls from South Carolina.
   ``It was very moving. I had to hold back the tears at the end,''
she said.
   ``The man is on target. Nobody can do it better,'' said state
Rep. Al Edwards of Texas.
   Ray Moore, a paper mill worker from Green Bay, Wis., who has
been on strike for 14 months, had tears in his eyes most of the
speech and chanted ``Keep the hope alive'' during the pauses.
   Moore said Jackson's message to his supporters was to ``keep
working as hard as ever'' for Dukakis' election in November.
   ``There's no choice, we've got to,'' Moore said. ``This is the
only ship we have and we have to sail that ship.''
   And for those who hadn't been followers of Jackson, the speech
brought a new understanding to the question, ``What does Jesse
want?''
   ``Jesse Jackson explained to everybody why he runs,'' said Tom
Cain, a white Dukakis delegate from Atlanta.
   ``He runs because of what he once was, not in a negative way but
in a positive way. He wants to be at the table of decisions and
power, for himself and for others,'' he said.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., called Jackson's speech a
``tremendous appeal for unity.''
   And Monique Davis, a black member of the Illinois legislature
from Chicago and Jackson delegate, said she had seen Jackson mature.
   ``Jesse recognizes that America has not learned yet the value of
making a quilt. He let us know that until we do that, we'll
continue to have foreclosed farms and a working underclass. He
turned the country inside out and it saw the ugly insides of its
stomach,'' she said.
   ``I'm so proud of him. I've seen him grow without bitterness
into a statesman that America should be proud of.''
</TEXT>
