<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Atlanta'sCoping     07-20 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Atlanta's Coping,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Primping And Prepping, There's Even Concern Over Too Much
Concern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city that says it's ``too busy to hate,''
hates to think people won't like it this week.
   As Atlanta prepared to host the Democratic National Convention,
residents and civic leaders worried about everything from courteous
cabbies to crime to cleanliness. They put up a new park, posted
police on convention-area corners, and even sent cabbies to charm
school.
   Now, at the midpoint of the convention, there's even concern
over too much concern.
   ``We sure will be glad when it's over,'' downtown hotel worker
Michael Johnson said Tuesday as he waited to catch a subway train.
   Michael Lomax, chairman of the Fulton County Commission,
suggested to residents in a newspaper column that ``obsessive
boosterism'' was damaging, and they ``just lighten up and enjoy the
show.''
   ``If there's a tendency to savage Atlanta in print, we certainly
contribute to it by being self-conscious about our appearance, so
preoccupied with making things picture-perfect,'' Lomax said.
   The Atlanta Constitution has been publishing excerpts of other
newspapers' comments on the city (``Downtown Atlanta ... is a
dreadful place'' _ the New York Daily News; ``... Cocky and gawky,
wallowing in self-love and self-doubt...'' _ The Chicago Tribune).
   But at the subway stops and on the street corners, residents
recite the refrain that it's worth it to put up late buses,
gridlock traffic and even bad reviews because the attention
garnered during the four-day affair will boost the city.
   ``I think it's great,'' said Robert Alpert, a downtown
chiropractor. ``The city did a lot of quick repair before the
convention got here, and it's paying off.''
   Still, they worry that something will go wrong while the
Democrats are in town _ something that could smudge the carefully
crafted image Atlanta is trying to project with all the primping
and prepping.
   ``It brought more money to Atlanta. More people are employed
now, even if it is just for a week,'' said Patricia Rush, who's
picked up a part-time security job at the convention site. ``It's
been good, and I think everything will work out all right.''
   Like so many, Ms. Rush is happy to have the convention here, and
a little sad, too.
   ``It's been nothing but hectic this week. The bus service is
slow because all the buses are taking delegates around. They've
blocked off some streets, and it's just a mess,'' she said.
   Johnson, too, is picking up extra money working long hours at
the Ritz-Carlton Hotel.
   ``In a sense it has brought a smile to the city, and also
frowns,'' said Johnson. ``When you disturb one's bed, you don't
rest.''
   And as far as the extra money he's making, ``I'm too tired to
enjoy it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Taiwan     07-20 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Cabinet Has Younger Officials, More Native Taiwanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui announced a major
Cabinet reshuffle today, promoting younger officials and native
Taiwanese less than two weeks after he was acclaimed chairman of
the ruling Nationalist Party.
   Lee brought eight new officials into the 25-member Cabinet and
transferred seven members to new posts. He kept Premier Yu Kuo-hwa,
the government's leading conservative.
   The Nationalist Party said in a press release that its
policy-making Central Standing Committee approved the appointments
today. Officials said the new appointees would take office Monday.
   A major Cabinet overhaul was expected after the 13th congress of
the Nationalist Party ended last week. Party personnel changes
showed power shifting from conservatives of the Chiang Kai-shek era
to a younger generation largely comprised of native Taiwanese.
   The Nationalists led by Chiang set up their authoritarian
government in Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to Communist
forces on the Chinese mainland.
   Lee, a 65-year-old native Taiwanese, promised to continue
democratic reform and other liberalization begun in recent years by
his predecessor, Chiang Ching-kuo, the eldest son of Chiang
Kai-shek. Chiang Ching-kuo died in January of heart failure.
   The new Cabinet indicates Lee will continue to move gradually.
   Native Taiwanese hold 11 seats in the new Cabinet, including the
important posts of foreign minister and finance minister, which
always have been held by mainland Chinese.
   This represents an increase of three seats held by native
Taiwanese, who comprise 85 percent of Taiwan's population of nearly
20 million.
   Many new Cabinet members are viewed as technocrats, including
several groomed by Yu and other party conservatives. But observers
believe the new lineup should speed up liberalization of the
state-dominated economic system.
   ``Premier Yu has been under tremendous pressure to reform,''
said Lin An-lo, chief economist at the Chunghwa Institute for
Economic Research. ``We hope he can do better with the cooperation
of the younger Cabinet members.''
   Lee has led calls for reform of the economic and financial
system, but economists say the Nationalist government has moved
slowly to avoid irritating powerful vested interests.
   The Nationalist Party controls Taiwan's banks and many other
large enterprises. Conservative party members generally oppose the
privatization of banks and other businesses and the reform of
taxation, steps that many people say are necessary to bring the
island into the modern global economy.
   Vice Premier Lien Chan, 52, will be the new foreign minister.
   Frederick Chien, 54, Taiwan's representative to Washington, will
replace 73-year-old Chao Yao-tung as head of the Council for
Economic Planning and Development. The announcement did not name a
new representative in Washington. Chen Li-an, 51, chairman of the
National Science Council, will replace 69-year-old Lee Ta-hai as
economic affairs minister.
   Both Lee and Chao would retire.
   Shirley Kuo, 58, deputy governor of the Central Bank, will head
the Finance Ministry, replacing Robert Chien, 59, named the
Cabinet's secretary general.
   The youngest Cabinet member will be Ma Ying-jeou, 38, a party
deputy secretary general, appointed to head the Research,
Development and Evaluation Commission.
   Lee also named a scientist, an agricultural expert and an
education administrator to replace three aging officials as
ministers without portfolio.
   Yu formally proposed the new Cabinet, and Lee submitted it to
the party Central Standing Committee after discussions with Yu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--RepublicanSideshow     07-20 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Republican Sideshow,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tacky Times For GOP in Town Geared for Demos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Republicans, getting a message out can be
trying in a town that's geared this week for Democrats. Or at least
a little tacky around the edges.
   ``Did you just save us?'' a worried Barrie Tron asked a
repairman urgently trying to restore electricity to the
``Republican Media Center.''
   He had, and another day's ``truth squad'' session came off as
scheduled, though hardly in the lap of luxury.
   When the National Republican Congressional Committee decided to
trot in top Republicans every day to counter the overwhelming focus
being given to this week's Democratic National Convention, they
quickly learned how much space is at a premium in a town that's
jammed with 35,000 extra people.
   The daily Republican sessions are at a downtown hotel, in a room
that's yet to be finished.
   ``It's the most finished of the unfinished rooms,'' said Tron, a
GOP committee staffer. ``In this case finished means air
conditioned.''
   So each day, the assembled press corps and the day's cast of
Republican luminaries troop into a small room where exposed pipes
dominate the higher reaches. Blue curtains have been hung to
partially cover bare concrete walls and windows that have paper
taped over them.
   When the power failed Tuesday, plunging the room into
semi-darkness, Tron was philosophical. ``We're mood lighting this
one,'' he said as he called for help.
   ``It's the first time I've ever seen a boiler room operation in
a boiler room,'' said one of the participants.
   Still, Tron said, there's room for everybody, and the blue
curtains make a nice backdrop for the television cameras showing up
every day.
   ``Actually, it's a pretty good room,'' he said.
   The daily GOP gathering is hardly the top news of the day, but
it's attracting increased attention, particularly as disputes among
the Democrats are resolved.
   Monday's meeting prompted Mike McCurry, a spokesman for the
Democratic National Committee, to compare the GOP gathering to ants
which inevitably show up at a picnic.
   Rich Galen, a GOP spokesman, quickly got into the swing of
things by firing off a letter to McCurry, accompanied by a
miniature ant farm.
   ``I know when you referred to us as ants, you were complimenting
us on our industriousness,'' Galen wrote. The ant farm was, he
said, ``a token of our appreciation.''
   The Republicans also just happened to land in the hotel where
Jesse Jackson is staying, and that has provided a few interesting
moments.
   During Monday's session thousands of Jackson backers chanted
``Run Jesse Run'' as former White House political strategist Ed
Rollins discussed the impact of the unity agreement between Jackson
and Michael Dukakis, the certain Democratic nominee.
   ``We're just here to give you folks the contrast you need,''
said New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, one of the designated critics
on Tuesday. ``We are here to provide an opportunity for comparison
shopping.''
   ``It's not an effort to be negative, it's an effort to be
comparative,'' Galen said.
   Galen dismissed suggestions that Republicans were trying to rain
on the Democrats' parade, and said he assumed they will dispatch a
similar force to next month's Republican National Convention in New
Orleans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
