<DOCNO> AP880720-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--SatelliteCity     07-20 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Satellite City,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Tech Satellite Encampment Nestled Between The Sewers And The
Dumpsters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Emeric in 3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the satellite trucks in America
are here for the Democratic convention, beaming nearly non-stop to
places like Japan and White River Junction, Vt., from their parking
spots next to a highway embankment.
   The people who run them are figurative light years away from the
rhetoric, klieg lights and air conditioning of the convention.
   They don't have a bathroom, either.
   ``We're on the other side of the tracks,'' said Emeric Feldman,
an engineer for WCVB in Boston. ``There're 40 trucks and 100 guys
out here and we can't get a port-o-john. There's no water, no
food.''
   He joked: ``We've threatened to boycott, shut the whole thing
down.''
   The 43 trucks lined up on a desolate street at the raw rear
entrance of the Georgia World Congress Center make up the largest
collection of dishes ever assembled in one place. A dozen more are
parked elsewhere in the city.
   Their presence is a boon for the Democrats, providing exposure
far beyond the couple of hours of convention coverage shown nightly
on the networks.
   The trucks and dishes enable local stations to showcase their
own people and generate as much material as their audience will
bear. The party has thoughtfully provided stand-up space for local
reporters inside The Omni convention hall.
   There were only a few satellite trucks at the 1984 conventions.
``They all laughed,'' Feldman recalled. ``They said it would never
work.''
   The satellite park just a few blocks away from the convention
glitz, at once awesome and grim, proves the skeptics definitively
wrong.
   Its three block-long rows of high-tech dish trucks _ Spacelink
and Skylink, Newstar and Livestar, a couple of U-Hauls and Budget
Rent-a-Trucks _ are spectacular in their number if not their
setting.
   ``We've got the sewers on one side and the Dumpsters on the
other,'' said Daryl Hunter, an engineer sent by GTE Spacelink Corp.
to check and repair equipment at this convention within a
convention.
   Along with their space and sky references, the trucks announce
their origins _ New York and Boston, Milwaukee and Winston-Salem,
Kansas City and Little Rock, Washington and Tampa, Springfield and
New Orleans, South Bend and Scranton. And, no kidding, White River
Junction, Vt.
   ``We're still kind of astonished'' to be here, said Keith
Bergstrom, director of satellite operations for WNNE in White River
Junction. ``We're a very small station. We operate out of the
basement of a motel.''
   Feldman, of WCVB in Boston, said his station sent 19 people and,
by network standards, is saturating viewers with convention news _
a half-hour at noon, live updates throughout the afternoon, 90
minutes at 7:30 p.m. in addition to heavy coverage on the 6 p.m.
and 11 p.m. local newscasts. The dish is shared with other stations
including one in Japan, he said.
   With home viewers the key to this year's convention, described
by the party chairman as a four-part mini-series with a live studio
audience, you might expect royal treatment for the dish operators.
But their most elegant amenity so far is an occasional visit by a
canteen truck.
   The work is hot _ especially when a dish goes awry and must be
fiddled with atop the truck. ``I've gone through all my changes of
clothing. I change twice a day and take showers three times a
day,'' said Hunter.
   ``I don't have time to go take showers. Last week I worked 96
hours and this week it'll probably be more,'' said Feldman. ``But
I'm having a ball.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0043 </DOCNO>
