<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the speech delivered by
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts to the Democratic National
Convention on Tuesday.
   Thank you, John for that moving introduction, and for the joy
you have given our family over the years. Tonight, you have given
something special to this convention and this country. You have
touched deep chords of memory and hope in Democrats and Americans
everywhere. You remind us that we are at our best when we have a
president who asks each of us what we can do for our country.
   For a long time, I have believed that what this country needs is
another president from Massachusetts. And now it's going to happen.
   President Dukakis _ it has a nice ring, doesn't it.
   Some people say _ don't count your chickens before they're
hatched. Well, the Republicans have already hatched their chicken
in this campaign _ and George Bush is a dead duck.
   And that doesn't even count all the other chickens they've
hatched in the past eight years that are coming home to roost on
election day this November.
   We know who and what we are running against. We know them by
their names and by their deeds. They are the party of Ed Meese and
Robert Bork. They are the party of Irangate, Contra-gate,
Pentagon-gate. They are the party that tolerates apartheid abroad
and retreats from civil rights here at home.
   They are the party that talks tough on drugs but deals softly
with drug-running dictators. We have heard the slogan _ ``Just say
no.'' The problem is _ our Republican opponents just couldn't say
``no'' to General Noriega.
</TEXT>
