<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Kennedy Text, 4th add,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: America's leadership.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Our people know the difference between right and wrong. We all
see the faces pressed against the windows of our affluence. And we
wonder now whether our children will be consigned to a lesser life
in a lesser land.
   We cannot be satisfied to see American students rank l5th among
the industrial nations in science and math.
   We must strengthen education _ not attack it.
   We must abolish illiteracy, not abide it.
   We must invest in Star Schools here on earth, not Star Wars in
the heavens.
   And we must heed the message of Jesse Jackson. We must banish
drugs from our classrooms, from our playgrounds, from the streets
of our cities, and from everywhere in our nation.
   We must make America once again the best educated society in the
world. We must see to it that in the 1990s, young Americans won't
just go to school _ they will learn in school.
   At the same time, we must respond to the human realities of a
day as distant from the New Deal as that era was from the age of
the horse and buggy. Today, when more than 50 percent of mothers
work, including half of those with children under the age of one,
it is a national disgrace that we have failed to secure basic child
care for working parents. No mother who wants to work, or has to
work, should have to fear for the health or safety of her child
when she is on the job.
   Nor shall we ever consent to the permanent division of our
nation into three societies _ one doing well, a second barely
holding on, the third trapped decade after decade in hopelessness,
anger and violence.
   All this _ and more _ will be decided at the desk of the next
president. A world transformed takes many different forms. There
are dangers and other challenges. But there is one of which I
finally speak _ and which must be one of the first priorities of
the next administration.
   All my public life, I have fought my heart out for the principle
that the state of a family's health should never be determined by
the size of a family's wealth. And I stand here this evening and
tell you that at long last, victory is within our grasp.
   The first critical step has already been taken this year in
Massachusetts. Governor Dukakis passed comprehensive,
cost-effective access to medical care for every citizen of our
state.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
