<HEAD>Few Notes of `Dixie' Greet Delegates Before Music Is Shut Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of the Democratic National
Convention went quickly into action when delegates entering The
Omni arena were greeted by strains of ``Dixie.''
   ``I gotta go,'' Don Fowler, chief executive officer of the
convention, told party chairman Paul Kirk when the taped music
started playing Tuesday. After unsuccessfully trying to signal the
sound technician about 80 feet away, Fowler picked up an in-house
telephone and called him.
   The song is considered offensive by some people who believe it
represents the racism of the Old South.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Wrong Fight Song Greets Michigan Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard was the victim of a
musical faux pas when he prepared to address Democratic National
Convention delegates about the party's campaign platform.
   While Blanchard was being introduced Tuesday, the convention
band swung into a loudly enthusiastic rendition of ``The Victors,''
the famed University of Michigan fight song.
   Blanchard didn't wince, but there was a slightly pained
expression on his face. Blanchard is a devoted fan of archrival
Michigan State University.
