<HEAD>Jerry Brown Hints At Future Bid For Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former California Gov. Jerry Brown says he may
run for the U.S. Senate in 1992, but the former presidential
aspirant is currently helping his sister run for California state
treasurer.
   Brown, 50, said Tuesday that ``it's possible'' he might run for
the Senate if Democrat Alan Cranston retires, but he has no
specific plans. Asked if he might run for governor again, he
replied: ``You shouldn't un-expect it.''
   Brown made a brief appearance before the California delegation
to the Democratic National Convention to help launch the 1990
campaign for state treasurer of his sister, Kathleen.
