<DOCNO> AP880720-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Networks     07-20 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Networks,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Extends Prime Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It went an hour beyond the end of prime time, but
there was no way the networks were going to cut away once the
show's star, Jesse Jackson, took center stage on the second night
of the Democrats' made-for-TV convention.
   Jackson didn't even get to the podium until 10:55, but the
networks stayed with him until well after his 50-minute speech
brought down the house. Prime time this time went well beyond its
normal 11 p.m. EDT closeoff.
   Jackson's stemwinder followed another enormously telegenic event
_ the first major public appearance of John F. Kennedy Jr., who
introduced a speech by his uncle, Sen. Edward Kennedy. The elder
Kennedy's address would have been the evening's highlight itself if
not for Jackson's long-awaited outpouring of emotion later in the
evening.
   ABC had the foresight to have on hand those famous photos of
``John-John'' crawling under his father's desk in the Oval Office,
and saluting as Kennedy's funeral procession departed the church.
   NBC's Connie Chung grabbed an exclusive interview with young
Kennedy as he left the podium. He said he had been nervous, but
that it felt pretty good standing up there.
   As for Uncle Ted, there seemed to be some split opinions among
the network commentators as to his future with the Democratic
Party. CBS' Walter Cronkite suggested that he should not be counted
out of the running for a future nomination. ABC's Sam Donaldson had
the opposite view.
   ``I don't think he's ever going to be president _ because of you
know what,'' he told Peter Jennings, in a reference to
Chappaquiddick.
   Despite the appearance by the Kennedy clan, the networks were
just eaten up with anticipation over the impending appearance by
Jackson, finally getting his big moment before the convention.
   ``It's Michael Dukakis' convention, but this is Jesse Jackson's
night to shine,'' said CBS' Dan Rather, who later touted Jackson's
appearance as something of a historical event.
   ``If you want to gather the children around the television set
or get grandmother from the other room, it's coming up in about 15
to 20 minutes,'' he offered helpfully.
   ``Better fasten your seatbelts,'' NBC's Tom Brokaw warned as
Jackson arrived on the podium.
   Jackson's speech was delayed by a series of speeches on such
weighty platform issues as national defense and taxation, speeches
the networks judged too boring for national television audiences.
   ABC carried an interview with George Bush's campaign manager
instead. NBC continued discussing whether Jackson would get into
prime time. Viewers who wanted to see lesser-known speakers talk
about the issues had to turn to C-SPAN, though CBS and CNN did
carry a portion of the speech on the economy by Rep. William Gray
III, D-Pa.
   During Jackson's lengthy address, NBC boasted some eloquent
camera work, doing slow dissolves of reaction shots, the faces
black, white, brown, young, old. NBC also had a nice cutaway to
Jackson's guest on the podium, Rosa Parks.
   There was pandemonium after the speech as network floor
reporters rushed to grab an interview. ABC's Sam Donaldson and CBS'
Ed Bradley were part of the crush of an impromptu news conference.
   Chung, NBC's podium reporter, could be seen struggling in the
background, out of microphone reach. She finally nabbed Jackson.
But shortly into their interview, he started giving
uncharacteristically curt answers. Chung seemed perplexed. Finally
the Reverend whispered over his shoulder, ``Right now they're
prayin'.'' Up on the podium, the closing prayer was under way.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Television producers complained Tuesday that the Democratic
Party was literally leaving them in the dark at times during
prime-time convention hours by dimming the lights below previously
agreed-upon levels.
   ``They're dimming them much more than they said they would,''
said pool producer Charlie Frey. ``We get into the actual show
itself and it's like a Las Vegas production.''
   Frey said light levels were set in advance. But Democratic
National Committee officials during speeches lowered the lights,
making it difficult for network cameras to get reaction shots of
delegates, he said.
   ``It's their convention and they can do what they want to do,''
Frey said. ``They control the lights, but we agreed on a level and
they're varying from it.''
   A DNC spokesman said officials familiar with the lighting
arrangements were unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Media quotes du jour:
   _``My legacy is that I was the first floor reporter to wear
running shoes. That's what I'll be remembered for.'' _ NBC anchor
Tom Brokaw, who wore them at the 1976 conventions.
   _``Everybody looks like Deborah Norville or Jessica Savitch
these days.'' _ NBC correspondent Dennis Murphy, observing local
anchorwomen.
   _``If you want it, pack it Thursday ... It won't be here Friday
morning. Here won't be here Friday morning.'' _ Sign posted in the
ABC trailers.
</TEXT>
