<DOCNO> AP880720-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Nielsens     07-20 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Nielsens,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cable Gains on Networks in Convention Ratings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CVN--Networks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It isn't just in theoretical terms that the
television networks are forfeiting coverage of the national
conventions to cable TV, at least according to A.C. Nielsen ratings
for the first night of the Democrats' 1988 meeting.
   Ratings for the three major networks' coverage has been on a
slide since 1980. Ratings for Cable News Network, though still
small, are up 25 percent in 1988 over 1984.
   C-SPAN has also become a player, although the extent of its
audience is not known because it has no advertising and is
therefore not rated.
   For Monday night's coverage, NBC had a 6.2 rating and 11 share.
It began at 8:30 p.m. EDT, a half-hour earlier than CBS and ABC.
CBS had a 5.8 and 11 share, and ABC a 5.7 and 10. All three major
networks signed off shortly after 11 p.m.
   CNN had a 2.0 rating and a 3.3 share for its gavel-to-gavel
coverage.
   For the networks, the rating is a percentage of the nation's
estimated 88.6 million households with television sets and the
share is a percentage of sets in use. For CNN, the rating is a
percentage of households in the cable markets where CNN is
available, roughly half of the total U.S. television homes.
   In 1984, the Democratic convention had a rating of 8.4 on CBS,
7.7 on ABC and 7.1 on NBC. The 1980 convention rated a 9.6 on NBC,
9.5 on CBS and 8.0 on ABC. The rating in 1984 for CNN's coverage
was a 1.6.
   The highest rated Democratic convention since the events have
been televised was the tumultuous 1968 convention in Chicago. It
had a rating of 16.1 on NBC, 14.1 on CBS and 8.5 on ABC.
   C-SPAN, which is carrying the convention sessions uninterrupted
by commentary, has a potential audience of 38 million households
and estimates its ``loyal audience'' at about 3 million viewers.
   ``Because most of our viewers are political junkies, we assume
we're having our biggest audience during convention time,'' said
C-SPAN spokeswoman Nan Gibson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0339EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-20 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workman's Failure Blamed For 1987 Amtrak Derailment In Iowa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are blaming the October
1987 derailment of an Amtrak passenger train in Iowa on a workman's
failure to restore a track switch to its proper position.
   The National Transportation Safety Board on Tuesday concluded in
its report that the accident occurred when a laborer parked
maintenance equipment on a siding and failed to reset the switch
for through-traffic use.
   Two locomotives and 11 of 14 passenger cars of Amtrak's
``California Zephyr'' collided with maintenance equipment on the
side track, injuring 15 crew members and 107 of the 230 passengers
aboard.
   The board also blamed the crane operator and a track foreman for
failing to check the switch and criticized the management of the
Burlington Northern Railroad, which owns the track, for inadequate
training of maintenance crews and not reducing the track speed in
the work area.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controllers Elect Union President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air traffic controller from New York has
been elected president of the new National Air Traffic Controllers
Association in balloting that stretched over several week.
   R. Steve Bell is the controllers' first union president since
the 1981 strike in which 11,400 controllers were fired and their
old union destroyed.
   Bell, who was hired as a controller after the 1981 strike,
received 1,948 votes compared with 1,138 for his chief rival, Fred
Gilbert of Chicago.
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association was formed last
year as a successor to the Professional Air Traffic Controllers
Association (PATCO), which went backrupt after its unsuccessful
1981 strike. The new union claims about 5,000 members, about 40
percent of those eligible to join.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Defends Pre-Publication Censorship Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. attorney representing the State
Department told a federal judge that regulations requiring
employees to submit their articles to a censor before publication
serve to safeguard foreign policy and national security interests.
   At a hearing Tuesday before U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, assistant U.S. attorney William Dempster said the State
Department's pre-publication regulations are designed to help keep
employees from violating the law or jeopardizing security.
   At issue in the case is an article written by Voice of America
employee Carolyn Weaver that is scheduled to appear in the
September-October issue of the Columbia Journalism Review.
   Ms. Weaver said in an affidavit that the article details
political abuses by the VOA, including ``the apparent illegal use
of VOA programs for covert activity.'' Her attorney, Stephen M.
Kohn, told the court that the regulation requiring her to submit
the article to a censor prior to publication ``is too broad ...
goes too far.''
   Jackson took the case under advisement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
