<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--RacialRemarks     07-20 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Racial Remarks,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Apologizes For Racial Comment On TV Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alabama legislator apologized to the state's
Democratic National Convention delegation for saying on a national
television program that he favored racially segregated schools.
   But state Sen. Earl Goodwin of Selma said Tuesday his comment
was taken out of context when it was broadcast on the
MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour.
   Elizabeth Brackett, correspondent for the public television
program, said later that Goodwin's remark was a small part of a
longer interview but that it was not presented out of context.
   In the Monday night segment featuring the Alabama convention
delegation, Goodwin was shown commenting, ``My philosophy of the
things that I think _ the separation of the races has been for the
good of the country.''
   Goodwin, a white retired businessman and longtime ally of frmer
Gov. George Wallace, said he was talking about the landmark 1954
Brown vs. Board ruling in which the U.S. Supreme Court struck down
the ``separate but equal'' doctrine in public schools.
   He said he favored segregated school systems, with improved
conditions for blacks, rather than the desegregation set into
motion by the Brown ruling.
   He said he told the television reporter that ``if that means I'm
a segregationist, then that's what I am.''
   But he said he does not favor any dismantling of desegregated
public schools now or a return to legal racial segregation. He also
said he never favored segregation of public facilities.
   ``Bus segregation and facilities, that was silly to start
with,'' he said.
   Appearing before the Alabama delegation, which is about half
black, Goodwin said his comment was not presented in context but,
``If I have offended any of my friends, I apologize.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
