<DOCNO> AP880720-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Kennedy     07-20 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Kennedy,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Makes Stinging Attack On GOP Nominee-To-Be Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy lambasted George Bush in a
convention address, citing Reagan administration troubles like the
Iran-Contra affair and leading the packed house in the chant,
``Where was George?''
   ``The vice president says he wasn't there, or can't recall, or
never heard, as the administration secretly plotted to sell arms to
Iran. So when that monumental mistake was being made, I think it is
fair to ask, `Where was George'?'' Kennedy asked Tuesday night.
   ``George Bush is the man who is never there _ and he won't be
there after the clock strikes noon on Jan. 20, 1989,'' the senator
told the Democratic National Convention.
   Kennedy listed the Iran-Contra scandal, drug trafficking in
Central America and civil rights as political baggage from the
Reagan administration that Bush, the certain GOP presidential
nominee, is trying to avoid.
   ``At least Ronald Reagan accepts the blame as well as the credit
for the policies of the last eight years. He comes without excuses
and equivocation. He stands up, looks us in the eye,'' Kennedy
said. ``But not George Bush, who on question after question keeps
burying his head in his hands and hiding from the record of the
Reagan-Bush mistakes.''
   Kennedy dismissed the GOP as ``the party of Ed Meese and Robert
Bork. They are the party of Iran-gate, Contra-gate, Pentagon-gate.
And they are the party that tolerates apartheid abroad and retreats
from civil rights at home.''
   ``After eight years of complacency and indifference, of problems
untended and pains untreated, it is time to restore purpose and
principle to America.''
   Kennedy also rekindled memories of his brother John and the
``New Frontier'' campaign of 1960.
   ``Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, like John Kennedy and Lyndon
Johnson, believe that we cannot be content with things as they are,
that there is a newer frontier to be crossed and a greater society
to be built,'' the Massachusetts senator said.
   Kennedy, who appears to have completed the transformation from
presidential heir apparent to party elder without ever achieving
his own White House ambitions, praised Dukakis, whom he supported
early in the primary campaign.
   ``I have seen the presidency up close, and I have seldom seen
anyone as matched to the demands and possibilities of that office
as Mike Dukakis,'' Kennedy said.
   The senator, a leader of the party's liberal wing, also reached
out to Jesse Jackson, calling him ``one of the most talented
individuals in this nation, one whose life and words alike give new
meaning to our oldest ideals. He stands for freedom and compassion,
and his effort makes all of us prouder than ever to be Americans.''
   The senator was introduced by his nephew, John F. Kennedy Jr.,
whose appearance Kennedy said ``touched deep chords of memory and
hope in Democrats and Americans everywhere.''
   Kennedy also referred to his own presidential bid, telling the
convention crowd: ``For a long time, I have believed that what this
country needs is another president from Massachusetts. And now it's
going to happen.''
   Kennedy, 56, who is seeking his fifth full Senate term this year
for the seat once occupied by his brother John, said the Democratic
Party may have ``lost some elections, but we never lost our soul.
And we now know that the struggle has made us stronger, that this
country is ready to move again, and we are ready to lead.''
</TEXT>
