<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-20 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Rebound, Dollar Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded sharply on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange Wednesday, and the dollar declined for the second
consecutive day against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which took the
biggest plunge of the year Tuesday, regained 404.95 points, or 1.49
percent, to close the day's trading at 27,553.98.
   The dollar, which opened at 133.05 yen and moved in a range of
132.90-133.35 yen, closed at 133.05 yen, down 0.80 yen. The dollar
was a 1.30 yen loser Tuesday.
   After opening the day at 27,330.72 points following Tuesday's
513.09-point loss, the most widely followed barometer on the stock
exchange fluctuated between 27,113.37 and 27,571.66 points.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was estimated
at 1.3 billion shares.
   Brokers said some investors took advantage of Tuesday's losses
and bought large shares, such as steels and shipbuildings, that
declined Tuesday.
   ``Despite the moderate gain, the market as a whole is still
unstable and seems to be looking for a direction,'' said a broker
at a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   Exchange dealers attributed the dollar's decline to a sharp drop
in New York overnight, when the dollar slumped 1.36 yen to 133.155
yen.
</TEXT>
