<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0512EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Armada     07-20 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Armada,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish Ambassador Lights Beacon On Armada Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chain of 461 beacons, part of a series of events
marking the 400th anniversary of the defeat of the Spanish Armada,
blazed across England early today to re-enact the warning that the
galleons were approaching.
   As then, the first fire was lit at Kynance, a headland near
Lizard village in the southwest tip of Cornwall, where local people
say the Armada was first sighted sailing up the English Channel in
1588.
   But it was a Spaniard, Ambasador Don Jose de la Bellacasa, who
lit the Kynance beacon Tuesday night.
   Using a long-handled flaming torch to fire the brazier atop an
oak pole, he parried reporters' questions about how he felt
celebrating one of his country's more spectacular reverses.
   ``It is not so clear it was a defeat,'' he said with a grin.
``You were lucky with the weather.''
   Historians have long argued over which played the greater part
in the defeat of the Armada _ Queen Elizabeth I's navy or gales
that decimated the ranks of the Spanish ships.
   The line of beacons stretched up the country as far as
Berwick-upon-Tweed about 450 miles northeast of Kynance.
   Bruno Peak, the organizer of the event called ``Fire Over
England,'' said: ``I invited the Spanish ambassador to light the
first beacon because I thought it was about time after 400 years
that we buried this old hatchet in a symbolic way.''
   The beacon lighting ceremony at Kynance and a dramatic fireworks
display there were shown live on nationwide television.
   Other celebrities lighting beacons elsewhere included Earl
Spencer, father of Princess Diana, who fired one at his stately
home of Althorp, 65 miles north of London.
   Britons staged processions, pageants and street-dancing, and
thousands donned Elizabethan dress and took up pikes and swords
after rehearsing for weeks.
   Legend has it that Elizabeth's favorite captain, Sir Francis
Drake, was so unflustered by the Armada's approach that he insisted
on finishing a game of bowls on a lawn at the southwestern port
city of Plymouth 80 miles from Kynance before sailing to battle.
   As crowds watched, a team of actors in Elizabeth costumes
enacted Drake's game at Plymouth on Tuesday.
   Tamsin Thomas, who was in charge of 10 of the 20 beacons in
Cornwall, said the Lizard villagers had been celebrating all day,
as they have done every anniversary for the past four centuries.
   Queen Elizabeth II will visit Plymouth on Thursday to join
Armada festivities.
   The Post Office issued 40 million stamps showing galleons and
cannon smoke, and a cereal company offered ``Armada Treasure
Replica Coins'' to British breakfasters.
   The replicas are copied from coins found in Armada ships wrecked
by gales as the great fleet struggled home after failing to link up
with a Spanish invasion army waiting in the Netherlands.
   The Armada's 125 ships carried 19,000 soldiers, 8,000 sailors,
2,000 galley slaves and 180 monks and friars, sent by King Philip
II of Roman Catholic Spain to overthrow England's Protestant Queen
Elizabeth I.
   James Mildren, a historian specializing in Armada lore, said of
the defeat of the Armada, ``The weather did help but the defeat was
a great victory for England because it raised the hearts of men in
dark hours.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SpaceShuttle Bjt   07-20 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50-50 Chance Discovery Will Have To Be Taken Off Launch Pad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers are trying to fix a tiny
gas leak in the space shuttle, but there's a 50-50 chance Discovery
will have to be rolled back from the launch pad to a hangar for
repairs, says Kennedy Space Center's director.
   Taking Discovery off the pad would delay the first launch since
the Challenger disaster, now scheduled for early September, by up
to two months, Forrest S. McCartney told reporters Tuesday.
   ``We wish we had found it (the leak) earlier,'' McCartney said.
``If we had found it when it was accessible, there would have been
no problem. But it's in an inaccessible place, and we don't know
what we're going to do about it.
   ``We've got people looking at the prudent and safe thing to do.
Whatever course we take there will be no compromise in flight
safety.
   ``The odds are 50-50 on a rollback,'' McCartney said.
   He said no decision was likely until after Discovery's three
main engines have been test-fired on the pad in a critical test set
for July 28. The main engines are separate from the steering engine
system, where the leak is.
   The tiny nitrogen tetroxide gas leak was detected Friday in an
engine compartment, and was traced to a fitting on a line leading
to an oxidizer tank. Nitrogen tetroxide normally combines with fuel
to power the steering engines.
   Shuttle managers were combing through documents to determine
whether workers might have missed a similar leak as early as last
January.
   Launch Director Bob Sieck said paperwork showed that a pressure
check was made on the oxidizer tank manifold in an engine
compartment before Christmas, and that a second reading taken two
weeks later showed a pressure drop.
   The pressure drop occurred in the same area as the one detected
in January.
   ``We are reviewing all procedures and documentation and
equipment associated with that event,'' Sieck said.
   The earlier readings may have been within specifications, he
said. ``And I wouldn't preclude the fact that we have other data
that says the integrity of the joint was confirmed.
   ``Until a final review is in it is pure speculation that a
requirement was violated and not reported,'' Sieck said.
   The problem with fixing the leak on the pad is that the
22-foot-tall engine compartment probably would have to be removed,
a difficult task never done there before.
   Another option would be to take Discovery to a hangar and
replace the compartment as soon as possible with one being prepared
for a November flight by Atlantis. Such a move would eliminate the
need to wait for a leak repair, and could cut the launch delay to
about a month.
   Flying with the leak is a possibility, ``but we would have to
assure ourselves that it would be absolutely safe,'' Sieck said. A
possible danger is that during the return to Earth the nitrogen
tetroxide would mix with water in the atmosphere and form corrosive
nitric acid.
   Discovery is being grooomed to make the first shuttle mission
since Challenger exploded Jan. 28, 1986, killing all seven crew
members. Five veteran shuttle astronauts are to make the four-day
flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0501EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hoover-Stanford     07-20 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hoover-Stanford,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Change at `Think Tank' That Shaped Reagan Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoover Institution Director W. Glenn
Campbell, who for nearly three decades has led the think tank that
launched many of the conservative ideas and leaders of the Reagan
presidency, says he will step down next year.
   Campbell said he hopes his move will end the academic, political
and legal dispute that has split the liberal Stanford University
campus and angered conservatives from California to Washington and
Wall Street.
   Campbell said he will remain at Hoover in an advisory role and
will hold the title of counselor, serve as member of all selection
and advisory committees, and stay in his office, formerly occupied
by founder and President Herbert Hoover.
   ``I used to be a young warrior, now I'm an aging warrior but not
yet an old warrior,'' he said in a two-hour interview Monday with
The Associated Press before presenting his proposal to Hoover's
Board of Overseers.
   Campbell, a close friend of President Reagan and a member of his
original ``kitchen cabinet,'' said the Hoover Institution on War,
Revolution and Peace will remain on the Stanford campus and keep
its financial and academic independence as a policy research center.
   Hoover has been a frequent target of criticism by Stanford
faculty and students who disapprove of its conservative political
activities and ties to the Reagan administration.
   Reagan, an honorary fellow at Hoover, charted his course as
California governor and in the White House with the help of
advisers from Hoover, including economists Martin Anderson and
Milton Friedman.
   Departing Attorney General Edwin Meese III recently accepted
Campbell's invitation to join Hoover as a visiting fellow while he
writes a book on his years with Reagan.
   Campbell, who has led Hoover since 1960, proposes to step aside
as director after he turns 65 next April, but remain in the job
until his successor takes over at the end of next summer.
   Anderson called Campbell ``the premier intellectual entrepreneur
of the century'' but said his move ``makes a lot of sense.''
Anderson will sit on a 10-person search committee for Campbell's
successor.
   James Gaither, Stanford trustee president, said he thought
Campbell made the right decision and hoped it would bring the
different sides together on campus.
   ``There have been problems in the past, obviously, but we're
committed to working together to improve relations between Stanford
and Hoover,'' Gaither said. ``I'm very happy that Dr. Campbell has
chosen to help resolve those problems.''
   Campbell's surprise announcement comes two months after he vowed
to sue Stanford if it tried to oust him at 65, five years before he
planned to leave, on the grounds it was the customary retirement
age at the university.
   Campbell, who noted several exceptions to the rule, called
Stanford's action ``an attempted takeover'' motivated by politics
and greed.
   Stanford president Donald Kennedy and former trustees' president
Warren Christopher were Carter administration officials, and the
majority of faculty are Democrats.
   Campbell, an unabashed conservative Republican, said the problem
between Hoover and Stanford is ``not as simple''' as politics alone.
   ``All these people (at Stanford) want is the money and
buildings,'' said Campbell, whose large wood-paneled office is on
the 11th floor of the landmark Hoover Tower in the center of campus.
   Gaither, Anderson and others said they believed Campbell decided
to step down as a constructive move to avoid further strains that
might hurt the images of Hoover and Stanford.
   Campbell, a Harvard economist who once had former Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Paul Volcker as a student, was selected by
former President Hoover as his successor at the institution.
   Campbell's fund-raising helped boost a $2 million endowment to
its current level of more than $110 million.
   The Hoover Institution is among the nation's premier think
tanks, a place where more than 100 scholars, policy makers and
leaders write books and articles on foreign affairs, national
security and economics.
   They meet regularly to exchange ideas, often while munching
cookies at the ritual midday coffee hour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Contra-Rift     07-20 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra-Rift,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Contra Commanders Resign To Protest Bermudez Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven commanders of the
Nicaraguan rebels' southern military front have quit in protest of
the election to the movement's political leadership of Contra
military chief Enrique Bermudez.
   The commanders, who resigned late Tuesday, lead 2,700 rebel
fighters. The rest of the Contras' estimated 12,000 guerrillas are
based in Honduras.
   Bermudez, 56, a colonel in the army of Anastasio Somoza before
the late right-wing Nicaraguan president was deposed, was elected
Monday to the seven-member directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance.
   The directorate oversees the U.S.-backed insurgency against the
leftist government of the Sandinistas, who led the revolution that
defeated Somoza in 1979. Many Contras backed the revolution but
later became disaffected with the Sandinistas.
   A communique released in San Jose Tuesday night by the seven
field commanders condemned ``the placing in charge of the highest
military post of the insurgents an ex-colonel of the hated
Somocista National Guard.''
   Dissidents have accused him of being inefficient, corrupt and
too close to Somoza supporters.
   The communique charged that Bermudez deliberately withheld U.S.
aid for southern front rebels to enhance his own power in the
movement.
   ``The Nicaraguan Resistance has not in the past, nor in the
present and nor will it in the future fulfill the yearnings and
hopes of the Nicaraguan exiles,'' the statement said.
   ``We want to emphasize that we don't question the right of all
Nicaraguans to participate in the liberation of the fatherland,''
it said.
   The resign commanders said their decision to leave the
Resistance was unanimously endorsed by the 2,700 fighters they
command, whom they claim represent 40 percent of the Contra forces.
   The communique did not say whether they would independently
continue effprts to topple Nicaragua's government.
   The statement identified the seven by their pseudonyms of Ganso,
Navegante, Pedro Rafa, Ramiro, Johnny, Ali and Omar. Commanders
Ganso, Ali, Omar and Navegante participated in high-level peace
negotiations between the Resistance and the Sandinistas held in
Managua.
   Those talks, conducted under a temporary cease-fire agreement
reached March 23, broke down June 9.
   On Tuesday, President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua announced a
unilateral extension of the cease-fire to Aug. 30.
   Bermudez was elected during a three-day meeting of the
Resistance, the Contras' umbrella organization, that ended Tuesday
in the Dominican Republic capital of Santo Domingo.
   The seven commanders said they decided not to attend the meeting
because they saw the election as a foregone conclusion.
   ``We always have suffered threats and pressures, most especially
on the part of ... Bermudez, who (with the support of) official
North American sectors notably reduced our U.S. assistance to
oblige us to submit'' to the colonel, the communique said.
   The statement said the southern front has received nothing from
a $17 million U.S. humanitarian aid package that Congress approved
in late March while ``troops in the northern front are supplied in
constant form.''
   The last deliveries in U.S. military aid were made Feb. 29.
Congress has refused to renew military aid.
   Of a total $127 million in U.S. assistance, the southern front
commanders said they received just $5.5 million.
   Bermudez's position in the Resistance was enhanced during the
Santo Domingo meeting by the re-election of his closest ally on the
directorate, Aristedes Sanchez, and of Alfredo Cesar, who spoke
strongly in favor of his candidacy.
   Newly elected director Wilfredo Montalvan also was seen as a
Bermudez supporter, but the allegiances of Roberto Ferrey and
Wycliffe Diego were less clear.
   Ferrey replaces his sister, Azucena, who decided not to seek
re-election, and Diego fills a vacant seat representing Nicaragua's
Atlantic Coast Indians and Creoles. Bermudez won a second vacant
seat.
   Adolfo Calero, 56, who as the directorate's senior member had
been regarded as its political head, also was re-elected. He is a
rival of Bermudez.
   Calero dismissed suggestions that the colonel's election would
lessen chances that Congress will resume military aid to the
Contras.
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, who was ousted from the directorate,
said he thought Bermudez was determined to take absolute control of
the Resistance.
   ``I don't think he has total control, but that his clearly his
intention,'' said Chamorro, a 36-year-old former Nicaraguan
journalist.
   In April, Calero and Chamorro sided with dissidents who tried
but failed to strip Bermudez of his military command after he fired
six commanders in Honduras for mutiny.
</TEXT>
