<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Also-Rans Bjt   07-20 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Also-Rans, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>For the Also-Rans: Brave Faces and Dashed Hopes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are here with brave faces and dashed hopes,
listening to speeches they hoped to make, watching the coronation
they fought for. They are the also-rans of 1988, and they had other
plans for this week.
   ``Obviously there are mixed feelings,'' said Sen. Paul Simon of
Illinois, who gave up his Democratic primary campaign April 7 after
washing out in Wisconsin. ``You'd like to be where Mike is.''
   Gov. Michael Dukakis is a day away from the victory speech that
will cap his long fight for the party's nomination. A year ago he
was with the rest of them: scrabbling for serious attention,
ridiculed for lacking stature.
   He gained both by outlasting his opponents, and all but one were
on hand to see him claim the spoils. They did so ungrudgingly, most
with expressions of support but with a tinge of wistfulness at what
might have been.
   ``I enjoyed it. I had a great time,'' Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee said Tuesday night, looking back on his 10-month
campaign. He called it quits on April 21, whipped in New York and
$2.1 million in debt.
   The debt's been retired and the lesson's been learned, Gore
said. If he were to do it again, and he may, ``I would start
earlier.''
   But there are pitfalls other than too little time, as the
vanquished veterans of the Democratic campaign will attest. Few
started earlier than Gary Hart, who finished second in 1984 and was
favored to win this time.
   A dalliance with a model spelled the Hart campaign's demise in
May 1987, though he tried a comeback that sputtered through Super
Tuesday before he quit, for keeps, on March 11. Hart is in Atlanta
as a newspaper columnist and a commentator for Italian television.
   No, he said this week, he's not resentful about the race. ``I'm
grateful to be alive and to be here.'' His viewpoint, while it may
reach fewer people now, is unchanged from the iconoclastic message
of his campaign. ``Everybody at the convention,'' he said, ``keeps
their sights too low.''
   A second former candidate has switched to the other side of the
notebook _ former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt, whose quick wit won
him favorable media reviews but few votes. He hung up his campaign
running shoes Feb. 18 and came to Atlanta as a newspaper and
television commentator.
   Though he was speaking of former President Carter, Babbitt's
thoughts in his column Tuesday could have been a reflection on his
own fortunes: ``I've always thought that the true test of character
is what politicians do when the lights go out and, humbled by
defeat, they make the long trip back home.''
   But there was a hint of frustration at his failed effort, too.
``Nothing happens at a convention anymore,'' he told an
interviewer. ``They don't even put our names in nomination anymore.
There is nothing but spectators.''
   Babbitt is more than a spectator, though. He is a delegate
pledged to Dukakis. Similarly, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri,
who gave up his campaign March 28, is here as a Dukakis delegate.
   Gephardt told his fellow delegates Tuesday he had been given a
fair shot at the presidency. He ran, he said, because ``I could not
bear the thought of sitting on the west side of the Capitol next
January, watching them swear in George Bush, and having to turn to
one of my colleagues and say, `Why didn't we do something about
this?'''
   Of the two other men who sought and lost the 1988 Democratic
nomination, one remained the most in the public eye, the other the
least.
   Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware quit Sept. 23 amid charges he
borrowed speeches without attribution and had been accused of
plagiarism as a college student. He was at home this week,
convalescing from surgery for an aneurysm near his brain.
   The other was Jesse Jackson, who lasted the course with Dukakis
and addressed the convention Tuesday night. Though he knew he could
not win, Jackson at least had the solace of speaking the words all
his former rivals had set as their goal.
   ``Hope is eternal,'' he said. ``Tomorrow night my name will go
into nomination for the presidency of the United States.''
</TEXT>
