<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShootingSpree     07-20 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shooting Spree,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses: Three Of Four Shooting Victims Died While Deputies
Watched</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ At least three of the four people
killed by a man with a rifle were gunned down at point-blank range
while sheriff's deputies crouched behind their cruisers some 40
yards away, witnesses said.
   ``They didn't fire at all,'' said Adrian Hodges, who watched
from a bank parking lot. ``There was two of them. I seen them
leaning against their cars with their hands across the cars. I
assume they had their guns out.''
   Forsyth County Sheriff's department officials on Tuesday
declined to discuss any details relating to the shooting, saying
that an investigation is not complete.
   After deputies arrived at the scene late Sunday night, witnesses
said they saw the gunman shoot at least three people. Witnesses
were unsure if the fourth victim was shot after deputies had
arrived.
   Five other motorists were wounded by the gunman, identified by
police as Michael Charles Hayes, 24. Hayes' family had tried to
have him committed to a mental hospital the day before the shooting.
   Hayes was in satisfactory condition today at North Carolina
Baptist Hospital, where he was being treated for gunshot wounds
suffered in a shootout with deputies. Authorities have charged him
with two counts of first-degree murder.
   Deputies blocked only northbound traffic on one street with
their parked cars, leaving open a road from the east and west and
another road southbound from Winston-Salem, Hodges and other
witnesses said. Cars continued to drive into the gunman's range
during the 12-minute rampage, they said.
   Sheriff's department officials refused to say how many deputies
were at the scene.
   Ronald Hull, one of the four killed, was eastbound with his
wife, Darlene, and son. His brother, David Hull, said the roadblock
prompted his brother to turn directly into the path of the gunman.
   ``People were shot before my brother even entered the area,''
Hull said. ``I just can't comprehend why they (the deputies) did
what they did. They put the traffic right into the middle of it.''
   Recounting his brother's final moments, he said, ``The man
jumped out in front of him and told him to stop, hollering and
waving a gun. He told him to cut his truck off and (turn) his
inside light on.
   ``Ron raised his hands off the steering wheel and said,
`Anything you say, just don't hurt my family.' And the boy busted
the window out and put the gun to his head and pulled the trigger.''
   The gunman also wounded Ronald Hull's wife.
   Hull insisted the sheriff's department should have blocked all
routes leading past Hayes' moped shop, even though it was near the
border of neighboring Davidson County.
   ``I think the sheriff's department is to blame,'' he said. ``If
they had crossed that county line and blocked (both roads), then my
brother wouldn't have been involved in it. I think they put the
roadblock in the wrong place.''
</TEXT>
