<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSEstimates     07-20 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Estimates,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Revises Number of AIDS-Infected People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A revised estimate that the AIDS virus has
infected half as many New Yorkers as thought could change national
figures, says the city's top health official, but a federal
spokesman contends it's ``too early to tell.''
   City Health Commissioner Dr. Stephen Joseph said he informed the
federal Centers for Disease Control on Tuesday about the revision
from 400,000 infected New York residents to 200,000.
   ``Since New York represents 23 percent of the AIDS cases
nationally, if they accept our methodology it will make some
changes in their estimates,'' Joseph told a news conference.
   The CDC estimates 1 million to 1.5 million Americans are
infected with the virus that causes acquired immune defiency
syndrome.
   ``It's really too early to tell if it will affect our figures,''
said CDC spokesman Charles Fallis in Atlanta. ``At this point,
we're sticking with what we originally said.''
   The new estimate does not mean there will be a change in
projections of how many AIDS cases there will be in the early
1990s, because those forecasts are based on cases of people who
actually have AIDS, Joseph said.
   New York has been using the old estimate of 400,000 for nearly
three years.
   It was based on decades-old data from research by Alfred Charles
Kinsey which estimated that one out of 10 men engaged in homosexual
behavior, and on surveys indicating there was a 50 percent AIDS
virus infection rate among homosexual men.
   The CDC bases its estimates on the same data.
   The city estimates that by 1991 there will be 43,000 AIDS
patients needing serious medical treatment in New York. That figure
was ``based on trends of past and current AIDS cases which we are
quite confident are accurate,'' Joseph said.
   The same cannot be said of the number of people infected with
the AIDS virus. That figure always has been ``just an estimate ...
and one that at times varies widely,'' Joseph said.
   The new figure is based on recent studies in San Francisco on
the number of infected homosexuals there.
   The New York figure is based on the hypothesis that the ratio of
the number of homosexual men with AIDS to the number of infected
gay men is about the same in the two cities, Joseph said.
   There are 7,499 homosexual men in New York with AIDS and 4,071
in San Francisco. Using that ratio and data that estimates there
are 27,517 infected homosexual and bisexual men in San Francisco,
officials theorize there are an estimated 50,000 infected gay men
in New York, rather than the previously estimated 200,000 to
250,000.
   The number is significant because most health officials now
agree that nearly all of those carrying the virus will get AIDS.
   Joseph said the San Francisco data were considered more valid
than old data because ``they are based on a much smaller, tighter,
more homogeneous situation'' and because San Francisco is further
ahead than anyone else in terms of blood test data.
   The number of intravenous drug users believed to be carrying the
virus is unchanged, Joseph said. About 100,000 of the approximately
200,000 intravenous drug users are estimated to be infected.
   
   Joseph also said the revision will not affect funding for AIDS
prevention or services.
   The new estimate came out just two months after the city
released a five-year master plan based on the old figure, under
which New York would spend $334 million on prevention, education
and services.
   ``It would really be a mistake for anybody or any group to take
these figures and say because of that we can do less or because of
that we can do differently,'' Joseph said. ``Those expenditures
will need to stay where they are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ValveBalloon     07-20 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Valve Balloon,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Plays Down Use of Balloons To Open Damaged Heart Valves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The following was originally embargoed for 6 p.m. EDT
Wednesday, but the embargo has been broken and it can be used now.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The use of balloons to open up damaged aortic
heart valves should be reserved for people who are too old and sick
to undergo surgery to repair the condition, according to a new
study.
   The balloon technique is used as an alternative to surgery in
people whose heart valves don't work properly.
   However, young, otherwise healthy patients with aortic valve
narrowing should have surgery to replace the valve, Dr. Peter C.
Block of Massachusetts General Hospital wrote in an editorial
accompanying a report on the study.
   The report is in the latest New England Journal of Medicine,
which comes out Thursday.
   The study, directed by Dr. Robert D. Safian of Beth Israel
Hospital in Boston, examined the balloon technique's value in
people with malfunctioning aortic valves, which allow blood to flow
into the aorta, the body's main artery.
   In about half of the 170 patients treated, the valves narrowed
up again within a year of the procedure. Six of the patients, whose
average age was 77, died in the hospital, and about three-fourths
survived at least a year.
   Block wrote that the balloon procedure may be useful for frail
and sick elderly people who have other heart problems.
   But he said elderly patients who have no other medical problems
and are strong and willing to undergo surgery should be advised to
choose surgery.
   Results have been more promising when the balloon procedure is
used to relieve narrowing of the mitral valve, which controls the
flow of blood into the left ventricle, the heart's main pumping
chamber.
   In another study reported in the journal, doctors concluded that
open-heart surgery can be effective for people in their 80s. They
reviewed the cases of 50 such people who underwent coronary bypass
or valve replacement operations.
   They calculated that 59 percent would still be alive after three
years and 54 percent after five years.
   The report, written by Dr. L. Henry Edmunds Jr. and others at
the University of Pennsylvania, concludes that surgery is ``a
reasonable therapeutic option'' in elderly people who cannot be
treated in other ways, even though death and complication rates are
high.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan     07-20 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zia Calls Elections For Nov. 16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammad Zia ul Haq today
set Nov. 16 for elections to the National Assembly and promised
free and independent balloting for a clean government.
   Zia, the army chief of staff, on May 29 fired his civilian prime
minister, Mohammad Khan Junejo, the 33-member Cabinet and the
237-member assembly, the lower but more powerful house of
Parliament.
   The president, speaking before the Senate, also called elections
for Nov. 16 for legislatures in the provinces of Punjab, Sind,
Baluchistan and Northwest Frontier.
   The announcement followed seven weeks of intense pressure by all
political parties to hold elections and let the nation return to a
democratically elected system.
   When he fired the government, Zia accused the officials of
corruption, incompetence and failure to move quickly on making
Islam the state religion and to prevent a breakdown in law and
order.
   Junejo and other politicians denied the charges. Junejo accused
Zia of ``arbitrarily dissolving the assembly and disrupting a
democratic system which was operating smoothly.''
   Some critics said the Constitution requires elections within 90
days of the dissolution of Parliament.
   But Zia said an August election was impossible because of a
religious holiday among Shiite Moslems, the monsoon season, the
absence of 80,000 to 90,000 pilgrims in Mecca and the need to
redraw districts to reflect population shifts.
   ``Elections will be free, fair and independent,'' he said. ``The
objective of the election is to establish and promote clean
politics, clean democracy and clean democratic institutions.''
   He offered an apology of sorts for his criticism of former
elected officials: ``If anyone has felt hurt by this I express my
regrets. My intention was not to hurt anyone, or assassinate
anyone's character.''
   Some opposition leaders have accused Zia supporters and former
Cabinet members with corruption since Zia seized power in a 1977
military coup.
   Zia overthrew Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, who was hanged in 1979. His
daughter, Benazir Bhutto, heads Pakistan's strongest opposition,
the Pakistan People`s Party.
</TEXT>
