<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Heat     07-20 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Heat,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Kills 71 in Shanghai</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blistering heat wave that has broiled the
Yangtze River area of China this month has killed 71 people in
Shanghai, an official Chinese report said.
   Hospitals in the Shanghai area also reported treating 353
patients, mostly the infirm and elderly, for heat stroke as of
Sunday, a China News Service article appearing in Hong Kong on
Wednesday said.
   The mercury soared to 100 degrees in Shanghai on Sunday, the
highest yet this year, but by Tuesday had cooled under the
influence of a typhoon that approached the southern China coast.
   The report warned, however, that after two or three days of
cooler weather the heat wave could return.
   The Shanghai death toll, which the news service attributed to
reports coming from two funeral homes, brings to more than 400 the
number of people who have died in the searing heat along the
Yangtze River.
   Official media has reported 290 elderly people died in the
southern city of Nanchang and 83 people died from the heat in
Nanjing, the capital of coastal Jiangsu province.
</TEXT>
