<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WildfiresRdp     07-20 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires Rdp,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Battle Blazes in Wyoming; Alaska Fires Allowed to
Burn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire crews used picks and shovels today as they tried to stop a
14,000-acre Wyoming wildfire from spreading into Yellowstone
National Park, where other fires charred nearly 13,000 acres of
backcountry.
   In Alaska, 50 fires _ one of them burning since April 16 _
covered about 450,000 acres in remote inland areas, but officials
left most of them to burn because there was no threat to lives or
property.
   Fires also burned in parts of California, Colorado, Utah and
Oregon.
   The blaze in Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National Forest wilderness
area edged to within two miles of Yellowstone.
   Crews brought industrial sprinklers and miles of plastic hose to
moisten Yellowstone Meadows, a popular recreational area on the
forest's border with the national park.
   Firefighters had little more than picks, shovels and the water
tanks they carry on their backs to fight the flames because of
wilderness area restrictions. They used natural firebreaks such as
meadows, streams and rock outcroppings to stop the fire.
   The fire ``continues to show the vulnerability and explosiveness
of the fuels,'' U.S. Forest Service spokesman Fred Kingwill said.
``It is very, very dry. It's been dry for a number of years. ...
It's a fire condition that probably very few people have seen
before.''
   The rugged territory, at an elevation of about 8,500 feet and in
prime grizzly bear habitat, has forced officials to use helicopters
to shuttle firefighters around.
   In Yellowstone, officials monitored several fires covering
12,850 acres, imposed campfire restrictions throughout the
backcountry and closed some backcountry campsites. Other campsites
and Yellowstone roads remained open.
   In northwest Colorado, all but two of 14 range and forest fires
were contained Tuesday after charring more than 20,000 acres. The
largest fire yet to be contained covered 3,130 acres near the
Dinosaur National Monument headquarters, said Mary Pressley, a U.S.
Bureau of Land Management spokeswoman.
   Northern California firefighters struggled to contain brush and
timber blazes that broke out as temperatures soared above 100
degrees.
   A 1,500-acre fire three miles south of the Calaveras County
community of West Point swept over a state pumper crew Tuesday
after they ran out of water, said California Department of Forestry
spokeswoman Karen Terrill.
   But the four firefighters survived because they took refuge in
heat-resistant shelters they carried with them, she said. None was
injured.
   Two houses, a mobile home and several outbuildings were
destroyed by a second, 2,500-acre blaze five miles to the south, a
forestry department spokesman said.
   Near San Luis Obispo, Calif., dense thickets of 100-year-old
undergrowth, sweltering temperatures and fatigue have hampered
efforts to contain a 4,200-acre wildfire in the Los Padres National
Forest.
   Firefighters had nearly contained the fire Tuesday following an
all-out air and ground assault by 1,000 firefighters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
