<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   07-20 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0573,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Kill Two Palestinians Protesting Death of Teen-ager</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with two killed, other developments. No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians attacked soldiers, stoned buses
and closed shops today to protest the unsolved killing of a
teen-ager. Israeli troops fatally shot two demonstrators and
wounded seven.
   The army said troops fatally shot one Palestinian as he tried to
throw a firebomb at a military patrol. The other died in
circumstances that were still under investigation.
   Police in Jerusalem fired rubber bullets and tear gas at
hundreds of Palestinian protesters, including children in a
schoolyard near the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, where tradition
says Jesus is buried.
   The violence was triggered by Tuesday's shooting death of
15-year-old Nidal Fuad Rabadi as he rode his bicycle near Jerusalem
city limits, and by a tour of the Temple Mount today by right-wing
Israeli legislators.
   Arab reporters and Israel Television said the boy may have been
shot by Israeli civilians who got off a bus to chase stone-throwing
youths.
   The fatalities raised to 227 the number of Palestinians killed
since the uprising began Dec. 8 against Israel's 21-year occupation
of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Four Israelis also have died.
   The army said a Palestinian identified by hospital officials as
Zaki Halaykeh, 23, was killed when he tried to throw a firebomb at
a military patrol in Shuyukh village near the West Bank city of
Hebron.
   Officals at nearby Alia Hospital said Halaykeh was shot through
the back. Three other youths in Shuyukh were wounded in a clash
with troops, the army said.
   In the northern West Bank town of Jenin, Hisham Zaid, 26, died
after being shot in the chest by troops during a stone throwing, an
official at Jenin Hospital said. Four Palestinians were wounded in
the clash, the army said.
   Violence broke out in Jerusalem shortly after three legislators
of the Tehiya Party toured the Temple Mount under heavy police
guard. The compound is sacred to both Jews and Moslems.
   Legislator Geula Cohen told reporters the tour was to coincide
with the Hebrew lunar calendar month of Av, when the ancient Jewish
temple was destroyed by the Romans about 2,000 years ago.
   In Arab east Jerusalem today, police blocked Rabadi's friends
from paying condolence calls to his family home and merchants
staged a strike, refusing to open their stores on the main Salah
Eddin shopping street.
   Palestinian shopkeeper Abed Alka said protesters in the Old City
shouted slogans such as ``Whose state is Palestine?''
   More than 50 Palestinian aged 6 to 8 fled the Al Aytem School
when soldiers fired tear gas.
   Angry protesters stoned Israeli buses, including one carrying
tourists, an Arab-owned vehicle and a police van. Israel radio said
a woman and a policeman were injured by rocks.
   An investigation into the circumstances of Rabadi's death was
delayed by a disagreement between police and army officials over
whether the shooting occurred within Jerusalem's city limits, where
Israeli law applies.
   Police officials contend the army is responsible for the West
Bank.
   Jerusalem Police Chief Yossi Yehudai told reporters today that
he had visited the site of the shooting, near the Arab neighborhood
of Beit Hanina, but found no witnesses to the attack.
   Yehudai did not rule out the possibility the killing was linked
the Palestinian uprising, but said he also believed ``this could be
a criminal case.'' He refused to elaborate.
   Also today, the head of Jerusalem's Moslem religious council,
Sheikh Salah El Din Al Alami, met diplomats from eight countries
including the United States and urged them to intervene to halt an
Israeli archaeological excavation beneath the Temple Mount compound.
   The dig to uncover an ancient tunnel touched off a violent
demonstration in the Old City two weeks ago.
   Israel's state television decided it would no longer cover
Israelis protesting military service in the occupied territories,
the Jerusalem Post reported. Since the uprising began, 29 Israelis
have served jail terms for refusing to serve in the disputed lands.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said Israel would cut services to
Palestinians in the occupied territories because of a 40 percent
decline in tax collections during the uprising, army radio reported.
</TEXT>
