<2ND_LINE>PM-Clements-Hospitalized,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov. Bill Clements To Remain In Hospital For Observation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements was in good condition
today after suffering a mild stroke, and will remain hospitalized
two to three days for observation and testing, aides said.
   ``He's walking around joking (and) says he's going to have some
ice cream,'' chief of staff George Bayoud said Tuesday night. ``The
governor is wide awake. If you saw him right now ... he looks
absolutely normal.''
   The 71-year-old Republican complained of illness before
admitting himself into Seton Medical Center around 6:30 p.m.
Tuesday. He was listed in good condition today.
   The stroke briefly blurred Clements' vision, but his vision was
normal late Tuesday night, gubenatorial spokesman Reggie Bashur
said, adding that he had spoken with neurologist Dr. Jerry Tindel.
   Clements had appeared in good spirits earlier Tuesday when he
posed for photographs with the 1987 Miss Texas.
   Bayoud said he was in his office when Clements walked in Tuesday
afternoon and said he was not feeling well and was going to see his
doctor.
   Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby, at the Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta, placed a call to Clements, but didn't talk to him, Bayoud
said, adding there was no reason for the state's second-in-command
to return to Texas early.
   The governor was expected to remain at Seton for two to three
days for observation, Bashur said. Aspirin was the only medication
being administered.
   Bayoud said that to his knowledge, Clements had not been
admitted to a hospital since hip surgery in 1983.
   Clements was first elected in 1978, becoming Texas' first
Republican governor since Reconstruction. He was ousted by Democrat
Mark White in 1982, but defeated White four years later.
</TEXT>
