<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BerettaVendetta     07-20 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beretta Vendetta,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Arms-Maker Sues U.S. Carmaker Over `Beretta' Name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beretta, the Italian arms manufacturer favored
by James Bond, is gunning for General Motors Corp., claiming in a
$250 million lawsuit that the automaker's four-wheeled Beretta is a
trademark violation.
   Fabrica D'Armi P. Beretta S.p.A., which calls itself the oldest
manufacturer of arms in the world, went after GM when the automaker
unveiled the Chevrolet Beretta in 1987, despite warning letters
from Beretta lawyers the previous year.
   The 500-year-old Italian arms-making dynasty had registered
trademarks in this country for the Beretta name as far back as 1954.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court here Tuesday, said Beretta
pistols are the standard military sidearm in several countries
including the United States, which signed an $80 million contract
for 315,000 pistols in 1985.
   It also noted that in novels, where price is no object, the
Italian-made pistols are the weapon of choice for numerous
fictional spies and detectives, including Agent 007.
   In Detroit, General Motors issued a statement saying that ``no
basis for the suit exists because there is no likelihood for
confusion as to the source of those vehicles between GM and the
Beretta gun company.''
   ``The GM employee who selected the Beretta name was unaware of
the existence of the Beretta gun company,'' the automaker said.
``Moreover, in the United States it is not uncommon that vehicle
models and firearms have the same names, such as Colt and Marlin.''
   Beretta's lawsuit, claiming that the Beretta automobile is ``the
subject of a recall'' and ``possibly can cause'' serious harm, also
charged that the car's problems could cause further damage to the
Beretta weapons business.
   GM spokesman James W. Crellin said the Beretta, a compact sport
coupe, has had ``two minor recalls'' for a hood latch and a
headlamp switch.
   The Italian company makes luggage, clothing, cutlery and optical
equipment as well as target, hunting and military guns.
</TEXT>
