<DOCNO> AP880720-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-USMissiles     07-20 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-US Missiles,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Begin Inspecting US Missiles Under Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors today began
inspecting U.S. nuclear missiles at two British bases, Greenham
Common and Molesworth, the U.S. military said.
   The 20-member Soviet team arrived Tuesday from Moscow for the
first inspection of bases in Britain under the superpower arms
treaty to dismantle medium-range nuclear missiles.
   Soviet team leader Vyacheslav S. Lebedev detailed the inspection
plan to Col. John Fer of the U.S. On-Site Inspection Agency.
   Half of the Soviets remained at Greenham, which has 96 missiles
and five spares, and the rest traveled on a three-hour bus ride to
Molesworth, near Cambridge, which has 16 missiles.
   Greenham Common is 50 miles west of London. Molesworth is 50
miles north of London.
   The Soviet inspectors spent the night at refurbished
servicemen's quarters at the heart of the Greenham Common base.
   On Tuesday night, U.S. officers took the team on a bus tour of
the base. It included a visit to a gift shop, the Black Knight,
where they bought small British souvenirs using American currency.
   Peace protesters who have camped outside the Greenham Common
base since before cruise missiles began arriving from the United
States in November 1983 said they wanted to give a letter to the
visiting Soviets.
   The liberal Guardian newspaper said the letter read in Russian:
``We are glad you are making a start on dismantling these terrible
weapons. We hope it's the beginning of total disarmament.''
   Lebedev said Tuesday that since the inspections began this month
in the United States, the Soviet Union and West Germany, no one
seemed to be cheating.
   ``The experience of the inspections has shown that the U.S.S.R.
and United States strictly implemented the treaty signed by them
and the first steps as to its realization are successful,'' he said.
   He spoke through an interpreter from behind a podium emblazoned
with the emblem of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The Greenham Common base commander, Col. Richard. R. Riddick,
promised the Soviet inspectors help ``in carrying out your
specified duties.''
   The inspections are part of a 60-day period of inspections that
started July 1 to check whether each side told the truth about
deployments.
   The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States and five
Western European countries, while U.S. inspectors are visiting 133
Soviet sites. No violations have been reported.
   The Intermediate Nuclear Forces Treaty, signed in December,
provides for the elimination of all land-based missiles in Europe
with ranges of 300 to 3,000 miles.
   Each side has the right to make 20 short-notice inspections a
year at bases until 1991, when all the missiles and their launchers
should have been destroyed, and to make periodic inspections for a
decade thereafter.
   The Soviets have the right to enter any buildings they suspect
could accommodate missiles and additionally can post inspectors at
base gates to ensure no missiles are removed.
   The missiles and their 55-foot mobile launchers are housed in
bunkers. The Soviets will not see the warheads, which do not have
to be destroyed under the treaty.
   The Soviets told the Americans on Monday evening that they were
coming Tuesday under terms of the 16-hour notice each side must
give. They are allowed 24 hours for each inspection and can ask for
eight more hours. They must submit a report before they leave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0826EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NiponVerdict     07-20 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nipon Verdict,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acquittal Does Not Solve Mystery Of Nipon Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a jury cleared a young man in
the machine-gun slayings of two relatives of fashion designer
Albert Nipon, a prosecutor said officials were still seeking
evidence against others who might be involved.
   Michael Wolcoff heaved a sigh of relief Tuesday after a Broward
Circuit Court jury cleared him of murdering Edward and Sylvia Nipon
of Hallandale.
   ``It's hard for an American jury to convict a 20-year-old kid
who may have been peripherally involved if they don't know
specifically what happened,'' defense attorney T. Don TenBrook said
after the verdict.
   Nipon, 58, retired president of his brother's designer clothing
company, Albert Nipon Inc., and his 67-year-old wife were shot to
death at their beachfront condominium in 1987. Prosecutors
described the slayings as ``a professional hit.''
   Wolcoff was identified as one of two people who visited the
Nipons the night they were killed, and Assistant State Attorney
Chuck Morton argued that although Wolcoff did not shoot the Nipons,
he played a key role in the plot.
   The scheme was devised by Sylvia Nipon's son-in-law, Bernard
Rubin, the prosecutor said.
   Rubin had borrowed about $100,000 from Edward Nipon for a
loan-sharking or money-laundering scheme, Morton said. When Nipon
demanded his money back, Rubin feared he would go to authorities
and ordered that the couple be killed, the prosecutor said.
   Rubin and another suspect in the deaths, reputed mob hit man
Stanley Diamond, have not been charged, although Morton said
investigators continue to seek evidence against them.
   Wolcoff's lawyer argued that his client was a pawn used by the
killers to mislead and confuse the police. Court testimony never
revealed who the triggerman was.
   More clues about the killings may surface during the August
trial of Michael Wolcoff's father, Burton Wolcoff, who also faces
murder charges in the Nipons' deaths.
   Burton Wolcoff helped hide the weapon and a diamond pinky ring
taken from Edward Nipon the night he was killed, Morton said during
the younger Wolcoff's trial.
   Morton tried to convince jurors that they did not need to know
who the killer was. Wolcoff was still part of the plan and,
therefore, guilty, he said.
   ``It doesn't legally matter who pulled the trigger,'' Morton
said in closing arguments. ``Don't let Michael Wolcoff get away
with murder.''
   ``(Wolcoff) knows too much about details,'' Morton said. ``He
knew how and why and who the killer was to be.''
   Michael Wolcoff was identified as the man dressed in black who
drove up to the Nipons' condominium and visited the couple the
night they died, and both lawyers surmised that Wolcoff was
carrying a payoff of some kind to Nipon.
   TenBrook said he thought the killer arrived after Wolcoff left,
but no witnesses explained what exactly happened that night and why.
   TenBrook said he thinks it is unlikely that Rubin, now serving
time in federal prison for labor racketeering, will be tried for
the killings.
   ``Who pulled the trigger?'' TenBrook said. ``I don't have the
slightest idea.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
