<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--MissingDynamite     07-20 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Missing Dynamite,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Search For Stolen Dynamite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal, state and city authorities searched the
city today for a van loaded with more than 100 pounds of stolen
dynamite after a telephone caller reportedly told police it would
be used to bomb an abortion clinic.
   There was no indication the theft was related to the Democratic
National Convention, said police spokeswoman Myrna May.
   The tan van involved in the heist was reportedly sighted in
several locations around the city, including the state Capitol and
The Omni, where the convention that brought 35,000 visitors to the
city was being held, Ms. May said.
   Atlanta Police Sgt. G.E. Smith, assigned to the convention
command center, said no arrests had been made.
   The dynamite was stolen early Tuesday from a suburban blasting
company by a ski-masked bandit, officials said.
   The Atlanta Constitution, quoting unidentified sources, said
police received a call saying the dynamite would be used against an
abortion clinic. Police had been warned that an abortion clinic
would be blown up during the convention, the newspaper said.
   Atlanta police and convention security officers were alerted to
the theft by the Henry County Sheriff's Department. Sheriff's Capt.
Keith McBrayer said two cases, each containing 50 pounds of
dynamite, or about 200 sticks, and 200 blasting caps were taken.
   The FBI, the Georgia Bureau of Investigation, the Secret Service
and the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms have joined
police from Atlanta and Henry County in the search, officials said.
   ``They've detected no connection with the convention,'' said GBI
spokesman John Bankhead. ``But the convention security people are
certainly aware of this.''
</TEXT>
