<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Dukakis-Family 1stLd-Writethru a0492 07-20 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Dukakis-Family, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 5 grafs new with mother's quotes, edits pvs graf 3 for
transition; picks u pvs graf 4: Her children.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Keeps Low Profile But Family's A Busy Bunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' 84-year-old mother, one of a
slew of family members who will watch Democratic delegates nominate
the Massachusetts governor as the party's presidential candidate,
said today the convention experience is awesome.
   Euterpe Dukakis also said she has derived joy and pleasure in
promoting her son among the thousands of people attending the
convention.
   While Dukakis has kept a relatively low profile awaiting his
coronation as the Democratic nominee, his family has been busy
rallying delegates, meeting the media and enjoying heaps of
Southern hospitality.
   ``It is certainly very awesome in the old sense of the word,
very awesome, and exciting...,'' Euterpe Dukakis said about the
convention. ``The reception that my son is getting, the responses
that he is getting are very gratifying,'' she said on ABC-TV's
``Good Morning America.''
   Kitty Dukakis, the candidate's wife, said some of her
experiences in this city have been ``so special I can't even
articulate how much it has meant to me and to us.''
   Kitty Dukakis' convention duties have included network
television interviews, an appearance before black delegates,
meetings with state delegations and a discussion with
Asian-Americans about her work on behalf of refugees.
   Her children have kept a hectic pace as well, but her husband,
the Massachusetts governor, generally has appeared at only one
public event a day and spent much of each day rehearsing his
Thursday night acceptance speech and holding private meetings at
his hotel. One such meeting was Monday's peacemaking session with
rival Jesse Jackson.
   That session has allowed the Dukakis family members to preach a
common theme: party unity.
   ``We may have traveled different paths to get here, but if we
are to win we must go forward together,'' Mrs. Dukakis told
Asian-American delegates Tuesday.
   Mrs. Dukakis delivered a similar message a day earlier, at a
barbecue with black delegates just hours after her husband and
Jackson emerged smiling from their summit.
   ``We all go forward, together, on the same team to victory in
November,'' Mrs. Dukakis said. Referring to Inauguration Day, she
added: ``We look forward to being together with all of you on a
colder day in January.''
   Campaigning is nothing new to the Dukakis clan. But Atlanta has
put them under a bigger spotlight, with an audience of more than
4,000 delegates and more than 13,000 representatives of the news
media.
   For son John Dukakis, Tuesday was `M' day, with morning visits
to the delegations from Missouri, Massachusetts and Michigan.
   ``Please recognize that you are ambassadors to all the other
delegations,'' he told delegates from his home state.
   He professed to be having the time of his life.
   ``This is the greatest week you could ever imagine for all of
us,'' he said.
   At a meeting of North Carolina delegates, he said Jackson and
his constituents are welcome members of the Dukakis campaign.
   ``The convention that America sees ... will reflect the
principles of fairness, inclusion and full participation that Mike
Dukakis has supported for his entire adult life,'' he said.
   Mrs. Dukakis and daughters Andrea and Kara spent Tuesday with an
alphabet soup of delegations. Between them, they visited delegates
from Florida, Pennsylvania, New Hampshire, Alaska, North Carolina,
Utah and Kentucky.
   At the Florida stop, Mrs. Dukakis was greeted by Wilma
Greenfield, her ``oldest friend,'' and Susan Guber, a grade-school
classmate of Dukakis.
   Kara Dukakis, a Brown University student who organized a
Students for Dukakis there, held a student reception Tuesday.
Andrea, who spent months in chilly Iowa preparing for its February
caucuses, took time during a scorching week in Atlanta to meet with
the National Rural Caucus.
   Lisa Dukakis, John's wife, also got into the act, including a
visit to the Kentucky delegation. She has now ``announced'' her
pregnancy to a party of Democrats.
   They aren't the only Dukakises in town.
   Another is Olympia Dukakis, who urged on her cousin Michael when
she accepted an Oscar earlier this year for her supporting role in
the movie ``Moonstruck.'' She will introduce Dukakis to the
delegates waiting for him to accept the nomination.
</TEXT>
