<HEAD>Sixteen Dead, 9 Missing In Korean Floods</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE toll from today's flooding to 16 dead,
nine missing, raises toll since July 8 and property damage figure.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Landslides and flooding caused by
torrential rains left 25 people dead or missing today, a government
agency said.
   The National Counter-Disaster Center said 16 people were
confirmed killed and nine were missing and presumed dead.
   News reports said about 650 houses were flooded and 2,640 people
were evacuated to schools and other temporary shelters after the
latest downpours, which dropped nearly eight inches of rain.
   Officials said that since the rainy season began July 8, 32
people have died and 10 are missing. Property damage was estimated
at $45 million.
   Six people, including four children under 12 years old, were
killed when landslides buried three homes in Yongwol, 75 miles east
of Seoul, the officials said. They spoke on condition of anonymnity.
   A taxi careened off a road and plunged into a flooded river in
Chechon, 65 miles south of Seoul. Two passengers were killed and
two were rescued, officials said.
   In the southern Youngju city, three family members, including
two children, were killed when a landslide smashed their house, the
officials said.
   Other deaths were caused by floods and landslides, and rescue
workers were digging through debris for possible survivors.
   Train service on the Taebaek and Jungang Railway lines in
eastern South Korea was suspended because some sections of track
were under water or washed away.
</TEXT>
