<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ireland-Shooting     07-20 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-Shooting,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lord Mountbatten Assassin Fires Gun In Courthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA guerrilla serving a life sentence
for the 1979 assassination of British statesman Earl Mountbatten of
Burma fired a gun inside a Dublin courthouse today, but no one was
injured, police said.
   Thomas McMahon, 40, pulled out a gun in a second-floor cell in
Dublin's High Court and fired one shot that struck a wall before he
was overpowered by two guards, police said.
   A police official who spoke on condition of anonymity said it
was not immediately clear how McMahon acquired the weapon.
   McMahon was later escorted to a courtroom to testify in his case
against the administrator of Portlaoise Prison. McMahon filed suit
after allegedly suffering a broken wrist during a strip search in
1983.
   McMahon, of Carrickmacross in County Monaghan, has been serving
a life sentence at the high-security prison since his conviction in
November 1979.
   Mountbatten, cousin of Queen Elizabeth II and the last British
viceroy of India, was killed Aug. 27, 1979, in a bomb blast aboard
his yacht off the coast of Ireland. Three other people were killed
in the bombing.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army said it carried out the
killing as part of its campaign to oust the British from Northern
Ireland and reunite the province with the predominantly Catholic
republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
