<2ND_LINE>PM-Bumper Stickers,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roemer Vetoes Bumper Sticker Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer has reversed himself
and vetoed legislation restricting the display of bumper stickers
deemed obscene.
   One bill listed specific words and said they could not appear on
bumper stickers in letters larger than one-eighth inch. A second
measure would have banned all words or pictures ruled obscene by
the courts on bumper stickers.
   Roemer first said he liked the bills, but killed them Tuesday,
citing First Amendment guarantees.
   ``It is just unconstitutional,'' the governor said. ``It could
cost us a ton'' of money to defend the laws in court.
   The Louisiana chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union had
said it would go to court if Roemer signed either bill.
   In his veto message, Roemer said: ``The intent of this
legislation is excellent, and I fully agree with the concept of
same. I personally find such public display of the prohibited words
extremely offensive.
   ``But after consultation between my legal staff and
representatives of the attorney general's office, I have been
advised that there is little chance that this statute will
withstand constitutional scrutiny.''
</TEXT>
