<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Children, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20,000 Children May Be Infected By AIDS Virus by 1991,
Pediatrician Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to CORRECT relationship between numbers
of children and beds. PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Not all ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By 1991, children infected by the AIDS virus may
occupy as many as one in 10 of the nation's pediatric hospital
beds, an AIDS researcher says.
   The number of infected children could reach 10,000 to 20,000 by
then, and infected children might occupy one in 15 to one in 10
pediatric beds, James Oleske said Tuesday at a science writers
conference sponsored by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
   Not all of them, however, would have full-blown acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, Oleske said.
   Oleske said he believes that by 1991 any city with poor people
and intravenous drug abuse ``can unfortunately expect to see
pediatric AIDS developing.''
   The pediatric researcher at the University of Medicine and
Dentistry of New Jersey-New Jersey Medical School in Newark, N.J.,
said his predictions were based on experience caring for infected
children in Newark and on federal statistics.
   The federal Centers for Disease Control has counted 1,065 cases
of AIDS so far in children who were diagnosed while younger than 13.
   CDC has no projections on how many children may become infected
by 1991, but the Atlanta-based agency does expect a cumulative
total of more than 3,000 pediatric AIDS cases by that time, a CDC
spokeswoman said.
   Robert Sweeney, president of the National Association of
Children's Hospitals and Related Institutions, said pediatric AIDS
cases may increase substantially.
   ``It looks like it could pretty well double in this year,'' he
said in a telephone interview. ``If they keep doubling, they do
tend to add up.''
   AIDS in children often results from an infected mother, and
Oleske said maternal-child care centers should be established to
care for the mother and child. It is ``preposterous'' that a woman
should have to ``take a crosstown bus'' to get care for herself
after having her child seen by a pediatrician, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RoarkRelease     07-20 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roark Release,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roark, Former W.Va. Mayor, Released From Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETERSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Mike Roark of Charleston,
W.Va., walked out of federal prison today after serving five months
for cocaine possession.
   The 42-year-old former prosecutor nicknamed ``Mad Dog'' for his
flamboyant ways, which included wearing a camouflage jacket and
sidearm on drug raids, was whisked past news cameras at the Federal
Correctional Institute shortly before 8 a.m.
   Warden J.J. Clark said Roark refused to sign consent forms
allowing himself to be interviewed or permitting prison officials
to discuss his incarceration.
   The one-time assistant U.S. attorney in Pittsburgh and Kanawha
County, W.Va., prosecutor pleaded guilty to six counts of cocaine
possession Nov. 17 and resigned as mayor Nov. 24, seven months
after being elected to a second four-year term.
   In January, he was sentenced to 179 days in prison and fined
$5,000. Roark entered prison Feb. 12 and was scheduled for release
Aug. 8. Federal authorities said he was released 18 days early
because he was a model prisoner.
   ``Obviously, he's presented no problems to us,'' Clark said,
adding that Roark worked as a clerk in the prison's education
department.
   Roark left prison in a convertible accompanied by a former aide,
Ed Esposito, and a man prison officials identified as Roark's
brother.
   Roark, once talked up as a Republican gubernatorial candidate,
has said he no longer has a political future in West Virginia. He
has said he wants to return to private practice if if he retains
his law license.
   ``His being a political candidate is about as absurd as electing
me to the papacy,'' said John Charnock, Charleston city attorney
and a close friend of Roark's. Roark hopes to join Charnock's law
firm.
   The state Bar Association is trying to revoke or suspend Roark's
license for breaching legal ethics by possessing and using cocaine.
He faces an Aug. 1 meeting with State Bar investigators.
   ``His mood is good. He'd like to get back to Charleston,''
Charnock said Tuesday.
   Last July, Roark was indicted on 27 cocaine-related counts and
three obstruction counts. He accepted a plea bargain.
   Twice divorced and a father of two, Roark led a highly visible
nightlife in West Virginia's capital. During his more than 4{ years
as mayor, he was dogged by rumors of cocaine use, which he
vehemently denied until he pleaded guilty.
   In an interview with the Charleston Daily Mail published the day
he entered prison, he said: ``I was stupid. ... I was weak. I had
to face the cold, hard facts of what I had done.''
   Roark called his behavior as prosecutor ``hypocritical'' but
denied his cocaine use affected his actions as prosecutor or mayor.
   ``You know, I was up at the top of the ladder, and now I'm at
the bottom of the ladder,'' Roark said in February. ``As far as I'm
concerned, the political, public life of Mike Roark is over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
