<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-NorthKorea     07-20 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-North Korea,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Picked Up Resolution and Letter from South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has accepted a letter from
South Korea's National Assembly urging it to take part in the
Olympic Games in Seoul, officials said today.
   The letter from Assembly Speaker Kim Chae-sun to his North
Korean counterpart, Yang Hyong Sop, was handed to North Korean
representatives at the Panmunjom truce site on Monday.
   It was the first time the communist North has accepted a letter
from the South via Panmunjom since Oct. 16. The North refused to
accept several South Korean government proposals on easing tension
during the past few weeks.
   Unification Board officials said they did not know why the North
picked up the letter this time. But the assembly is controlled by
the South Korean opposition, and the North might be more willing to
deal with the assembly than the administration.
   Pyongyang has threatened to boycott the Sept. 17-Oct.2 games
unless it is allowed to be a co-host. Olympic authorities have
rejected the North's demand.
   The North accuses the government of President Roh Tae-woo of
being dictatorial and has called on opposition forces, students and
workers in the South to oust the government to speed up
reunfication of the two Koreas.
   The peninsula has been divided into the pro-Western South and
the communist North since 1945.
</TEXT>
