<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OccultTrial     07-20 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Occult Trial,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libel Award in Trial Focusing on the Occult</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lion Serpent Sun was indeed a
satanist but was not involved in any human sacrifice attempt, a
jury decided in awarding him $10,000 in a libel suit.
   The British Columbia Supreme Court jury ruled Tuesday that Sun
was libeled when Len Olsen, in a 1984 appearance on the
Toronto-based TV show ``100 Huntley Street,'' claimed he and his
wife barely escaped death in a satanic ritual.
   Sun, a 39-year-old welfare recipient with self-proclaimed status
as bishop in the ``Holy Catholic Gnostic Ekklesia,'' was awarded
$10,000 Canadian ($8,300 U.S.) in damages and court costs from
Olsen, the TV show and an evangelist who appeared with Olsen.
   ``I do feel that the award should have been a little bit
higher,'' said Sun, who was wearing a brown cleric's collar.
   ``I do resent being called a satanist in the sense that it's
been explained in so many ways as being such a negative thing,'' he
said. ``I don't like being called a satanist. I find that
difficult.''
   Olsen, now a Pentecostal preacher who runs a Vancouver clinic
for troubled teen-agers, said he and his wife were considering an
appeal.
   ``We feel somewhat vindicated in that it was said by the jury
that the group was satanist,'' said Olsen, flanked by his wife,
Sheila.
   Geoff Cowper, counsel for ``100 Huntley Street,'' said he would
make his recommendation on an appeal within a few weeks.
   During six weeks of testimony, the jury heard one lurid tale
after another of nude ritual meetings, drugs, satanic practices and
witchcraft in Sun's now-defunct Diddling Metaphysical Bookstore.
   What the jury had to decide was what happened the night of Oct.
14, 1972.
   Witnesses for Sun said the only thing out of the ordinary was
Olsen's behavior following the consecration of some ceremonial
knives.
   One of the ``high priests,'' Gary Gage-Cole, testifed that
Olsen's chanting suddenly went off key. Olsen became ``wild-eyed''
and starting screaming that the others were going to kill him,
Gage-Cole said.
   Gage-Cole said Sun tried to calm Olsen by putting his arm around
him and then bringing a statue of Christ decorated with angels and
demons into the ritual circle.
   The Olsens testified that as the ritual was drawing to a close,
Sun, Gage-Cole and two others drew their ceremonial knives and held
them to the couple's throats.
   Olsen said he saw the statue and heard the voice of God telling
him to break the circle. When he did that, Olsen said, the sound of
a flute came out of his mouth. Olsen and his wife then fled.
   ``There has to be an easier way to become a Christian than
that,'' Olsen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
