<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-ShipAttack     07-20 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Ship Attack,1st Ld - Writethru, a0605,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It has Identified Ringleader and Accomplices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 9th, `Hours before...' with ministry
handing out photos of suspects. ADDS 3 grafs after last graf to
detail security measures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it has
identified the ringleader of a massacre aboard a Greek cruise ship,
and it linked him to a slaying claimed by the Abu Nidal terrorist
group.
   Public Order Minister Anastasios Sehiotis said the leader was
Hejab Jaballa, who holds a Libyan passport. Sehiotis said Jaballa
was involved in the slaying of an Egyptian newspaper editor 10
years ago in Nicosia, Cyprus, which was claimed by Abu Nidal.
   He said three accomplices to the ship attack also were
identified. Sehiotis identified them as Aboul Amoud, Adnan Sojod
and Merhi Mehieddine.
   Terrorists fired guns and threw grenades aboard the ship, the
City of Poros, in the Aegean Sea on July 11. Nine people were
killed and at least 98 were wounded.
   Police matched fingerprints found in an Athens apartment rented
by Jaballa with those uncovered in 1978 in Cyprus and found they
belonged to the same person, Sehiotis said.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, gets much of his
funding from Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi and maintains
headquarters in Tripoli. U.S. officials have said Abu Nidal
probably conducted the ship attack.
   Sehiotis, who read a long statement to journalists, refused to
say whether Jaballa and his alleged accomplices were dead or had
fled the country.
   Sehiotis said police speculated that at least one of the gunmen
may have been killed by an explosion that rocked the ship's bridge.
No positive identification of two bodies has been made.
   Hours before the attack, two men believed to be Arabs died in a
car explosion near a marina where the City of Poros was scheduled
to dock. Their car contained automatic weapons and explosives.
   Officials released photographs of three Arab suspects. They said
the photographs were found in forged passports and at the site of
the explosion of the car. The officials identified only two of the
men in the photographs _ Jaballa and Mehieddine _ but were unable
to name the third man.
   Police said they believe the occupants of the car were waiting
for the cruise liner to arrive at the marina and planned to hijack
it.
   Sehiotis said Jaballa arrived in Greece by air from Copenhagen
on June 1. He was preceded by his three accomplices, who arrived in
Athens early in May from Belgrade after starting out from Beirut,
Sehiotis said.
   ``All the evidence indicates that Jaballa played the leading
role in the terrorist operation since he had all the details of
members of his group in his possession,'' Sehiotis said.
   Police said that during their investigation, they found forged
passports belonging to the suspects.
   Greek officials were reluctant to say whatArab group could
possibly be behind the massacre aboard the ship. But CIA director
William Webster in Washington reportedly said last week that the
terrorist attack appeared to be the work of the Abu Nidal group.
   Merchant Marine Minister Evangelos Yannopoulos outlined new
security measures in effect at the country's major ports and aboard
cruise liners.
   He said that five to 10 commandos would be assigned to each
cruise ship and would be responsible for neutralizing terrorist
attempts to take over a vessel.
   Passengers at the port of Piraeus near Athens reported they
underwent a body search and their luggage was photographed by X-ray
equipment before boarding a ship for a cruise last weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
