<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Kidnapping     07-20 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnapping,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church People Shocked At Discovery Of Girl Under Altar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pastor of a church where a
4-year-old girl may have been held for up to six weeks says no one
would have heard her if she yelled for help because she was kept in
a space far beneath the altar.
   A deaf-mute church janitor, Kenneth Alvin Michel, was scheduled
for arraignment late today on kidnapping charges in the case.
   Michel, 32, was arrested Monday as he drove up to the United
Methodist Church in suburban Elk Grove where officers found two
missing girls.
   Five-year-old Muey Han Saefong, who was kidnapped Monday in
Sacramento, was found in the back of Michel's car, her mouth taped
and legs bound, police said.
   The 4-year-old, Candi Talarico, who had been missing since June
4, was found in an L-shaped space under the church.
   The hiding space, officers said, had a dirt floor, concrete
walls and a wooden ceiling. It was furnished with blankets, stuffed
animals, books, food, lights, a television and newspapers that
contained articles about the Talarico kidnapping, which was
featured on Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``America's Most Wanted'' TV
program.
   Boards covered the entrance to the space, which church pastor
Linda Inlow said was below a wooden crawl space under the church.
   Inlow said the discovery shocked church officials.
   ``We don't know how long she was down there, or if she was down
there the whole time,'' Inlow said Tuesday. ``We don't know if she
was tied up or able to communicate. (But) the crawl space is well
insulated and you wouldn't have necessarily been able to hear
anyone.''
   She said that Candi was kept in a 7-by-9-by-3 foot space under
the crawl space floor.
   Investigators found Michel after a witness gave them the license
number of a car allegedly used in an attempted abduction Monday of
a 6-year-old girl; the girl's 9-year-old sister and the witness
foiled the abduction, said police Sgt. Bob Burns.
   Inlow said Michel had been placed on leave of absence by a day
care center where he also worked because of ``potential problems
with his behavior.''
   Inlow said Michel ``was never accused of molestation or
fondling.''
   The Rev. David Delaplane, an adviser to Inlow, said the center
placed Michel on leave of absence last spring because Michel
pinched some children who had teased him because of his handicaps.
</TEXT>
