<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--SealedConvention 2ndLd-Writethru a0569 07-20 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Sealed Convention, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0569,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Omni Locked Up; Some Delegates Miss Jackson Speech</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Kirk's comments, picks up 4th graf pvs,
Jackson's speech; subs 10th graf to eliminate redundant title.
^By RICHARD L. VERNACI</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Party Chairman Paul Kirk, facing
complaints from delegates who couldn't get in to see Jesse Jackson,
said today that they knew the size of the hall and that they should
stay in the building during convention sessions to keep the same
thing from happening again.
   ``This is not a superdome,'' Kir said. ``For all intents and
purposes, it's a live TV studio.''
   Kirk's comments came after as many as 1,000 unhappy people, some
of them delegates, were left outside the Omni Tuesday night because
party leaders had the building's entrances sealed off before
Jackson's late speech at the fire marshal's suggestion.
   To avoid a repeat situation, Kirk suggested delegates remain in
the building after the gavel sounds to open the convention each day.
   On Tuesday, police gazed across their barricades at a shouting
throng of credential-waving delegates, guests and reporters who
were left standing in the warm night breeze.
   Jackson's speech could be seen on large televisions set up in a
cavernous exhibition hall across the street, but those who were
stuck outside didn't pay their way to Atlanta to watch TV.
   ``I would rather die,'' said Richard Koster, who traveled from
Panama as part of the Democrats Abroad delegation. ``Why don't you
watch your wedding night on TV?''
   ``It was not unexpected that we would have problems with the
hall,'' said party spokesman Mike McCurry.
   The same thing happened at least three times in 1984, when
Democrats held their convention in the 15,000-seat Moscone Center
Hall in San Francisco, McCurry said.
   So why did the party four years later decide to meet in a hall
that could seat only 11,000?
   ``I'm just not going to go into that right now,'' he said.
``That's ancient history and we're here now.''
   Kirk said the building wasn't too small, the crowd was just too
big. ``People should have known,'' Kirk said. ``Obviously people
had plenty of notice. It has nothing to do with the size of the
hall.''
   The great and the small alike found themselves unable to budge
the police.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., was seen emerging from a crowd that was
trying without success to gain entry. When asked his thoughts about
being barred from a building in his home state, Nunn's reply was a
stare followed by a no comment.
   Aides said later that Nunn wasn't really trying to get back in
the hall but was leaving so he could watch Jackson on television.
   A handful of relatives of Michael Dukakis, the party's
nominee-to-be, were detained for a few minutes by a skeptical
policeman. They eventually were allowed to pass.
   Delegates ran from one gate to the next in hopes that someone
somewhere would let them in. About three dozen of them eventually
made it.
   The rest elbowed their way through crowds yelling ``delegate,
delegate.'' There were shouts of ``Let me in'' and ``This is
America, buddy.''
   Rep. Carol Moseley Braun, assistant majority leader of the
Illinois General Assembly, said she was turned away from The Omni
and watched Jackson's speech on television in the adjoining World
Congress Center.
   ``I was furious about not getting in, particularly as a delegate
from the state of Illinois,'' she said. ``I though it was a denial
of my right to participate in the process.''
   Delegates did not miss any key votes, but Koster said they were
denied the possibility to witness history.
   He drew a connection to the convention in 1896 when a relatively
unknown politician, William Jennings Bryan, delivered his famous
``cross of gold'' speech that propelled him instantly from
obscurity to the Democratic presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
