<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0597 07-20 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Africa Approves Agreement On Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs with government announcing agreement
accepted. Picks up 4th pvs, `The agreement... ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has agreed to
principles negotiated in New York to remove foreign troops from
Angola and grant independence to South-West Africa, the Department
of Foreign Affairs announced today.
   The governments of Angola, Cuba and the United States were
expected to make similar announcements, agreeing to a list of 14
principles signed by negotiators from the four countries in peace
talks last week.
   The principles include acceptance of a withdrawal of Cuban
troops from Angola and implementation of a U.N. peace plan for
South-West Africa, that includes South African withdrawal from the
territory it rules.
   A call for South African withdrawal of an estimated 3,000 troops
from Angola was not specifically contained in the principles made
public here.
   The agreement reached in New York calls for an estimated 50,000
Cuban troops to leave Marxist-ruled Angola and for South Africa to
end its 73-year rule over South-West Africa, commonly known as
Namibia.
   But no timetable has been set for the withdrawal of Cuban troops
or independence for Namibia, the main issues to be negotiated in
future talks.
   Angola, with help from its Cuban allies, has been fighting a
civil war since it gained independence from Portugal in 1975,
battling the pro-Western rebels of UNITA, or the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola.
   The United States supplies military aid to UNITA while South
Africa has several thousand troops in southern Angola fighting
alongside the rebels.
   The United States and South Africa are seeking a full Cuban
troop withdrawal over a one-year period. Cuba and Angola have
talked of a four-year period for the Cuban pullback but they have
indicated flexibility.
   Under a 1978 United Nations resolution, independence in Namibia
would be carried out over a one-year time frame once South Africa
consents to that step.
   But South Africa, with U.S. backing, has said the South African
withdrawal will not take place unless Cuba agrees to withdraw its
forces simultaneously.
   Sparsely populated Namibia is between South Africa and Angola.
South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I under a League of
Nations mandate. The League's successor, the United Nations,
revoked that mandate.
   The four parties involved in the talks began their meetings in
London in May. The next round is tentatively scheduled for August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
