<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma-Van     07-20 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Van,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>41 Suffocate In Prison Van</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State radio reported that 41 people who
were arrested and packed into a prison van on March 18 died during
a two-hour ride to jail.
   Home Minister U Min Goung took responsibility and resigned from
office, according to the announcement on Tuesday.
   It said the government delayed its disclosure to prevent the
possible spread of unrest. The radio said the bodies were cremated
March 19.
   The 41 victims were among 71 people arrested during student
riots and sent in a prison van from downtown Rangoon to Insein
jail, the radio said. It said the detainees were crowded into one
van because of a shortage of such vehicles.
   The ride to the jail, eight miles north of Rangoon, usually
takes 45 minutes but took two hours, the announcement said. It
didn't say why it took so long.
   The 41 were found dead when the van arrived at the jail, with
the deaths due to suffocation caused by exposure to tear gas and to
the long period spent in the overcrowded prison van, the radio said.
   In March, official announcements mentioned two deaths in
connection with the riots.
</TEXT>
