<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 4thLd-Writethru a0608 07-20 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0608,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Expelled in Wake of Fight for Nagorno-Karabakh
^Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf pvs: `The decision...' to
UPDATE with Ayrikyan pardoned, explanation of charges and quotes
from girlfriend. Pick up 5th graf pvs: `On Tuesday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today expelled a prominent Armenian
activist and stripped him of his Soviet citizenship as punishment
for stirring up nationalist sentiment in an ethnic dispute, the
Tass news agency said.
   Tass did not say where the activist, Paruyr Ayrikyan, 39, was
headed or whether he left the Soviet Union.
   The expulsion came two days after the Soviet leadership gave a
final ruling in the heated and sometimes violent struggle between
Armenians and Azerbaijanis over control of the small
Nagorno-Karabakh region in the Caucasus Mountains.
   The decision by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet to reject
Armenia's bid to annex the region appeared today on the front pages
of national newspapers.
   Tass also said that Ayrikyan was pardoned, but it did not say
what he was pardoned for. He was arrested last March on charges of
defaming the Soviet state, but it is not known whether he was
convicted.
   Susana Avakyan, his girlfriend and fellow member of the
underground group Alliance for National Self-Determination, said in
a telephone interview that authorities have been trying for months
to get Ayrikyan to agree to expulsion but that he refused.
   ``He said that if you hear that I agreed, it's a provocation. I
won't agree,'' said Avakyan, 39.
   Ayrikyan relayed the message to two of his sisters who visited
him in prison in late June, Avakyan said.
   On Tuesday night, state-run television showed a debate in the
Presidium during which Mikhail S. Gorbachev chastised nationalists
in Azerbaijan and Armenia for stirring up tensions in the dispute.
   Hundreds of Armenians tried to gather at Red Square on Tuesday
night to protest the decision of the Presidium, the nation's
nominal parliament, to reject the annexation, said an Armenian
activist in Moscow, Leon Sudzhyan. He said police roughed them up
and took them away to police stations.
   Residents of the Armenian capital of Yerevan were said to be
``despondent'' but relatively calm earlier today before Ayrikyan's
expulsion was reported.
   The nationalist helped organize the Armenian drive to have
Nagorno-Karabakh removed from Azerbaijan's control and annexed to
the Armenian republic. He also provided frequent reports to foreign
correspondents in Moscow on the mass demonstrations and strikes
staged in support of the annexation effort.
   ``From youth, he has been involved in fanning up nationalist
animosity,'' Tass said of Ayrikyan, who has spent 17 years in labor
camps and in exile for his activity.
   Tass said the ``former criminal...created a crisis situation in
Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh,'' and it accused him of giving
information to Moscow-based correspondents that was ``based on
imagination.'' Ayrikyan was arrested March 25 and charged with
defaming the Soviet state.
   Armenians are predominantly Christian and the Nagorno-Karabakh
region was part of Armenia until 1923. Armenians make up
three-quarters of the 160,000 people of the contested region, and
they claim that Azerbaijanis, who are mostly Moslem, are
discriminating against them.
   Strikes and demonstrations have been common in Nagorno-Karabakh
and the Armenian capital of Yerevan since February, when the
disputed region's initial appeal for transfer to Armenia was
denied. On Feb. 28, rioting in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait left
32 people dead, 26 of them Armenians.
   Repeated telephone calls to Nagorno-Karabakh failed to go
through today.
   The Presidium, heeding Gorbachev's call, said during an
extraordinary eight-hour session on Monday that the constitution
makes the annexation of the region by Armenia ``impossible.''
   During the highlights of the session broacast Tuesday night,
Nagorno-Karabakh leader Genrikh Pogosyan made an impassioned speech
saying the only correct decision was to return the territory to
Armenia.
   But dozens of other speakers contended Azerbaijan was within its
rights in vetoing the annexation bid and called for maintaining the
status quo.
   Gorbachev urged Armenians and Azerbaijanis to accept the
``existing reality'' of the republic's location and struck out at
what he called constant tests of his reforms by groups with selfish
interests at heart.
   Many of the Armenian activists who had been pressing for
annexation have cast the question as a test of the sincerity of
Gorbachev's campaigns to give Soviets more say in governmental
affairs.
</TEXT>
