<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ArmsControl 530   07-20 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Control, 530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Praises Soviet Offer To Level Disputed Radar Facility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration today welcomed as a
``positive step'' a Soviet offer to dismantle a disputed radar
complex in Krasnoyarsk, but said there should be no strings
attached to the proposal.
   ``It should be unconditional,'' said a U.S. official, who
described the offer as a step forward in discussions with the
Soviets over the Siberian facility.
   So far, however, the Soviets have not proposed a date for a
joint review with the United States of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty, which imposes constraints on radar and other
defenses against rocket attack.
   The offer to dismantle Krasnoyarsk`s phased array radar was
coupled in Moscow on Tuesday with a proposal that the United States
promise to adhere to the pact.
   ``If an understanding to abide by the ABM treaty, as signed in
1972, is reached, the Soviet Union will be ready to dismantle the
Krasnoyarsk redar in a verifiable way that would leave no doubts on
the part of the United States,'' Viktor P. Karpov, the Soviet
foreign ministry's top arms control specialist, said.
   The U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
President Reagan had not decided whether to accuse the Soviets of a
``material breach'' of the treaty at Krasnoyarsk, a step that could
clear the way for the United States to expand its ``Star War''
tests.
   The head of the Arms Control Agency wants Reagan to level the
charge against Moscow while the Joint Chiefs of Staff have urged
him to hold to the 1972 pact.
   The odd lineup reflects a deep and peculiar division within the
administration as Reagan awaits a response from Moscow on when to
review the treaty, considered a cornerstone of the arms control
process.
   Reagan has already labeled the Krasnoyarsk radar a violation of
the 1972 treaty in two reports to Congress. While the Soviets deny
any infraction, even many liberal critics of the administration's
arm control policy question the legality of the facility.
   The joint chiefs recommended that Reagan not charge the Soviets
with a ``material breach'' because that could lead to an unraveling
of the treaty, the U.S. official told The Associated Press. ``The
chiefs are convinced if that happens the Soviets are in a better
position to take advantage of a breakout,'' the official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   This puts the chiefs at odds with arms control director William
F. Burns Jr., who takes a harder stance on the treaty than the
military. But Burns would give the Soviets time to level the
facilities before the United States retaliated.
   The official said that even if Reagan accepted the advice of
Burns and other hard-line advisers, it did not mean he would
scuttle the treaty, which limits U.S. and Soviet defenses against
ballistic missiles.
   ``It would mean we have a right to do something restricted by
the treaty,'' the official said. ``It doesn't mean we are going to
throw the treaty out the window.''
   In the meantime, the treaty is due for its five-year review, and
the United States had proposed to the Soviets that the review begin
last Friday in Geneva.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
