<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     07-20 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor: Biaggi `A Thug in a Congressman's Suit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mario Biaggi is ``a thug in a congressman's
suit,'' a prosecutor said in closing arguments today at the
4-month-old Wedtech Corp. corruption trial.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Edward J. Little told the jury that the
10-term Bronx Democrat had extorted cash and stock from the
now-defunct defense contractor through the power of his office.
   ``He wasn't a thug with a gun. He's a thug in a congressman's
suit,'' Little said.
   Biaggi, 70, his eldest son, Richard, and five others are charged
with turning Wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid out
millions of dollars in bribes to obtain no-bid defense contracts.
   The defense has maintained that four corrupt Wedtech executives,
who testified for the government in exchange for leniency, had
links to White House insiders like Attorney General Edwin Meese III
and did not need help.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley denied a defense
request to call Meese as a witness, saying his actions had nothing
to do with the guilt or innocence of those on trial. Meese has not
been charged with any wrongdoing.
   The final witness in the trial Tuesday was Toni Patricia Biaggi,
Richard Biaggi's wife. She was called by the defense for her
supposed familiarity with her husband's dealings.
   During cross-examination by prosecutors, however, she admitted
that she was unaware of the existence of two companies in which her
husband owned 50 percent of the shares and served as director.
   Prosecutors said the companies, Four Star Military Marketing
Corp. and the Five Star Realty Corp., were vehicles through which
the younger Biaggi was paid kickbacks from military contractors
doing business with Wedtech.
   Mrs. Biaggi also said her husband never told her anything about
Martin Marietta Corp. Earlier in the trial, a former director of
operation at Martin Marietta, John W. Paxton, said the congressman
telephoned him ``at least two, maybe three or four times,'' to urge
the company to select Wedtech as a subcontractor.
   All of the defendants except Biaggi, his son and Bernard
Ehrlich, the congressman's former law partner, took the witness
stand during the trial, which began March 11.
   Biaggi had intended to take the stand himself until Motley gave
prosecutors wide latitude to cross-examine the congressman about
his past, including his conviction in an unrelated case on charges
of accepting an illegal gratuity.
</TEXT>
