<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   07-20 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0792</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   July 19
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on Iran accepting cease fire
resolution:
   Iran shocked and surprised the diplomatic world Monday by
announcing that it accepted a year-old U.N. Security Council
resolution calling for a cease fire in its bloody, eight-year war
with neighboring Iraq.
   With its fingers crossed against disappointment, the Reagan
administration called the step a ``major breakthrough'' toward
peace.
   With grim suspicion, Iraq saw a ``tactical'' move by the
``devious Iranian regime.''
   Whichever view proves correct, Tehran's statement still must be
welcomed. It was the first time it had talked about an
unconditional truce.
   Iraq may be making the diplomatic error of refusing to take yes
for an answer. It should enter U.N.-mediated negotiations with Iran
to see where they lead.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 15
   The Seattle Times on the Mexican election:
   In 1846, the United States stole half of Mexico, and this
country has never felt obliged to pay much attention since.
Mexico's presidential election may change that.
   After 60 years of popular allegiance, the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary party held on to power by a whisker. Carlos Salinas
de Gortari won the presidency by a humbling 50.36 percent of the
vote. His predecessors never received less than 70 percent.
   Democracy is messy, and the proof will come in the
protest-filled streets of Mexican cities. Minority parties on both
the left and right believe Salinas' narrow win is as much of a
fraud as his party's string of victories since 1929. ...
   Over the years, the United States has lectured and wagged a
finger at Mexico about drugs, pollution, Central American politics
and immigration. ...
   Mexico is still smarting over what it considers the unwarranted
condemnation of its drug-enforcement efforts by Congress.
   As new, angry voices gain ascendancy in Mexico, Washington may
have to listen for a change.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 15
   Anchorage (Alaska) Daily News on George Bush at the United
Nations:
   A few days back, Vice President George Bush said that he
couldn't wait to tell the United Nations the U.S. view of the July
3 Iranian airliner tragedy.
   But now that he's had his say, it's clear Bush's narrow view of
events wasn't worth the buildup.
   Bush couldn't resist a recitation of this country's right to
sail the Persian Gulf and a detailed review of Iran's many sins in
its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   Clearly the United States does have a right to use the gulf.
Clearly Iran's radical government has conducted a bloody war
against Iraq that frequently has been characterized by outright
barbarism.
   But ... Bush's account of the war was distorted. Iraq is as much
to blame for the war as Iran. If the Iranians have attacked neutral
ships _ so have the Iraquis. If Iranians repeatedly have shown
contempt for the United States _ so have the Iraquis. ...
   Bush spent his visit to the U.N. talking at the Iranian
delegation _ and the television cameras. That might be great for
his campaign against Democrat Michael Dukakis, but it didn't do
anything to improve our relations with Iran or bring peace to the
Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 18
   The Times of Trenton, N.J., on Dukakis-Jackson:
   Gov. (Michael) Dukakis made a mistake, we think, in not
personally notifying Jesse Jackson of (his vice presidential)
selection before it became public knowledge.
   The governor may well have been irritated by Jackson's refusal
to close down his campaign and by his public insistence that he had
somehow earned first refusal of the vice presidential nomination.
   Even so, by committing what Jackson and his followers can
interpret as a discourtesy, Dukakis has created a needless problem
for himself.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 18
   San Antonio (Texas) Express-News on the cost efficiency of
prisons:
   Tough prison sentences for hardened criminals serve the cause of
justice, but some fear that they cost more than taxpayers can
afford.
   A recent Justice Department study has some reassuring news:
Keeping repeat offenders behind bars actually is cheaper than
granting them early release.
   The department's research arm, the National Institute of
Justice, found that the average prisoner costs $25,000 a year _
including prison construction and maintenance expenses.
   But crimes committed by repeat offenders who have been freed
early cost about $430,000 a year in losses to victims and in
outlays for police, courts, etc.
   It is true that many prisons are overcrowded. The remedy is not
to turn their inmates loose, but to build more prisons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
