<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--Dukakis 3rdLd-Writethru a0664 07-20 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Dukakis, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0664,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Dukakis, One Race Ends But The Marathon Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 6 grafs new with Dukakis remarks at reception; pickup
graf 4 pvs, bgng, ``Later, speaking....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today called his successful quest
for the Democratic presidential nomination ``a real kick,'' saluted
the last of his campaign opponents and worked on the speech he will
deliver to party delegates and millions of American voters.
   Dukakis also delivered an anti-drug message and praised his
wife, Kitty, for her activism on behalf of the homeless and
refugees.
   ``This has been a real kick,'' Dukakis told a reception held in
honor of his wife.
   Dukakis, who called Jesse Jackson this morning and planned to
meet with him this afternoon, congratulated his rival for his
speech to the convention Tuesday night and also heaped praise on
Jackson's five children.
   ``I thought to myself just how lucky we are to have the families
we have,'' Dukakis said. ``And just how important this institution
we call the family is.''
   At a morning briefing, Christopher Edley, Dukakis' issues
director, said the acceptance speech Dukakis will give Thursday
would invoke the same theme the Masschusetts governor emphasized
during his campaign. ``We're going to let Dukakis be Dukakis,''
Edley said. It will focus on economic security and opportunity and
accuse Republicans of ``romantic attachment to the status quo in
both domestic and foreign policy,'' Edley said.
   Later, speaking to a youth club in nearby Conyers, Dukakis said
young people can lead the fight against drugs. ``You tell me what
you want me to do as president,'' he said.
   Dukakis arrived around noon at the Georgia governor's mansion
for lunch with Georgia Gov. Joe Frank Harris and other governors.
``I feel great,'' Dukakis said.e
   On Tuesday, Dukakis huddled with speechwriter Bill Woodward for
several hours reviewing a draft speech which senior aides said
contained an upbeat message focusing on economic opportunity and
praise for Jackson and Dukakis' chosen running mate, Texas Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen.
   Jackson's rousing speech and Texas Treasurer Ann Richards'
lively address to open the convention Monday will be tough acts to
follow for Dukakis, known for anything but his oratory.
   The nominee-to-be acknowledged that on Tuesday after touring the
Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Change with Bentsen
and Coretta Scott King, the widow of the slain civil rights leader.
   Neither he nor Bentsen, said Dukakis, ``have ever won any blue
ribbons for great oratory. ... None of us will meet the standard
Ann Richards and Jesse Jackson set for this convention.''
   Nevertheless, Dukakis promised leadership that would ``inspire
and uplift this country.''
   In a brief speech that included several quotations from King,
Dukakis described the civil rights leader as ``a man of action. He
was a man of inspiration.''
   Later, Dukakis met briefly at his hotel with Hispanic members of
Congress. Both Dukakis and Bentsen speak fluent Spanish, and Rep.
Albert Bustamante of Texas said Dukakis promised to involve
Hispanics in the campaign and in the transition team if he is
elected.
   ``He wanted to establish a dialogue with the leadership of the
Hispanic community in Congress,'' said Bustamante. ``We were real
pleased.''
   After that session Dukakis took a ``power walk'' with an aide in
Atlanta's Piedmont Park.
   Dukakis had dinner at the hotel with his wife before she and
their children attended the convention. Dukakis stepped out to a
fund-raiser before returning to the hotel to watch the Jackson
speech and to work on his own.
   With him at the fund-raiser was his Academy Award-winning
cousin, actress Olympia Dukakis, who will introduce the nominee to
the delegates Thursday night.
</TEXT>
