<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SwimmingBan     07-20 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swimming Ban,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Link To Lake Confirmed In Shigellosis Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lake was reopened today after scientists
found no remaining traces of bacteria that sickened at least 120
swimmers.
   Officials said they believe an infected swimmer defecating in
Beltzville Lake, not leaking sewage, introduced the shigella
bacteria, which causes shigellosis. Swimming at the reservoir has
been banned since July 12.
   Shigellosis typically causes acute diarrhea, fever and cramps
and can be fatal in people who were ill before contracting it. None
of the victims of the outbreak here has been in danger of dying,
health officials said.
   Health Department officials said the lake was contaminated July
8. Test results returned Tuesday revealed no traces of the
bacteria, said Department of Environmental Resources spokeswoman
Susan Woods.
   Water-borne shigella usually are killed by sunlight within a few
days, officials said.
   Ms. Woods said the state will continue twice-a-week testing of
the 949-acre reservoir.
   ``The common thread was that every person who tested positive
for shigellosis not only went swimming at Beltzville July 8, but
could recall either swallowing water or having water go up their
nose,'' said Health Department spokesman Bruce Reimer.
   While individual cases of shigellosis are fairly common, health
officials said outbreaks such as this are rare. The federal Centers
for Disease Control in Atlanta reported 12 outbreaks in the past 10
years.
</TEXT>
