<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Namibia-Attack 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Namibia-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0592,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Soldier Killed, 12 Injured In Grenade Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with SWAPO guerrillas claiming
responsibility. No pickup.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ One black soldier was killed
and 12 were seriously injured today when two grenades were thrown
into the back of their military vehicle, police said.
   Two unidentified men tossed the grenades into the rear of a
troop carrier as it was picking up the soldiers in Katutura, the
main township outside Windhoek, said police spokesman Kierie du
Rand.
   The South-West African People's Organization said in a dispatch
to the Mozambican news agency, AIM, that SWAPO guerrilla forces
were responsible for the attack.
   However, the SWAPO Press Agency said 24 soldiers were injured,
and it identified the dead solder as a South African. The SWAPO
release did not give the race of those it said were killed and
injured, but said the attack occurred in Katutura.
   The soldiers injured are part of the South-West Africa
Territorial Force. South Africa has administered South-West Africa,
also known as Namibia, for 73 years despite a 1978 U.N. resolution
calling for independence for the territory.
   SWAPO has been fighting against South African rule since 1966.
</TEXT>
