<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VoodooMayor     07-20 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Voodoo Mayor,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snake-Draped Mayor Kicks Off `National Voodoo Week'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor who faces an impeachment trial
proclaimed ``National Voodoo Week'' on Wednesday while wearing a
white turban and a red cape, but the state attorney general said
the ``voodoo antics'' show why he should be ousted.
   Florala Mayor H.T. Mathis, standing on the steps of the
Covington County Courthouse, read a proclamation at a midnight news
conference saying ``National Voodoo Week'' begins at midnight
Friday.
   Mathis, who faces an impeachment trial next month on charges of
mismanagement and improperly pardoning drunken drivers, stood in
front of a table that had candles, several Halloween masks and a
black rubber bat hanging on a string. Snakes were taped to his
shoulders.
   The 85-year-old first-term mayor said the publicity generated
last year when he sprinkled ``voodoo dust'' around Florala's City
Hall has been good for the town of 2,200 residents on the
Alabama-Florida border.
   ``The voodoo story, like a television commercial, has notified
thousands of people that Florala is a solid little town and it's
ideally located for any type of industry,'' Mathis said.
   But later Wednesday morning, Attorney General Don Siegelman made
it clear he wasn't amused.
   Mathis ``continues to be a threat to the public safety and an
embarrassment to the people of Florala and Covington County,''
Siegelman said, adding that the news conference ``demonstrates his
incompetence.''
   Siegelman said the ``voodoo antics'' ``may or may not be'' an
issue in his impeachment trial.
   Mathis accused Siegelman, who initiated the impeachment
proceedings, of ``trumping up the charges for his own political
gain.''
   Calling himself a Christian, Mathis said he does not believe in
black magic, but that since the media has turned him into the
``voodoo mayor'' he will use the opportunity for publicity.
   Siegelman has accused Mathis of mismanagement and improperly
pardoning more than two dozen drunken drivers. Mathis, who is
seeking a second term, said he has pardoned numerous driving
convictions because of what he calls overzealousness by city police.
   Siegelman asked a judge to impanel a county grand jury, which
brought the charges. A state court jury will hear the case. If he
is convicted, Mathis would be removed from office but would still
be able to run in this year's election.
   Sue Chambers, Mathis' daughter, said she was afraid her father's
credibility might be hurt. She said her father was making a mockery
of voodoo.
   ``I hope they will take it for what it's meant, but I don't know
that,'' she said.
   Regardless, Mathis said he planned to continue using voodoo.
   ``It's more or less fun. It's a joke. I do not believe in it, so
far as I'm concerned,'' said Mathis. ``Now there's a lot of
witchraft going on, though. There's a man (practicing it) just
across the Georiga line.''
</TEXT>
