<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WhiteHouse-Democrats     07-20 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House-Democrats,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Spokesman Defends Bush Against Democratic Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater on Wednesday defended his former boss, Vice President
George Bush, against the ``Where was George'' attacks of Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy and delegates to the Democratic convention in
Atlanta.
   Kennedy, D-Mass., repeatedly asked ``Where was George'' on
specific issues in a speech at the convention on Tuesday night,
prompting delegates to chant the same words in response.
   Fitzwater, who was Bush's press secretary before becoming White
House spokesman, commented, ``George was cutting taxes, not raising
them. George was defending America, not tearing it down. George was
leading the drug interdiction effort, not blowing smoke. And George
was pushing arms control, not cutting defense.''
   The spokesman declined comment, however, on an apparent
reference to first lady Nancy Reagan in the convention speech of
Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson.
   Jackson told the delegates that, in fighting drug abuse, it is
necessary to do more than ``just say no,'' Mrs. Reagan's anti-drug
slogan, or to consult an astrologer, as Mrs. Reagan has
acknowledged that she does on some matters.
   ``In the course of the convention, you are going to see all
kinds of hyperbole and outrage and silly statements from all of the
candidates and party members,'' Fitzwater said. ``That's what
conventions are all about, but we won't respond to them
individually.''
   Fitzwater said he did not know what parts, if any, of the
convention President and Mrs. Reagan had watched on television at
their ranch north of Santa Barbara, where they are vacationing. He
said he assumed they were watching parts of it.
</TEXT>
