<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DukakisGetsReady     07-20 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis Gets Ready,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Preparing Speech With Pen, Not Computer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Convention Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, often depicted as the high-tech
governor, used pen and paper to work on the words he would use to
accept the presidential nomination because he doesn't use a
personal computer, aides said Wednesday.
   Dukakis spent much of his private time during the Democratic
National Convention putting the speech through at least three major
drafts _ with the revisions entered into a word-processing computer
by aides.
   ``The governor does not use a computer,'' said Christopher
Edley, the campaign's issues director.
   ``I've only tried to get him to use a lap top (computer) once,''
he added. ``He humored me for three or four minutes, and that was
it.''
   Aides did not invite comparison to Jesse Jackson's emotionally
stirring speech of the night before _ except, Edley said, both
would prove to be ``kind of a greatest hits'' collection from
earlier campaign speeches.
   ``We're going to let Dukakis be Dukakis,'' Edley said.
   Ensconced in his penthouse hotel suite, Dukakis has been going
over triple-spaced drafts of the speech prepared by two aides,
penning changes between the lines, in the margins and on legal pads.
   Aides discussed Dukakis' preparations as the Massachusetts
governor was still at work on the speech he is to deliver Thursday
night. They said the final version was not yet prepared.
   Edley said Dukakis plans to place primary focus on creating
``economic opportunity and security'' for all Americans and also to
touch on ``redirecting'' foreign policy in areas such as Central
America and South Africa.
   He will criticize the Republicans for ``romantic attachment to
the status quo in both domestic and foreign policy,'' Edley said.
   But the speech is not planned as stridently partisan.
   ``It will be a positive speech,'' Edley said. ``There is not
going to be a harsh, partisan edge to it. That is not the Dukakis
style.''
   Aides said no surprises were planned and that he would to stick
to the basic themes and issues he commonly mentions: affordable
housing, quality education, health care and advance notice to
workers losing jobs because of plant closings.
   ``For much of the public that will be watching this speech, it
will be the first serious look at who Michael Dukakis is and where
he wants to take this country,'' Edley said. ``So an effort to
distill the essence of the candidacy is perfectly appropriate.''
   ``The message doesn't change from week to week; the themes don't
change from week to week,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
