<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--1992 Convention,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston Pushes for 1992 Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Houstonians on Wednesday cranked up their pitch
to host the 1992 Democratic National Convention. They also tried
not to sound pleased about the problems Atlanta is having.
   Officials locked the doors to The Omni arena Tuesday night
because of an overflow crowd that wanted to hear Jesse Jackson's
speech.
   On Wednesday, Houston officials were ready with a T-shirt
response in support of their 1992 bid.
   ``We have space for you in '92,'' said the shirts distributed to
Texas delegates to wear during the Wednesday night presidential
nomination vote.
   Back in Houston, Mayor Kathy Whitmire planned to attend a
convention watch party at the George R. Brown Convention Center,
the massive, new downtown building that Houston unsuccessfully
pitched for the 1988 convention.
   Don Ward of the Houston Convention and Visitors Bureau offered a
graphic comment on the relative merits of The Omni and the Houston
site.
   ``The George R. Brown would contain three Omnis. You could keep
all the press and everything under one roof,'' he said in Atlanta.
   The press is housed here in the Georgia World Congress Center
adjacent to The Omni.
   ``We'd like to show them what a real convention center looks
like,'' Ward said.
   Texas Democratic Chairman Bob Slagle said he did not want to
sound like an ungrateful guest here, but ...
   ``It's always embarrassing when anybody gets locked out of a
Democratic convention for any reason. We pride ourselves on
inclusion. It's a shame and I'm sorry it happened,'' he said of the
Tuesday night lockout.
   ``It's not the most useful hall we ever worked in,'' Slagle said
of The Omni. ``If you like being crammed in like a sardine, it's a
pretty nice place to be.''
   Claire Giesen of Houston, an aide to U.S. Rep. Mike Andrews, did
not complain about the weather as she handed out stickers that
feature a big blue ``92,'' which at times can seem like the average
humidity on a summer day in Houston.
   ``The weather has been great. Perfect weather,'' she said of the
hot, humid Atlanta days.
</TEXT>
