<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Appropriations     07-20 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Appropriations,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs $18 Billion Energy, Water Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed an $18
billion energy and water bill Wednesday and commended Congress for
enacting the measure promptly and holding spending to levels
acceptable to the administration.
   Reagan said in a statement that the bill had been submitted to
him earlier in the year than any other appropriation bill since he
took office in 1981. He urged the lawmakers to act quickly on the
remaining 12 appropriations bills.
   The bill is the first regular spending measure to get Reagan's
signature since December 1985.
   In recent years, appropriations bill have been lumped together
in catchall emergency spending measures enacted at the end of the
fiscal year. The bills are being enacted separately this year as a
result of last fall's deficit-reduction agreement between Reagan
and congressional leaders that decided in advance the overall
spending levels for military, foreign aid and domestic agency
programs.
   ``As I noted in my State of the Union address earlier this
year,'' Reagan said, ``the use of ... patched-together,
multiple-purpose spending bills does not permit the legislative and
executive branches to exercise proper scrutiny of government
spending.''
   ``The public interest is best served when budget laws are
enacted individually, after careful deliberation ... and well
before the crisis atmosphere sets in at the end of the fiscal year
in September,'' he said. ``I therefore urge the Congress to
complete consideration of the remaining 12 appropriations bills and
to transmit them to me in a timely manner as well.''
   Reagan said the appropriations in the energy and water bill ``do
not exceed the amounts I requested in my budget while fully funding
the essential requests for atomic energy defense activities.''
   ``I want to take this opportunity to commend the Congress ...
for keeping funding contained in this act at acceptable levels,''
he said.
   The bill was one of five signed by the president as he
vacationed at his mountaintop ranch north of Santa Barbara.
   The others were an authorization bill for the National
Transportation Safety Board, a codification of measures affecting
the Defense Department, a measure reauthorizing U.S. participation
in an international energy program, and a bill naming a federal
courthouse in Portland, Maine, for Judge Edward Gignoux.
</TEXT>
