<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-Contras     07-20 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Contras,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Unconcerned About Contra Tensions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman said
Wednesday that the Contras face a ``period of uncertainty'' but
that the election of Col. Enrique Bermudez to the directorate of
the Nicaraguan resistance will likely prove beneficial to the
Contra cause.
   Marlin Fitzwater also said that ``we would not expect his
becoming an official member of it to change the policies or
directions in any substantial way.''
   When asked about the resignations of seven commanders in the
resistance force's Southern Front in protest of Bermudez's
ascension to the top leadership post, Fitzwater replied, ``I don't
really know what the seven commander situation is in terms of
exactly what their status is now or how that will affect the
operations of the Contras themselves. ... I don't think there's
anything to worry about.''
   Fitzwater said that the leadership of the resistance force was
merely ``getting its act together'' and that the Contras face a
``period of uncertainty.''
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega has unilaterally extended a
cease-fire to Aug. 30, but at the same time, his Sandinista regime
recently cracked down on political opponents and expelled U.S.
Ambassador Richard Melton and seven associates.
   Seven commanders along the Contras southern military front quit
the organization Monday after Bermudez, 56, was elected to the
seven-member directorate of the resistance force.
   Bermudez was a colonel in President Anastasio Somoza's army
before Somoza was deposed by the Sandinistas in 1979.
   Fitzwater said that concerns about the colonel's past
connections with Somoza ``have always been there for anybody who
wanted to draw on them. The fact is, he has been the military
leader of the Contras. He has not hidden that fact.''
   The spokesman said the resistance force has some internal
problems because of ``Congress' cutoff of funds and the
uncertainties that they've faced in the peace process.'' He said it
appears that the Contra directorate ``is trying to fashion a course
as best they can at this point, and the election of Bermudez ...
should be helpful in the sense that he's been an integral part of
the military leadership all the way.''
</TEXT>
