<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SockAid     07-20 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sock Aid,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hosiery Group Cranking Out 100,000 Pairs Of Socks For Southeast's
Needy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hosiery industry group is cranking out
more than 100,000 pairs of socks to be distributed among the needy
this fall at hundreds of Salvation Army missions across the
Southeast.
   ``We always like to do things in a big way,'' said Clark Houck,
merchandise manager for Buster Brown Apparel Inc. in Chattanooga
and coordinator for the project ``No Cold Feet.''
   ``Last year we made the world's biggest sock. This year we're
going to have a lot of little socks for people that really need
them,'' he said Wednesday.
   Last year the Tennessee chapter celebrated National Hosiery Week
by hoisting a 65-foot sock, made by sewing together quilt-type
pieces donated by mills and hosiery-related companies, atop an arts
and community center in Morristown, Tenn.
   This year's project is the work of the Tennessee Chapter of the
National Association of Hosiery Manufacturers. The national
association and its chapters are composed of hosiery mills,
packagers, yarn suppliers and other businesses that deal with
hosiery.
   The 45 businesses in Tennessee's chapter consider the project
part of National Hosiery Week events scheduled for Aug. 14-20.
   The Tennessee chapter, Houck said, is aiming for the socks to
reach all 438 Salvation Army offices across the Southeast by early
fall, in time for the cold months ahead.
   This month, various mills began sending their donated socks to a
distribution point in Chattanooga for assembly into crates
containing 20 dozen pairs each. Each crate will have socks for
infants, children and adults, he said.
   Mills are sending a range of their products and specialties, not
just white tube socks, he said.
   ``It will be a veritable rainbow of socks,'' he added.
   ``Spinning plants are donating the yarn, printers are donating
their services and packagers the cartons. And, of course, the
manufacturers are knitting the socks,'' Houck said.
   The donated socks are destined for 14 states, Houck said. They
are Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Mississippi, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee,
Texas, Virginia and West Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
