<DOCNO> AP880720-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--RepublicanVersion     07-20 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Republican Version,640</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>GOP Leaders Make it Clear They're Running Against `Troika'
^By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders made it clear Wednesday that
they plan to direct their fall political attack against a
Democratic ``troika'' that includes Jesse Jackson as well as
Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen.
   Illinois Gov. James Thompson said Michael Dukakis granted
Jackson virtually the same status in the campaign as he did
Bentsen, the Texas senator he has picked to be his vice
presidential running mate.
   ``Governor Dukakis has accepted Jesse Jackson as his partner in
this campaign, elevated him to a position equal to or perhaps
higher than his nominal running mate Lloyd Bentsen,'' Thompson said.
   Thompson called it a clever strategy to offer Bentsen as ``the
soothing, reassuring conservative.'' But he said, ``My guess is
those two partners of the troika, Dukakis and Jackson, will soon
leave Bentsen in the dust.''
   Thompson's comments came as part of a Republican ``truth squad''
which has held dailing news conferences this week in Atlanta to
present the GOP side of things during the Democratic convention.
Thompson was joined by Virginia Sen. John Warner and Texas Rep.
Beau Boulter, who is running against Bentsen for the Senate.
   All used the term ``troika'' to describe the Democratic ticket,
repeatedly mentioning Jackson, who most polls show hurts Democratic
chances in the fall campaign against certain nominee George Bush.
   ``Michael Dukakis has tied Jesse Jackson to this ticket rather
firmly,'' Thompson said. ``With Bentsen whispering in one ear and
Jackson whispering in his other ear, who is Dukakis going to listen
to? ... I think that's the question the American people need to
have answered.''
   Thompson himself has been mentioned as a potential running mate
for Bush, but he downplayed any suggestions that he was campaigning
for the job.
   ``There are a number of qualified candidates,'' Thompson said.
``There's no lack of talent in our party.''
   In addition to being Dukakis' pick for the No. 2 spot on the
ticket, Bentsen is running for re-election to his Senate seat,
simultaneous campaigns that are allowed under Texas law.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen wants it both ways,'' Boulter said, contending
that Bentsen should ``have the courage to decide which office he
wants to run for.''
   The selection of Bentsen as a running mate is viewed as an
effort to cut into Republican strength in the South, but Boulter
said Republicans will make sure the conservative Texan is saying
the same things in all regions of the nation.
   ``In the other 49 states, he's going to have to campaign, I
suppose, on Michael Dukakis' platform,'' Boulter said. ``I expect
him to say different things in Texas, to the voters there, than
he's saying in the other 49 states.''
   Boulter also repeated GOP attacks on Bentsen for the $6 million
campaign chest he's built for his Senate race, arguing that money
will be spent instead to boost the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket.
   Warner, ranking Republican on the Senate Armed Services
Committee, attacked Democrats for the platform they adopted on
Tuesday.
   ``The defense platform, indeed, is a smokescreen,'' Warner said.
``Clearly we're seeing deception in the areas of national defense
and foreign policy.''
   In another attack on the Democrats, L. Brent Bozell, executive
director of the Conservative Victory Committee, previewed planned
television ads criticizing Dukakis for his 1977 veto of a bill
requiring school children to recite the pledge of allegiance.
   ``He's a 100 percent dyed-in-the-wool bleeding heart liberal
who's completely out of touch with the American public,'' Bozell
told a news conference.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
