<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--MissingDynamite     07-20 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Missing Dynamite,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Still Looking For Stolen Dynamite In Convention City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement authorities in the city playing
host to the Democratic National Convention searched a second day
Wednesday for 100 pounds of dynamite stolen from a suburban
blasting company.
   Although police said there was no indication the theft was
related to the convention, which has brought an estimated 35,000
visitors, the FBI said it was giving the matter more than routine
attention.
   ``We're not treating it as a run-of-the-mill thing,'' said
Atlanta agent Diader Rosario. ``Any time you have a situation where
explosives have been stolen, certainly it is a very serious
matter.''
   Police spokeswoman Myrna May said there had been several
reported sightings of a tan van that was used to transport the
dynamite.
   One was near the state Capitol and another was near The Omni,
where the convention is being held, she said. On Wednesday, bomb
squad officers were searching tan vans in the convention zone.
   Rosario said the FBI was aware of a reported threat to blow up
an abortion clinic, but added, ``I don't have any (further)
information regarding that.''
   Henry County sheriff's Capt. Keith McBrayer said two cases of
explosives were stolen Tuesday from a blasting company worker. Each
case contained 50 pounds of dynamite, or about 200 sticks, and 200
blasting caps, he said.
   Besides the FBI, the Georgia Bureau of Investigation, the Secret
Service and the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
joined police from Atlanta and Henry County in searching for the
explosives.
</TEXT>
