<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Khomeini     07-20 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khomeini,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini says Accepting Cease-fire Like Drinking Poison</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini told his
people Wednesday accepting a truce with Iraq was like drinking
poison, but asked them to support his decision and said those
``martyred'' by the war had benefited.
   Until this week Khomeini had been adamant in opposing an end to
the war, which began in September 1980 with border skirmishes and
an Iraqi invasion, until President Saddam Hussein of Iraq was
driven from power.
   ``I shall say again that the acceptance of this issue is more
deadly to me than poison, but I am happy to submit to God's will
and drank this cup for his satisfaction,'' the 87-year-old
revolutionary patriarch said in a statement.
   Although the statement said he could not immediately reveal the
reasons for changing his mind, it said he acted on the
recommendation of military and political leaders. Khomeini's
statement was his first since the government said Monday it would
accept a year-old, U.N. cease-fire resolution.
   ``In view of the opinion of all high-ranking political and
military experts ... I agreed with the acceptance of the resolution
and cease-fire, and under the existing juncture I believe this to
be in the interest of the revolution and the system,'' he said. His
statement was distributed by Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency which was monitored in Nicosia.
   Iran's acceptance of U.N. Resolution 598 does not mean the war
is over, Khomeini said, but added that the decision was not just a
tactic to allow the Iranian military to regroup. Iraq has made that
accusation.
   He said the war had been ``good for the people who were martyred
and good for those whose children were martyred.'' Western
estimates put the number of dead and wounded in the 8-year-old
conflict at 1 million, divided about evenly between the two sides.
   Shiite Moslems, the overwhelming majority in Iran, revere the
martyrdom of the Prophet Mohammed's grandson Hussein in 680, in an
Islamic factional war from which the Sunni and Shiite branches of
the faith developed.
   Khomeini repeated several times that he did not want to accept
the resolution and said he felt ``ashamed in front of such a great
nation.'' He also told the public and media not to create a furor
over questions that would not be answered immediately.
   The patriarch said Iran has yet to settle accounts with the
United States, which he calls the ``great Satan,'' and with Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait.
   ``I hereby warn the American and European military forces to
leave the Persian Gulf before it is too late,'' he declared,
without elaboration. About 60 foreign warships are stationed in and
around the gulf, 27 of them American.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
