<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1603EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Cable     07-20 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Cable,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Moves Toward Phone-Company Cable TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission moved a
step closer Wednesday toward allowing telephone companies to
provide cable television services.
   An 18-year-old FCC rule and a 4-year-old law bar telephone
companies from running cable systems in their own service areas,
but the FCC indicated by a series of actions Wednesday it favors
lifting those prohibitions.
   The commission called the prohibitions a draconian form of
regulation that no longer is needed because the cable industry has
become large and strong enough to compete with the telephone
companies.
   The FCC voted tentatively to recommend to Congress that it
repeal the 1984 prohibition against telephone companies providing
cable television services and directed its staff to begin the
process of repealing its own rule against such activity.
   It also asked the staff to formally define what would be ``good
cause'' for waivers of the prohibition as allowed by the law and
the rule. By that action, the commission indicated that it could
use waivers to allow telephone companies into the cable television
business even if the l984 law is not rescinded.
   If telephone companies are allowed to operate cable systems the
consumer will benefit from increased video services, including home
shopping and video phones, as well as having an additional source
of pay television programming, the commission said.
   James P. Mooney, president of the National Cable Television
Association, suggested that consumers' basic phone bills would
increase if the telephone companies delve into cable television.
   ``Consumers ... would find themselves forced to subsidize
high-risk investments in pay TV. The only certain results would be
to push telephone rates even higher than they are now,'' he said in
a statement.
   While it will be up to Congress to lift its prohibition and the
FCC is not expected to develop a final recommendation to Capitol
Hill until later this year, the commission made clear it believes
the existing prohibitions are out of date.
   Cable companies can serve about 80 percent of the homes in the
nation, the commission said.
   Thus, in contrast to 1970 when the commission rule was adopted,
telephone companies no longer can ``enjoy the advantage of being
the first provider of cable television service or preemptively
eliminate competition from independent cable operators,'' the
commission said.
   There is a ``general consensus'' among the FCC commissioners
that the current prohibitions against cable-telephone cross
ownership ``are no longer the most appropriate or most desirable
form of regulation,'' Gerald Brooks, chief of the FCC's common
carrier bureau, told reporters.
</TEXT>
