<1ST_LINE>u p PM-CVN--ConventionRdp 7thLd-Writethru a0752 07-20 1125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Convention Rdp, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0752,1180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Hours Before Nomination, Says ``It's for Real''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson comment after meeting, subbing 3 grafs
for grafs 6-7 pvs, Just hours ... meeting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, saying ``I think it's for
real,'' was poised to win the Democratic presidential nomination
tonight in a prime-time roll call of delegates energized by waves
of ridicule directed at George Bush.
   ``This has been a real kick,'' Dukakis said this afternoon,
looking back over a 17-month quest for the nomination and the right
to challenge Republican Bush in November.
   Standing alongside his wife, Kitty, at a reception, the
Massachusetts governor said, ``As we we came into Atlanta on
Sunday, I turned to my bride and I said, `Well, I think it's for
real. I mean this is happening.''' The audience cheered.
   Both Dukakis and Jesse Jackson, survivors from a field of seven,
will have their names entered in nomination. Dukakis began the day
with a commanding 2,763 delegates, compared to 1,161 for Jackson
and had exercised his muscle by winning a brief and moderate
platform.
   Jackson, who captivated the convention with a forceful address
Tuesday night, acknowledged the obvious this morning. Asked if he
planned to endorse and work for the ticket, he said, ``Oh, yes I
am.'' He said his role ``must be defined by Gov. Dukakis.''
   Just hours before tonight's convention session, the two
candidates met privately in Dukakis' hotel suite for more than an
hour, accompanied by senior aides and Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
Dukakis' running mate.
   Afterward, Jackson said, ``Basically it was a get-acquainted
meeting for staff and key policy advisers, most of whom do not know
each other but now must work together since we are in the same boat
with a common objective _ that is, to win in November.''
   Jackson added: ``As you end the primary campaign, you fold in
some means of becoming friends, developing new and different
relationships.''
   Earlier, Dukakis toured the Omni convention hall, trying out the
podium where he will deliver his acceptance speech Thursday night.
Dukakis aides said the governor was still working on the address,
which has gone through multiple drafts.
   Christopher Edley, campaign issues director, said Dukakis would
focus on economic security and opportunity and would accuse the
Republicans of ``romantic attachment to the status quo in both
domestic and foreign policy.''
   ``We're going to let Dukakis be Dukakis,'' Edley said.
   At the afternoon reception, Dukakis spoke warmly of his wife and
said both he and Jackson were blessed with good families.
   He said a woman in tobacco-rich North Carolina told him recently
she planned to vote for him. When he asked why, she replied: ``Your
wife smokes.''
   Making clear he wasn't happy about the fact that his wife does
smoke, Dukakis said, ``I don't have to tell you what kind of first
lady she's going to be: a non-smoking first lady.'' Again, the
audience laughed.
   Earlier, the nominee-in-waiting telphoned Jackson and told him,
``I thought the speech was terrific.''
   Dukakis spent part of the morning at a youth club in Conyers
outside Atlanta discussing the battle against illegal drugs. He
said young people can be the best helpers in that effort and he
told the youngsters, ``You tell me what you want me to do as
president.''
   Dukakis, who has spent much of his time the past several days at
his hotel headquarters, said, ``The problem with being a candidate
is they never let you out of the hotel room, so this is a joy to
me.''
   Jackson, even though he is certain to lose, said he wants his
name placed in nomination ``as a testament to the struggles of our
fathers and mothers.''
   He said today that his ``mission'' was to pave the way for a
black to win the White House.
   ``My children and your children will get through those doors,
and the White House is within reach,'' he told NBC's Bryant Gumbel,
the ``Today'' show's black anchorman. ``I am pushing back barriers
and removing ceilings off of dreams every day. I see it as my
obligation, in a real sense now my mission.''
   Jackson had his night in the spotlight Tuesday, delivering a
graceful swan song before a noisy and excited house. Citing
dangerous overcrowding, police sealed all entrances to the Omni
shortly before Jackson spoke, locking out about 1,000 delegates,
guests and reporters.
   Inside the hall, Jackson declared, ``We meet tonight at a
crossroads, a point of decision. Shall we expand, be inclusive,
find unity and power, or suffer division and impotence?
   ``The only time we win is when we come together,'' Jackson said,
as his supporters waved a sea of red banners proclaiming,
``Jesse.'' On orders from Dukakis' floor leaders, the governor's
supporters kept their own blue-colored placards out of sight.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and other speakers trained
their sights on Vice President Bush, the certain nominee when the
Republicans convene next month in New Orleans.
   Kennedy derided Bush as the man who ``keeps burying his head in
his hands and hiding from the record of the Reagan-Bush mistakes.''
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower told the delegates
that Bush was a ``toothache of a man'' who doesn't care about the
problems of anyone but the rich.
   ``George has always been in another world. His is an upper-class
world in which wealth is given to you at birth,'' Hightower said.
``He is a man who was born on third base and thinks he hit a
triple.''
   The convention already had rebuffed Jackson's calls for higher
taxes on the wealthy and a pledge to reject the first use of
nuclear weapons. Instead, delegates approved a Dukakis-endorsed
platform worded in such general terms that it won't provide much of
a target for Republicans.
   Showing no sign of defeat, Jackson told the delegates, ``Tonight
I salute Gov. Michael Dukakis. He has run a well-managed and
dignified campaign. No matter how tired or how tried, he always
resisted the temptation to stoop to demagoguery.''
   Jackson said, ``His foreparents came to American in immigrant
ships. My foreparents came to American in slave ships.
   ``But whatever the original ships, we are in the same boat
tonight.''
   ``Keep hope alive! Keep hope alive! Keep hope alive,'' he
shouted in conclusion, sparking an eruption of cheers and applause.
   As the party's nominee, Dukakis will face Bush, the target
during the second night of the convention of verbal abuse from some
of the Democrats' top stars.
   Bush emerges today from the seclusion of a fishing trip in
Wyoming to go on the campaign trail and try to divert attention
from Dukakis' triumph. The vice president will campaign in the
Detroit area in the first stop on an eight-state tour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
