<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FDA-Sulfites Bjt   07-20 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FDA-Sulfites, Bjt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Rejects Appeals to Broaden Ban on Sulfites In Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unpublished memo written by the head of the
Food and Drug Administration shows the agency wants to reject
proposals for broader limitations on sulfite food preservatives,
despite estimates that the chemicals can be extremely dangerous to
a million or more Americans.
   A consumer health group said Wednesday the FDA's failure to act
endangers many asthmatics and others who have a severe reaction to
sulfites, including the possibility of death within hours after
food containing the chemicals is eaten.
   Sulfites, which have been used for decades to prevent
discoloration in food, have been banned since 1986 for use on fresh
fruits and vegetables, such as those sold in salad bars. Fresh
potatoes have been exempted from the ban, but will be included
later this year, FDA officials say.
   The FDA memo, written by Commissioner Frank E. Young, says the
agency proposes to affirm its classification of sulfites as
``generally recognized as safe'' for other foods. Young
acknowledges in the document that many new uses have been found for
sulfites and that ``a significant number of individuals'' have
experienced ``severe allergic-type responses.''
   Other FDA officials have estimated that sulfites are dangerous
to about 10 percent of the 10 million people in the United States
with asthma and to a small number of non-asthmatics, according to
agency spokesman Chris Lecos.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest, a privately
funded consumer health group, says sulfites have caused coma, brain
damage and at least five deaths.
   Young's memo says that a 1987 sulfite labeling requirement for
some packaged foods would be extended to additional items, but not
to dehydrated or frozen potatoes, which would remain exempt.
   Under existing rules all drugs must be labeled as to sulfite
content.
   The June 20 memo was addressed to Health and Human Services
Secretary Otis Bowen, whose department must sign off on over 100
pages of regulations that accompanied the document.
   Mitch Zeller, staff attorney for the consumer group, predicted
that the FDA's position would be approved by Health and Human
Services, saying it ``does so little and bends over backwards to
placate the food industry.''
   Lecos said the FDA had no comment on the memo. Nancy Tiller of
the FDA's executive secretariat, acknowledged the existence of the
memo but said it was not for public release. The Associated Press
obtained a copy from a source outside the agency.
   The memo said the FDA had considered prohibiting all uses of
sulfites in food, broadening the ban to include other foods or
requiring labeling of all sulfite-treated food used in restaurants.
   The memo says ``the available safety data'' does not support a
complete ban or an extension to foods other than those already
covered, except for fresh potatoes. Health groups have said it
should also cover processed and frozen potatoes.
   Restaurant labeling would be ``labor intensive and difficult to
enforce,'' the memo says, adding that it would require regular
inspection of over 500,000 eating establishments.
   The memo asks for action on the proposed regulations by July 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-HamadiTrial     07-20 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says Hamadi Admitted Being A Member of Hezbollah</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigator testified
Wednesday that a Lebanese Shiite Moslem charged in the hijacking of
a TWA jet admitted joining a radical group linked to the
kidnappings of Westerners in Beirut.
   The defendant, Mohammed Ali Hamadi, told the court trying him
that he hates the United States, which sought his extradition.
   Hamadi is charged with air piracy and murder in the June 1985
hijacking of TWA flight 847 to Beirut. Thirty-nine Americans were
held captive for 17 days, and a U.S. Navy diver was killed during
the ordeal.
   West German federal police investigator Heinrich Brandtjen said
Hamadi admitted joining the radical Hezbollah group after the TWA
hijacking.
   Hamadi was arrested and charged with carrying liquid explosives
at Frankfurt Airport in 1987.
   ``He told me he has belonged to Hezbollah since the autumn of
1985 or 1986, but I cannot remember exactly the year,'' Brandtjen
told the court.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is believed to be the umbrella
organization for pro-Iranian groups holding 18 foreign hostages in
Lebanon, including nine Americans. Hamadi denied last week that he
had been a member of Hezbollah.
   One of Hamadi's brothers, Abdul-Hadi Hamadi, is the Beirut
security chief of Hezbollah. Another brother is accused of
kidnapping two West Germans in Lebanon in a bid to force German
authorities to free Mohammed Hamadi.
   When Brandtjen was asked if Mohammed Hamadi's actions were
linked to those of his brother Abdul-Hadi, Brandtjen said: ``He
told me that he had stood under the orders of his brother,
Abdul-Hadi Hamadi... He told me his brother was not directly
involved in military operations of Hezbollah, but had a mediating
role between rival factions.''
   During the time the questioning was taking place, the West
Germans were coming under pressure from Washington to extradite
Hamadi to the United States, a request which was ultimately turned
down.
   When Hamadi was given a copy of the U.S. extradition request,
Brandtjen quoted him as saying, ``I had nothing to do with that
(hijacking).''
   In his testimony last week, Hamadi said his admissions to
Brandtjen came as a result of threats by West German authorities to
extradite him to the United States unless he confessed. Brandtjen
said no threats were made against Hamadi.
   The defendant also read from a statement he started Tuesday and
criticized U.S. policy in the Middle East.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger asked him: ``Do you hate the
U.S.A.?''
   ``I grew up in Lebanon in the middle of the war, and one
naturally asks himself _ why? The answer was always America, or
Israel with support of America,'' Hamadi replied. ``I have hateful
feelings for all that attacked us, not just for the U.S.A. alone,''
Hamadi said through an interpreter.
   Abbas Hamadi, 29, was arrested Jan. 26, 1987, at Frankfurt
Airport when he returned after the kidnappings of West Germans
Rudolf Cordes and Alfred Schmidt in Beirut. Schmidt was freed in
September, but Cordes remains a hostage.
   Abbas Hamadi was convicted in April of masterminding the
kidnappings in a bid to force his brother's release and sentenced
to 13 years in prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
