<1ST_LINE>u i BC-UN-Airliner     07-20 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UN-Airliner,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Security Council Adopts Resolution On U.S. Downing of Iranian
Jetliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council on Wednesday
unanimously adopted a mild resolution expressing ``deep distress''
over the accidental U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner and urging
rapid implementation of a U.N. cease-fire and peace plan.
   After days of negotiations and bargaining, the 15-member council
adopted a watered-down document that would satisfy both the United
States and Iran and would not provoke a U.S. veto.
   The council session was requested by Iran, which had boycotted
the council for eight years but returned to urge condemnation of
the U.S. military action and demand withdrawal of all U.S. forces
from the Persian Gulf.
   The USS Vincennes shot down the Iran Air jetliner on July 3 in
the gulf, killing all 290 people aboard. The United States said the
airliner was mistaken for an Iranian fighter jet.
   Iran was unable to muster enough votes to condemn the United
States.
   Diplomats said the council decided to delete controversial
passages to ensure passage of the brief resolution. It deleted a
sentence proposed by Iran calling on foreign naval forces to
reassess their presence in the Persian Gulf. It also deleted strong
language of condemnation of the U.S. military action.
   The resolution said the council ``expresses its deep distress at
the downing of an Iranian civil aircraates to be in their seats promptly
at the 7
p.m. EDT starting hour. More than a thousand people were locked out
on Wednesday night when authorities shut the coliseum doors due to
overcrowding.
   Thus was the stage set for the most peaceful nominating night
the Democrats have known since 1976 _ a result entirely unlike the
tumultuous brokered convention scenarios that were fashionable in
Washington political salons when the campaign year began.
   Dukakis made short order of those scenarios, as he did of his
rivals. He won the bronze medal when the first votes were counted
in the Iowa caucuses on a freezing cold night in February, but won
the gold in the New Hampshire primary the following week and
methodically began piling up delegates, first by the handful and
later by the hundreds.
   It was a success that capped a remarkable political comeback.
Elected governor of Massachusetts in 1974, he lost a re-election
bid in a primary campaign four years later in what his wife termed
a ``public death.''
   He renewed himself in his four years out of power, and has twice
won statehouse terms since.
   The Massachusetts governor went into the roll call with 2,798
delegates according to The Associated Press count, to 1,168 for
Jackson. That was hundreds more than the 2,082 needed to win.
   By day three the convention city had settled into a routine,
from the street vendors hawking everything from T-shirts to jars of
vidalia onion relish to the demonstrators showcasing their causes
in a parking lot set aside for them a few blocks from the hall.
   The security detail seemed large beyond numbers, from the Secret
Service to the Georgia state troopers, to the Atlanta city police
to the private security guards _ and more.
   Dukakis, the man at the center of it all, telephoned Jackson to
tell him, ``I thought the speech was terrific.''
   Aides said Dukakis had tried to reach Jackson the night before
at the podium but couldn't get through. There was irony in that _
Dukakis said last week he tried and failed to reach Jackson to tell
him of Bentsen's selection as running mate, but Jackson felt he had
been snubbed when he learned the news from a reporter.
   The result was an outbreak of political tension that wasn't
resolved until Dukakis and Jackson met privately for more than two
hours before the convention's opening session on Monday.
   But that was then, and this time, no one seemed to care if
Dukakis couldn't get his call through.
   Aides said Dukakis was polishing the acceptance speech that he
will deliver at the convention's final session Thursday night, and
would watch the nominating roll call on television in his hotel
suite with his family.
   At the luncheon for his wife, he chided her about her smoking
habits, and said she would make a great first lady _ a ``no smoking
first lady.''
   He added that when he arrived in Atlanta last Sunday to claim
his prize, he had told her, ``This is a kick...I think it's for
real, I mean it's happening.''
   In an interview on NBC's ``Today'' program, Jackson said his
mission was to pave the way for a black to someday reach the White
House. ``My children and your children will get through those
doors,'' he told Bryant Gumbel, NBC's black anchorman.
   Democrats who fell by the campaign wayside admitted to some
thoughts of what might have been, even though they rallied behind
the winner.
   ``Obviously there are mixed feelings,'' confessed Illinois Sen.
Paul Simon, whose own campaign ended during the spring.
   ``Reach for the hand of your fellow Democrat and hold on tight.
We're going to make this country over again,'' said Rep. Richard
Gephardt, who won the Iowa caucuses but quit the race a month later.
   Among the delegates, the talk was of a healed party and unity
for the fall campaign, and of Jackson's 45-minute speech on
Wednesday night.
   ``I think it was very stimulating, very conciliatory, and very
much what the party needs,'' said Chicago Alderman Juan Soliz, a
Dukakis backer.
   Ron Yengich, an alternate from Utah, was so moved by Jackson's
Tuesday night speech that he took a midnight detour on his way back
to his hotel, driving by the birthplace of slain civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr.
</TEXT>
