<1ST_LINE>u a AM-US-Gulf     07-20 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lingering Skirmishes Expected, Fitzwater Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman said
Wednesday the administration was not surprised by lingering
skirmishes in the Iran-Iraq war, voicing hope that it is merely a
prelude to a cease-fire.
   ``The fighting, of course, is continuing there, as I think
everyone assumed it would,'' said spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Briefing reporters at his seaside resort while Reagan continued
his week-long vacation, Fitzwater said, ``I think everyone assumed
it would continue until the cease-fire. ... So I think we should
all assume that the war is receding and we can expect skirmishes
until the cease-fire is agreed to.''
   Fitzwater commented not long after United Nations Secretary
General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced he was dispatching a team
to Iran and Iraq to seek implementation of a ceasefire under U.N.
Security Council Resolution 598.
   Iran's government had announced Monday for the first time that
it was unconditionally accepting the cease-fire resolution. But on
Tuesday, Iraq bombed an Iranian nuclear power plant and hit other
Iranian industrial targets.
   Fitzwater said the administration welcomed Iraq's move to hold
direct talks with Iran as soon as possible on establishing a
cease-fire in the nearly 8-year-old war.
   Iraq's deputy foreign minister, Tariq Aziz, made the proposal in
a message to Perez de Cuellar.
   On another matter, Fitzwater reiterated that the United States
is interested in improving relations with Iran, but he said this is
not related to the continued captivity of eight Americans held
hostage by pro-Iranian elements in Iran.
   The spokesman said the administration was continuing to do
everything possible to win the release of the hostages but said
``we don't believe there should be any linkage'' of the
hostage-holding with the possible renewal of contacts with Iranian
government officials.
   ``We have had that signal out for a number of months ... and
whenever we have pressed them for names or assurances that there
were authoritative persons (with whom the U.S. could do business),
we didn't hear back,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said he thought that it had been ``at least a couple
of months'' since the United States made any attempt at direct
contacts with Iranian officials.
   ``We have continued to say that we're open to it, but it is up
to Iran, and that's where the ball is now,'' he said.
   Fitzwater has said in the past that the United States insists on
dealing with Iranians who can speak authoritatively for the
revolutionary goverment of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   The spokesman said U.S. officials would have to be convinced of
the legitimacy of any Iranians who might be contacted because the
administration wants no repetitions of the Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
