<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--ForWomenOnly     07-20 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--For Women Only,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Some Delegates, Looking for Women to Talk About Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While other delegates to the Democratic National
Convention were shopping, sunbathing, eating lunch with mayors or
taking pictures of each other, Dorothy Eck and Helen Kerr were
engaged in more serious pursuits.
   They were talking with other women about problems facing women.
   ``We're here today,'' said Mrs. Kerr, ``because we suddenly
realized we are tired of listening to men.''
   When delegates look at the podium in the convention hall, she
said, all they see is men _ men keeping track of time, men ushering
in visitors, men orchestrating the playing or non-playing of music
and men hitting the buttons to move the podium up and down in order
to make 6-foot-2 Jesse Jackson and 5-foot-8 Michael Dukakis the
same height.
   She explained that she has no quarrel with the Democratic Party,
which is scrupulous about dividing delegate representation evenly
between men and women. She thinks, too, that women are well
represented among speakers.
   But, well, there is that pervasive presence of men _ especially
in the daytime caucuses and on the platform.
   ``This morning, when we were planning our day, Dorothy said
let's find some women to listen to,'' said Mrs. Kerr.
   That's how they wound up miles from the delegate-clogged
downtown area at a branch library where there was a ``Southern
Hospitality, Women's Style, Welcome Delegates'' meeting.
   Ms. Eck and Mrs. Kerr are from Bozeman, Mont., both are in their
60s, and they belie the image of the carousing, fun-loving delegate
who may or may not find time to make it into the convention hall.
   From early in the morning, when they attend a meeting of the
Montana delegation, to after 11 at night when the convention ends,
the two women are on the go. They went to a Democratic National
Committee seminar, then a session of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference and after the women's meeting were going to
visit a musum. All this before a convention session lasting five
hours or more.
   ``We've got a choice of 20 places to go,'' said Ms. Eck, a state
senator who headed the Dukakis campaign in Montana.
   ``I was married to a regular Army officer and didn't open my
mouth,'' said Mrs. Kerr. ``Then I worked for the federal government
and didn't open my mouth. Now it's my turn to act.''
   She was particularly impressed with Geraldine Ferraro, the 1984
Democratic vice presidential nominee, who told a caucus Tuesday
that the reason more women aren't considered for national office is
because so few are running for other posts and working their way
through the system.
   Has she run for office?
   No, said Mrs. Kerr. ``I haven't the guts for it. I want
everybody to think I'm wonderful; it would hurt too much to find
out some people didn't think so.''
  
</TEXT>
