<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Richards Returns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Richards Finds Attention Embarrassing, Looses Wit Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st 2 grafs with 1 graf to RESTORE dropped words, FIX
punctuation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Treasurer Ann Richards said Wednesday that
all the attention generated by her keynote speech to the Democratic
National Convention is ``a little embarrassing'' _ and proceeded to
once again turn her acid wit on Vice President George Bush.
   Speaking to a meeting of women activists, Ms. Richards recounted
being asked by a reporter why women seem reluctant to support Bush,
who is the certain Republican nominee for president.
   ``I said it was very hard to explain unless you've ever gone to
a high school dance and looked at the stag line and there was that
guy raising his eyebrows at you and you said to yourself, `Oh Lord,
I hope he doesn't ask me,''' Ms. Richards said.
   On the opening night of this year's convention, Ms. Richards
unleashed a stinging attack on Bush, saying among other things that
he was ``born with a silver foot in his mouth.''
   Since that crowd-pleasing speech, Ms. Richards has been the
focus of heavy attention around the convention and on Wednesday,
she quoted some advice given to her by veteran feminist Bella
Abzug: ``You just lean back and enjoy it.''
   ``I find all the attention a little embarrassing,'' she said.
``I know who I am.''
   In addition, Ms. Richards dismissed with a joke suggestions from
admirers that she was vice presidential material.
   ``I am not prepared to be vice president,'' she said. ``I need a
lot more seasoning, I need a lot more experience, I need a lot more
broadening.
   ``I really know what my talents are,'' she said. ``I hope my
future is full of wonderful things. I think being vice president
would be great. I'm good at weddings, I'm good at funerals.''
   Ms. Richards also attacked the Reagan administration's record on
women's issues, pointing to small gains women have made in income
compared to men.
   In a voice dripping with sarcasm, she said: ``In eight years
it's almost a 5 percent increase. How can we possibly complain?
   ``As usual, it is up to the women to clean up the mess,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
