<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DukakisNotebook     07-20 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis Notebook,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Rare Joke, An Oversized Shirt, New Signs And A Road Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, in an unusually jovial mood as
he prepared to be crowned his party's presidential nominee, cracked
a joke about his wife's smoking habit _ perhaps costing himself a
vote in North Carolina.
   At a luncheon reception for Kitty Dukakis hosted by the
Democratic National Committee, Dukakis spoke of a North Carolina
woman who approached him and promised her support.
   Dukakis said he asked the reason for the endorsement and was
told: ``Your wife smokes.''
   ``I don't have to tell you what kind of first lady she is going
to be,'' Dukakis said as his wife stood at his side. ``A
non-smoking first lady,'' he added, winning laughter from the crowd.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis, known for his thriftiness, tried in vain Wednesday to
return a gift T-shirt because he said it was too big.
   After an anti-drug rally in Conyers, not far from the convention
city, the trim Dukakis was presented with a shirt bearing the logo
of the local Boys Club. As he held it up for photographers, Dukakis
glanced down at the tag.
   ``I hate to look a gift horse in the mouth,'' he said, ``but I'd
love to wear this this afternoon when I'm working out in Piedmont
Park. It's an extra large and that's a little big on me. If you've
got something a little smaller I could wear it.''
   Organizers of the event looked on awkwardly, as did Dukakis'
wife, Kitty, who also received a shirt from the local Girls Club.
   Dukakis kept the shirt.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   At a made-for-TV convention, the Dukakis campaign has flooded
The Omni arena with made-for-TV signs.
   Gone are the placards the campaign has used for more than a
year. They were predominantly white with blue lettering that read:
``Mike Dukakis for President.''
   The new signs match the red, white and blue colors of the
convention rostrum. The have large lettering reading, ``DUKAKIS,''
and a smaller tag line that reads ``President '88.''
   And they come in two sizes.
   Two people are needed to wave the larger signs effectively,
while a lone supporter can handle the smaller models.
   All told, 1,000 of the larger versions have been distributed on
the Omni floor, and 20,000 of the smaller models.
   Another Dukakis sign is to be unveiled Wednesday night as
Dukakis is nominated for the presidency. It says: ``Duke. Duke
Duke.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After spending five days in steamy Atlanta, Dukakis and his
running mate, Lloyd Bentsen, will hit the campaign trail together
for three days.
   The first stops will be Bentsen's home state of Texas Friday.
After appearances in McAllen and Houston, the pair will fly to
Modesto, Calif., and spend the night there.
   On Saturday they will campaign in Minot, N.D., and St. Louis.
The next day they will appear in Erie, Pa., before returning to
Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
