<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Three in West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with third death. PICKS up 4th
graf pvs bgng, Two small groups ... SUBS grafs 13-15 pvs, The
Palestinian killed...Palestinians wounded. with 3 grafs to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops killed three Palestinians
Wednesday in clashes in the occupied West Bank, while hundreds of
policemen fired tear gas and rubber bullets in Jerusalem to quash
protests over the unsolved killing of an Arab high school student.
   One Arab was killed in the city of Jenin when troops opened fire
to disperse stone-throwing protesters who blocked major
thoroughfares, an army official said. A second Arab shot and
wounded in the clash died later Wednesday, the official said.
   Troops shot a third Palestinian as he tried to hurl a firebomb
at their patrol in Shuyukh village near Hebron, the official said.
   Six Palestinians were wounded in the clashes, the army said.
   It was the highest casualty toll in two months, bringing to 228
the number of Palestinians killed in the 7{-month-old revolt in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Four Israelis also have died.
   Two small groups of right-wing Israelis accompanied by more than
200 police and border patrolman in riot gear paid 20-minute visits
to Temple Mount, where the Al Aqsa and Dome of the Rock mosques are
built on the site of the biblical Jewish temple.
   Jews are permitted to visit the site, which is called Haram al
Sharif in Arabic and is the third holiest site of Islam, but not to
pray there in groups.
   Gershon Solomon, leader of an organization that wants Jews to
regain control of the site, came down with a fistful of soil and
declared: ``My friends, we are going to lose Jerusalem. Without the
Temple Mount and without Jerusalem, the state of Israel cannot
exist. This is a terrible danger.''
   Hours earlier, the Supreme Islamic Council met with
representatives of eight foreign consulates and appealed for a halt
to Israeli archaeological digs near the mosque walls.
   In the Christian quarter of the Old City, policemen fired tear
gas at several hundred Arabs who started an illegal march in memory
of 15-year-old Nidal Fuad Rabadi, who was shot to death in unclear
circumstances Tuesday near the Jerusalem city limits.
   Police Chief Yosef Yehudai said authorities had no leads in the
shooting. He said Rabadi, a Jerusalem resident, had been arrested
four times in recent months for throwing stones at cars and buses.
   Both police and the army have denied involvement in the killing.
Arab journalists said Israelis driving to the West Bank may have
shot Rabadi when firing at youths who threw rocks at their cars.
   On Wednesday, police raided a house near the Rabadi home and
arrested 25 Palestinians, including some allegedly involved in the
critical wounding of a border patrolman on Tuesday.
   Hassan Muhamad, 21, is one of many members of the Arab Druse
minority who serve in Israel's armed forces. His skull was
fractured by a 45-pound concrete cinderblock that was dropped on
his head after Rabadi's funeral.
   The Palestinian killed when he tried to throw a firebomb in
Shuyukh village was identified as Zaki Halaykeh, 23. An official at
Alia Hospital in Hebron said the man was shot in the back.
   Three other young Arabs in Shuyukh were wounded, the army said.
   At Jenin, a hospital official said 26-year-old Hisham Zaid died
after soldiers shot him in the chest. The army said it was
investigating, and reported four Palestinians wounded in Jenin, one
of which later died.
   A Palestinian physician who leads the Charitable Societies
Federation, an umbrella group for West Bank charity groups, was
sentenced to three months in jail.
   Charges against him were not made public immediately, but Israel
suspects charitable societies of contributing to the rebellion by
directing local protests and distributing funds.
   One of the most successful protest actions has been an Arab tax
boycott. Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said on Wednesday that tax
revenues from the occupied lands have dropped 40 percent since the
uprising began.
   Maj. Gen. Ehud Barak, the deputy military chief of staff, told
the parliament that 5,600 Palestinians are in jail but some will be
released Sunday as a gesture on the Moslem holiday Id el Adha.
   Two Palestinian guerrillas were sentenced to life in prison for
infiltrating Israel from Jordan and a third was given 25 years, a
military court announced. They were captured by Israeli soldiers in
December after a border firefight in which one was wounded.
</TEXT>
