<DOCNO> AP880720-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1711EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Khomeini-Excerpts     07-20 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Khomeini-Excerpts,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Khomeini Statement Accepting Cease-Fire Resolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Khomeini</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following are excerpts from a
statement Wednesday by Iran's leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
accepting a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire resolution toward ending the
Iran-Iraq war.
   It contains direct quotes from the address carried by Iran's
official Islamic Republic News Agency, Tehran Radio and Iran
televison and material paraphrased from the speech by IRNA. No full
text was released.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``I shall say again that the acceptance of this issue is more
deadly to me than poison, but I am happy to submit to God's will
and drank this cup for his satisfaction.
   ``However, thanks to some incidents and factors that I do not
mention at this moment and God willing will become clear in the
future, and in view of the opinion of all the high-ranking
political and military experts of the country, whom I trust for
their commitment, sympathy and sincerity, I agreed with the
acceptance of the resolution and cease-fire, and under the existing
circumstances I believe this to be in the interest of the
revolution and the system.
   ``God knows that had it not been for the motive that all of us
and our honor and credibility should be sacrificed in the interest
of Islam and the Muslims, I would never have agreed with this
issue, and to me it would have been more bearable to accept death
and martyrdom.
   ``I strongly recommend to the dear nation of Iran to remain
alert and vigilant.
   ``The acceptance of the resolution by the Islamic Republic of
Iran does not mean a solution to the problem of war. Rather, by
announcing this decision, the propaganda weapons of the
world-devourers against us is blunted, but one cannot seriously and
decisively predict the outcome of events.
   ``The enemy has not abandoned his atrocities yet, and it is
likely that, by seeking excuses, he would continue his aggressive
methods. We must be ready and prepared to repulse the enemy's
possible aggression and our nation should not think the issue is
over yet.
   ``Of course we formally announce that our objective is not to
have a new tactic for continuation of the war.''
   Khomeini told the nation that in light of the situation it is
likely in future days some people may tend to indulge in polemics
about the wisdom of the decision but suggested this should best be
postponed until later.
   He said the war had been ``good for the people who were martyred
and good for those whose children were martyred.''
   On Islam's international policy, Khomeini said: ``We are trying
to enlighten other parts of the world with Islam. We have always
sought and are still seeking to put an end to the domination of
world-devourers over the oppressed nations and uproot capitalism,
communism and Zionism, without fearing that U.S. lackeys might
accuse us of pursuing a policy of expansionism or founding a great
empire.
   ``We will try, with all our might and even through armed
struggles, to prevent American policy-makers from spreading their
bullying policies.
   ``I hereby warn the American and European military forces to
leave the Persian Gulf before it is too late.''
   He praised freedom-loving Moslems who helped unveil ``the joint
U.S.-Saudi Arabian crime in Mecca,'' referring to the 1987 riot by
Iranian pilgrims in which 402 persons died, mostly Iranian. He
advised Moslems to strive to tilt the balance of power to their own
benefit or else the U.S. and the Soviet Union will create new
catastrophes under the pretext of safeguarding their vested
interests.
   Khomeini said that God willing, all Moslems would ``raise their
voice against all the world's oppressors and prove that the
superpowers and their servants and lackeys are among the most
despicable creatures of this world.
   ``Are the world's Moslems going to forget the tragedy of the
massacre of hundreds of scholars and thousands of men and women
belonging to Moslem sects, during the length of the shameless life
of the al-Saud (the ruling family of Saudi Arabia) and also the
tragedy of the massacre of the pilgrims in the house of God (Mecca)?
   ``The goverment of the al-Saud has taken over the responsibility
for controlling the pilgrims in the house of God. And it is here
that we say, with confidence, that the Mecca incident is not a
separate matter from the fundamental policy of the world-devourers
in routing free-spirited Moslems.''
</TEXT>
