<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--RisingStars 2ndLd-Writethru a0771 07-20 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Rising Stars, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0771,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats' Rising Stars Strut Their Stuff at Party Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf bgng ``Each harbors'' that Richards
would not be first woman governor of Texas.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a host of up-and-coming Democrats who aren't
named Dukakis or Jackson, the party convention provides a stage for
them to strut their stuff and dream of bigger days to come.
   Among the rising stars who got to perform before the crowd of
11,000 in The Omni and millions more watching on television:
Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, selected to nominate Michael Dukakis on
Wednesday night, and Texas Treasurer Ann W. Richards, who skewered
George Bush in her folksy keynote address Monday.
   Each harbors higher ambitions, Clinton to run for president
himself one day, and Richards to become governor of the Lone Star
state in 1990.
   Others play out bit roles at the 40th Democratic National
Convention, often making their entrance when the cameras of the
national television networks are dark, or turned the other way.
   But for young politicians like Louisiana State Sen. Cleo Fields,
who is all of 25, and Texas State Rep. Lena Guerrero, 30, just
getting to the rostrum was a sign that somebody in the party
hierarchy liked them.
   Fields spoke with passion Tuesday evening on Jesse Jackson's
futile bid to get the party to oppose first use of nuclear weapons,
regardless of the circumstances. ``We must say America will not be
the country that will end this world,'' he declared.
   Guerrero, a Dukakis delegate from Austin, won high marks for her
role in drafting the party platform. She also made a prime-time
introduction Tuesday of Rep. Robert Matsui of California, who moved
the adoption of the no-frills platform.
   Another Texan, Jim Hightower, gave a national audience a taste
of the populist one-liners that have made him a force back home.
The two-term Agriculture commissioner has his eyes on a U.S. Senate
seat _ either Republican Sen. Phil Gramm's in 1990, or Lloyd
Bentsen's if the Democrats capture the White House and set off a
free-for-all for that vacancy.
   In a week filled with rhetorical fusillades aimed at George
Bush, Hightower may have scored a big hit with his quip, ``He is a
man who was born on third base and thinks he hit a triple.''
   Although his speech Tuesday night did not light any fires,
Michigan Gov. James J. Blanchard fulfilled his mission from party
chief Paul G. Kirk Jr. to produce a pithy platform devoid of
troublesome special interest promises.
   With a governor at the head of the ticket, the party also was
highlighting the accomplishments of Blanchard, who takes credit for
helping revive Michigan's economy, Clinton, a national leader of
welfare and school improvement efforts, Louisiana's reform-minded
Buddy Roemer and others.
   A film aired at the convention said these governors exemplify
``a new approach to problem solving: problem-solvers with an eye on
the balance sheet.''
   The party has other stars already established, including Al Gore
and other also-rans in this year's presidential contest, and some
of those considered presidential timber who chose not to run, such
as Mario Cuomo and Bill Bradley.
   Others, already well established, look to even larger roles down
the road: California Rep. Tony Coelho, the party whip, who had the
convention chanting ``Where was George?'' even before Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy used the same line; Arkansas Rep. Beryl F. Anthony,
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee; Rep.
Thomas Foley of Washington, House majority leader and convention
parliamentarian who is heir apparent to Speaker Jim Wright; Rep.
Bill Gray of Philadelphia, chairman of the House Budget Committee
and perhaps the country's most powerful black officeholder; and
Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, whose role in the Iran-Contra
hearings boosted his chances to succeed Robert Byrd as Senate
majority leader.
   Then, for democratic-minded Americans (with a small ``d'') who
still love a political dynasty, this convention had two young
Kennedys to offer: 35-year-old Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II, Bobby
Kennedy's oldest son, a movie-star handsome figure roaming the
floor posing for pictures with awe-struck delegates; and his
cousin, John F. Kennedy Jr., the 27-year-old son of the late
president. The younger Kennedy, now a law student, drew cheers from
the delegates with his reference to his father: ``So many of you
came into public service because of him. In a very real sense,
because of you, he is still with us.''
   Another potential dynasty in the making passed along this stage:
the children of Jesse Jackson, including his oldest son, Jesse Jr.,
23, who proclaimed in a ringing voice, ``Those who say this is an
age of cynicism and despair are wrong. A new generation, my
generation, is coming. We have not given up the dream.''
</TEXT>
