<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     07-20 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Democrats `Frantic Name-Callers,' Confirms Dole on Veep
List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Wednesday
that Democrats who have criticized him from their convention in
Atlanta are ``a bunch of frantic name-callers'' and confirmed that
former GOP rival Robert Dole of Kansas is on his list of
prospective running mates.
   The certain Republican presidential nominee, ending a four-day
fishing trip, said that he had given some thought to the selection
of a running mate and, when asked specifically if Dole were among
those considered, replied ``Sen. Dole would be on any list because
he's so widely respected.''
   The vice president said that, even though he and Dole engaged in
a bitter primary contest, ``that's all been laid to rest.''
   However, Bush said that he still had not narrowed any potential
list of running mates and had only decided upon a process that he
would follow. That process, Bush said, would be low-key.
   Asked about attacks on him by Democratic speakers in Atlanta,
Bush said that he had not been following the Democratic convention.
``I don't want to be cute with you, but I've been out of contact
for four days,'' Bush said.
   Bush said he did not intend to criticize Democrats during their
convention. ``I'm not good at being a slash-and-burn candidate,''
he said.
   When told by reporters about criticism of him from the
Democrats, Bush said, ``It might show a little desperation. Why
don't they run on what they're for? Why respond to a bunch of
frantic name-callers?''
   Told about caustic attacks on him by Democratic keynote speaker
Ann Richards, who told the convention in its opening session that
Bush was born ``with a silver foot in his mouth,'' the vice
president said only that he planned to carry Texas in the fall
election. Ms. Richards is Texas state treasurer.
   ``If you just go nasty, go ugly, that isn't an effective way to
do business,'' Bush said.
   The vice president spoke to reporters before addressing a
Captive Nations banquet in this Detroit suburb.
   In his speech to the largely Ukrainian audience, Bush delivered
a strongly anti-communist line. ``We will never cease to work and
pray for the freedom of our families, friends, our brothers all, in
nations held captive around the world,'' Bush said.
   He called upon Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev to free Eastern
European political prisoners who are being held in Soviet jails.
   Bush told reporters that his fishing trip with Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III had been a success. ``We stayed in the
same tent. We fished three days....We caught a lot of fish, went to
bed very early and had a minimal discussion of politics,'' Bush
said of his outing near Cody, Wyo. Baker is expected to become his
campaign manager.
   Told that Sen. Edward M. Kennedy had been particularly critical
of his role in the Iran-Contra affair, Bush told the news
conference, ``The good thing about the absolute wilderness is you
don't have to listen to Ted Kennedy.''
   The vice president said he wasn't troubled by the fact that his
campaigning Wednesday and Thursday during the final days of the
convention was a break in tradition.
   ``You tell me I shouldn't be in the wilderness. Now you say I
shouldn't be campaigning. What should I do?'' Bush said.
   Bush said he had no intention of waging an offensive campaign
during the Democrats' convention. ``I'm not going to rain on their
parade,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
