<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-20 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Schuller was expecting a wonderful
birthday present Thursday: the birth of triplets by Caesarean
section.
   But his wife, Rickey, went into premature labor and gave birth
to the three boys on her own birthday _ in the same hospital where
she was born.
   ``I was accused of doing this on purpose,'' Mrs. Schuller said.
``It was a perfect delivery. Things just went very smoothly.''
   William, James and Michael, each weighing 3 to 4 pounds, were
born July 14 at Baptist Hospital.
   ``I just thought, `I'm not ready for this,''' Mrs. Schuller
said. ``Obviously, it was really exciting.''
   All three babies are doing well, and the two largest are
expected to leave the hospital in the next 10 days, said Gorge
Rojas, a neonatologist at Baptist's special care nursery.
   Mrs. Schuller entered the hospital in May with premature labor
signs and remained in bed until the babies were born. She left the
hospital Tuesday.
   Triplets occur once in every 7,000 births and often are the
result of fertility drugs, which the couple didn't take. The
Schullers knew since February they were to have triplets.
   The Schullers have one other child, a 2-year-old son.
   ``It's going to be wild, but it's going to be fun,'' Schuller
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 physicians at the
University of Alabama at Birmingham have spent $2 million to go
into the hamburger business but they aren't setting up a new
practice.
   The University of Alabama Health Services Foundation, a
non-profit group of more than 500 doctors, bought a Wendy's Old
Fashioned Hamburgers franchise near the UAB campus because it wants
the land to build an outpatient clinic, said Dick Briggs Jr.,
acting president of the foundation.
   The group purchased the land in March for $1.6 million and the
hamburger franchise for $400,000. The foundation has kept the
restaurant operating because of a commitment not to have empty
buildings while it waits for construction of the $103.5 million
clinic to begin, Briggs said.
   ``But,'' he said, ``we don't have any long-range visions of
making our fortunes in the burger business.''
   The foundation likely will sell the franchise rights rather than
incorporating a Wendy's into the retail space that will be
available in the new clinic's parking deck. After all, he said,
``It may be hard to push cholesterol-lowering diets in our building
with a Wendy's next door.''
</TEXT>
