<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PandaDies     07-20 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Dies,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pe-Pe Dies at Chapultepec Zoo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pe-Pe, father of the largest panda bear
family outside China, died on Wednesday of cancer, zoo officials
said. He was 13.
   ``He died at 9:30 a.m. of the sickness he had. Right now they
are performing the autopsy that will last four hours,'' Maru Nunez,
an administrative assistant at the Chapultepec Zoo, said in a phone
interview.
   A biopsy last month determined cancer in each of the panda's
armpits, and chemotherapy started earlier in July. The panda had
been losing weight.
   The Chinese government gave Pe-Pe and his mate, Ying-Ying, to
Mexico in September 1975. The prolific couple had seven
naturally-conceived cubs, of which four survived. The family of
giant pandas became one of the zoo's most popular attractions.
   Last week, Pe-Pe was down to 215 pounds from his normal weight
of 280 pounds, according to zoo director Maria Elena Hoyo.
   Ms. Hoyo said it was the first time chemotherapy treatments were
administered to a panda.
   The only two giant pandas on permanent display in the United
States are at the National Zoo in Washington, D.C., a gift from
China.
   Pe-Pe puppets, candy and cartoons became some of the most
popular figures of Mexican children's entertainment.
   Pandas normally live about 20 years.
   Fewer than 1,000 of the bears, which are an endangered species,
are believed to be living in the wild, mostly in China.
</TEXT>
