<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1753EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Clements     07-20 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clements,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor `Feeling Fine,' Aide Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A laughing Gov. Bill Clements said
Wednesday he feels fine after suffering a minor stroke that
temporarily affected his vision and speech, adding he hoped to
leave the hospital Thursday.
   ``I feel great. I feel real good,'' Clements, 71, said in a
brief interview in his room at Seton Medical Center.
   Clements, who admitted himself to the hospital Tuesday night,
said doctors told him it appears a small blood clot formed and
passed into the upper left quarter of his brain, causing temporary
problems Monday night in his right eye and with his speech.
   Clements and his wife, Rita, said the problems developed while
he was reading after having watched the Democratic National
Convention on television.
   ``That Democratic Convention may have made this happen. I don't
know,'' the state's first Republican governor since Reconstruction
joked. ``The next morning, Tuesday, I felt fine.''
   Clements said he grew ``a little droopy,'' during the day
Tuesday and decided to see a doctor.
   Reggie Bashur, the governor's press secretary said Clements had
been undergoing tests since his hospitalization.
   ``The results are excellent, and I feel very fortunate that it
was just a temporary situation,'' the governor said.
   Mrs. Clements, seated beside her husband on a sofa during the
interview, said doctors told her such problems often last about 24
hours and clear up.
   Bashur said physicians would not comment until all test results
were known.
   Clements said the doctors hadn't yet told him what might have
caused the stroke. But he said he planned to resume a full schedule
and keep playing tennis.
   Bashur said Clements still hoped to be able to attend a prison
groundbreaking ceremony Friday in Amarillo. The State Board of
Corrections voted Wednesday to name the facility the William P.
Clements Jr. Unit.
   Clements was first elected in 1978. He lost to Democrat Mark
White in 1982 but came back to defeat White in the 1986 election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
