<HEAD>Singing Kansans Jab Dole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Democrats poked fun Wednesday at
Republican Sen. Bob Dole's ``acid-tongued barbs'' Wednesday,
singing ditties about his sharp wit at a caucus meeting.
   ``It sounds like they're talking about Ann Richards,'' joked
Dole when told of the Democrats' lyrics in Tokepa.
   Richards, the Texas treasurer, entertained Democratic delegates
at the national convention Monday night with stinging remarks about
Vice President George Bush.
   At the daily caucus meeting, the Kansas delegates wrote their
own lyrics to the tune of ``My Favorite Things'' from ``The Sound
of Music.''
   ``Razor-sharp hatchets and knives honed for stabbing,
   ``Acid-tongued barbs and the headlines they're grabbing,
   ``Partisan charges and mud that he slings,
   ``These are a few of Dole's favorite things.''
   While one Kansan played a kazoo, delegates were asked to join in
the sing-along. After a few stanzas, delegates sang at the top of
their voices and gave themselves a standing ovation at the end of
the session.
