<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BenzeneRegulations     07-20 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Benzene Regulations,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Delays Develping Benzene Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on
Wednesday delayed developing regulations for more controls on the
leukemia-causing air pollutant benzene until it hears from the
public on what is an acceptable environmental risk.
   The approach the agency adopts for benzene, one of the most
widely used of all chemicals, is expected to set the standard for
agency rulings on acceptable levels of risk for dozens of other air
pollutants.
   ``One question is: Should we opt for additional controls that
may be expensive but only buy society little additional
reduction?'' EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas said in a statement
announcing the delay.
   Currently, about 10 cases of leukemia occur in the general
population every three years as a result of leaks from plant
equipment and other exposure from making and using benzene. The
chemical is used in making gasoline, plastics, rubber, artificial
fibers and many other chemicals.
   Under the plans the EPA is considering, about one death every
other year would result from benzene exposure.
   Environmentalists have sought standards that, in effect, would
result in one death every 550 years. The EPA believes that such
stringent standards would force massive plant closings and lead to
the loss of thousands of jobs.
   At issue in the matter is whether environmental risk should
depend on where a person lives. Some analysts contend that society
has already answered that question by refusing to allow such
facilities as nuclear power plants to be built in urban areas but
allowing them in the countryside.
   With benzene, the EPA is trying to decide whether to rule that
nobody living near industrial sources should face a lifetime risk
greater than one in a million, as the environmentalists argue, or
whether larger risks to individuals should be allowed when few
people are exposed and the expected number of cancers is small.
   The agency asked for ``maximum public comment'' on the
sidetracked plan and three others. In order of increasing
stringency those others would:
   _Limit annual cases of leukemia to one in the entire population.
This would mean little cost to industry.
   _Limit the maximum likely risk to the most exposed individual to
one in 10,000, ignoring total cases.
   _Limit the maximum likely risk to one in a million. This, the
EPA said, could result in the closing of 131 chemical plants that
couldn't control leaks and the loss of 35,000 jobs, plus the
closing of 44 coke-oven byproduct recovery plants and the loss of
7,000 jobs.
   David Doniger, an attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said that he was ``gratified that the one-in-a-million
risk standard is under serious consideration,'' and was almost
certain that EPA had greatly overestimated the costs of compliance.
   He said it appeared the agency had not considered the ability of
industry to pass on cost increases in prices and also that EPA
assumed all plants would have to reduce emissions by the same
proportion as the dirtiest plants.
   He said the EPA also ignored the possibility that industry could
develop new technologies to control benzene emissions.
   The EPA's current benzene regulations, which were adopted in
1984, were challenged in court by Doniger. The agency had a court
deadline to make a proposal by Wednesday and a decision by December.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
said last year in a decision on another pollutant, vinyl chloride,
that the EPA must disregard all questions of costs in deciding
acceptable risks, but may consider costs and feasibility in
deciding the ``ample margin of safety'' called for by the law.
   The American Petroleum Institute said in a statement that the
new proposal offered ``a good opportunity to develop a workable
program in this area,'' and that it hoped the EPA would ``resist
the unreasonable demands of environmental groups'' to adopt
standards that are almost ``zero-risk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ContraRift Bjt   07-20 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Rift, Bjt,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Contra Split Seen as Militarily Mino, But Politically
Damaging</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new, harder line shift in the
leadership of the Nicaraguan Contras and a resulting split with
their so-called ``Southern Front'' could be politically costly to
the anti-Sandinista rebels.
   The alliance between the Southern Front and the principal Contra
coalition known as the Nicaraguan Resistance has always been
fragile, marred by frequent disputes and an almost constant lack of
cooperation.
   But the announcement of a break in that alliance Tuesday night
by seven Southern Front field commanders highlighted anew the
growing turmoil within the Contra organization brought about by
last year's congressional decision to end U.S. aid.
   Ironically, the new Contra leadership disputes surfaced as the
rebels appeared to have gained their best hope in months of winning
renewed aid from a Congress concerned over recent repressive acts
by Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   ``It's hard to say who's best at shooting themselves in the
foot, the Sandinistas or the Contras,'' one western European
diplomat observed Wednesday. ``They seem to trade political miscues
as often as they trade bullets.''
   ``But the Contras are not likely to win any converts with this
political shakeup and their apparent drift to the right,'' added
the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It could give
some wavering congressmen, especially Democrats, second thoughts.''
   The diplomat referred to an election in the Dominican Republic
on Monday night that gave Enrique Bermudez, commander of the main
rebel army known as the Nicaraguan Democratic Front, a seat on the
Contras' seven-member political directorate.
   The General Assembly of the Nicaraguan Resistance also dumped
two of Bermudez's most outspoken critics, Alfonso Robelo and Pedro
Joaquin Chamorro, leaving the military commander as the apparent
first among equals on the policy-making board.
   Bermudez, a former colonel in the National Guard of ousted
Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza, has long been a major point
of friction among Contra leaders, some of whom, like Robelo, are
former Sandinistas themselves and leery of a return to a
military-dominated government.
   At least five of the Southern Front field commanders who split
away from the Resistance because of Bermudez's election also are
former Sandinistas. They denounced his election as an attempt to
gain control of the Contra movement by ``the extreme right.''
   After being ousted from the directorate, Chamorro, a former
editor of the Nicaraguan opposition daily newspaper La Prensa,
accused the 50-member General Assembly of creating a ``military
hegemony.''
   ``This effort to confuse the military and the civilian
(leadership) brings back tragic memories from the past,'' Chamorro
said, in a clear reference to the 42-year rule of the Somoza family
that was ended by the Sandinistas in a popular revolution on July
19, 1979.
   The Southern Front has fought the Sandinista government along
the Nicaraguan-Costa Rican frontier since 1983, when it was first
formed under the name of the Democratic Revolutionary Alliance by
Eden Pastora, another former Sandinista guerrilla leader.
   Pastora, whose nom de guerre was Commander Zero, dropped out of
the fight in 1986, but many of his field commanders continued the
battle under the leadership of one of Pastora's former chief
lieutenants, Fernando ``El Negro'' Chamorro, and a new name, the
Opposition Bloc of the South.
   Chamorro also gave up the fight last year and returned to
Managua. But, again, many of the field commanders chose to fight
on, this time as the Southern Front under the leadership of Pedro
J. Lara, another former Sandinista known by his guerrilla name of
``Ganso.''
   From the beginning, the Southern Front guerrillas have received
but a fraction of the U.S. aid bestowed on the larger, better known
Contra army commanded by Bermudez and based in Honduras. Although
the Southern Front claims 2,700 combatants, most observers place
its strength at no more than 500 men and it has not been known to
have scored any significant military victories in recent years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reid G. Miller is a roving correspondent in
Central America for The Associated Press, based in San Jose, Costa
Rica since 1984.
</TEXT>
