<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BirdSmuggling     07-20 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bird Smuggling,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Plead Not Guilty in Cuban Bird Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five people have pleaded innocent to charges they
smuggled 243 exotic birds from Cuba into the United States. The
case, says their attorney, was ``for the birds.''
   Ellis Rubin said his clients, Cuban immigrants who live in the
Miami area, were only moving the birds from Miami to Marathon for
the breeding season when they were arrested Easter Sunday.
   But U.S. Customs agents say correspondence on the ship _
including a letter from a woman asking to buy ``a girdle, size
medium, that I need very much to go out,'' showed the boat had been
in Cuba.
   They also found Cuban coins, a bill from a hotel and souvenirs
of Cuba aboard, but were puzzled as to how the boat got in and out
of the island nation.
   The birds included 193 Cuban melodius finches, 48 Cuban Amazon
parrots, one mustached parakeet and a scarlet macaw. The parrots
can be bought cheaply abroad and sold for $1,500 to $3,000 each in
the United States.
   Each defendant is charged with three felony counts, one of
conspiracy to violate the Lacy Act, and two counts each of
violation of the act itself.
   The defendants entered innocent pleas on Tuesday. They are free
on bond, and a trial was scheduled Sept. 12.
</TEXT>
