<DOCNO> AP880720-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Angola     07-20 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola Talks To Continue In Geneva Next Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola Accord Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will mediate four-way talks
in Switzerland starting Aug. 2 aimed at working out a final
agreement on the withdrawal of foreign forces from Angola and on
Namibian independence from South Africa, it was announced Wedneday.
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker made the
announcement after South Africa, Cuba and Angola _ the other
participants in the talks _ gave final endorsement to a statement
of principles governing future negotiations.
   ``This is an important step. We are not saying it is more than
that,'' Crocker told a news conference. ``There are a great many
hard and difficult compromises to be achieved.''
   The statement of principles was worked out on a tentative basis
last week during talks in New York. But it left unresolved the
thorny question of the timetables during which the withdrawals
would take place. This has emerged as the major area of
disagreement among the parties.
   Aside from the timetable issue, Crocker said the statement of
principles clears the way for the drafting of treaties, discussions
on verification of a final agreement and a process for the
disengagement of forces.
   The United States has been serving as mediator for the four-way
talks, which began in early May. The previous rounds were held in
London, Cairo and New York. The Switzerland talks will take place
in Geneva.
   The administration's involvement in the issue dates back to 1981
when Crocker began pursuing a settlement that would lead to the
withdrawal of Cuban and South African forces from Angola and South
African consent to independence for Namibia, Africa's last colony.
   The Cubans have sent up to 15,000 additional troops to Angola
since last fall but at the same time have shown a much greater
willingness to work out an agreement on a total withdrawal, a
senior official said, insisting on anonymity.
   The Cuban presence in Angola is believed to number between
47,500 and 50,000 forces. There are believed to be several thousand
South Africa forces in Angola supporting a U.S.-backed insurgency.
   The biggest remaining obstacle is a timetable for the mutual
troop withdrawals.
   Under a United Nations resolution, the independence process in
Namibia would be carried out over a one-year period once South
Africa consents to that step. That timetable is considered
non-negotiable.
   But South Africa, with U.S. backing, has said the South African
withdrawal will not take place unless Cuba agrees to withdraw its
forces simultaneously.
   In effect, that appears to mean Cuba would have to agree to
roughly a one-year withdrawal timetable or there is no agreement.
   As an opening bargaining position, Cuba and Angola have talked
of a four-year period for the Cuban pullback but both sides have
indicated flexibility on that point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
