<DOCNO> AP880720-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbductedNun     07-20 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abducted Nun,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would-be Nun Glad Her Family Removed Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman whose family abducted her from a
convent says she won't go back and is glad her family cared enough
about her to physically drag her away.
   ``I'm not going to go back to a convent,'' said Mary Susan
Greve, the former Sister Mary Cecelia. ``People are saying, `Live
your own life. Well, I am going to live my own life _ and I'm
excited about it.''
   Ms. Greve, 22, of Cincinnati, says she wants to finish college
to get the teaching degree she left half-completed when she joined
the St. Joseph Novitiate Convent in Roundtop, N.Y.
   Members of her family were long-time followers of the convent's
spiritual leader, the Rev. Clarence Kelly. However, they became
disturbed at his conservative practices, which were not sanctioned
by the Roman Catholic Church in Rome, and left his congregation.
   They tried to persuade Ms. Greve to leave.
   The family said it resorted to abducting her June 26 after Kelly
allegedly kept them from communicating with her.
   The church has said little since New York police dropped charges
against the family.
   Kelly has maintained Ms. Greve was brainwashed by her family
into believing the convent was a cult.
   Ms. Greve discussed her decision Tuesday during a taping of the
Phil Donahue Show. Kelly also appeared on the program.
   The traditional religious order follows the teachings of the
Roman Catholic Church prior to Vatican II, which gave bishops a
greater influence in church affairs, gave the laity a more active
part in the liturgy and liberalized church positions with regard to
non-Catholic and non-Christian faiths.
</TEXT>
