<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-GulfWar     07-20 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Gulf War,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Warns of Iraqi Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli defense officials warned on Wednesday
of the potential threat to Israel of an Iraqi army left idle after
peace with Iran, but said the danger was not immediate.
   ``If there is an eastern front of Syria, Iraq and Jordan, with
the assistance of Saudi Arabia, the armored force facing Israel
will be equal to the number of tanks of all NATO countries,''
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said on Israel radio.
   He noted that Iraq has participated in every Arab war against
Israel, but said the danger of a new attack was not imminent
because it probably would take another year or two for the Persian
Gulf combatants to disentangle.
   Rabin also said that, if Arab leaders tried to use missiles
equipped with chemical warheads against Israel, ``they will get it
back hundredfold and more.'' Iraq and Syria are known to have
chemical weapons.
   Israeli defense officials said the size of Iraq's military
forces had grown from 300,000 troops to 1.1 million since the war
began in September 1980, the number of army divisions from 12 to 54
and the armored strength from 4,000 tanks to 6,000, Israel radio
reported, without identifying the officials.
   It quoted them as saying Iraq has about 560 jet fighters capable
of flying long-distance missions.
</TEXT>
