<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mecca-Demonstration     07-20 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecca-Demonstration,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-U.S. Demonstration Reported During Mecca Moslem Pilgrimage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem pilgrims in the Saudi Arabian city
of Mecca on Wednesday shouted ``Death!'' to the United States, the
Soviet Union and Israel, Tehran Radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said the demonstration was ``in
response to the call by Imam Khomeini.''
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini is the religious and revolutionary
leader of Iran.
   Tehran Radio gave no source or further details in its report,
which was not confirmed from other sources.
   The radio said the demonstration was carried out by ``Moslem
pilgrims in the midst of Saudi security and police forces and close
to the house of God,'' a reference to the Kaaba, Islam's holiest
shrine in central Mecca.
   Saudi security forces have been on high alert to prevent
incidents such as last year's riot, following an anti-American,
anti-Saudi demonstration by fanatical Iranian pilgrims in which 402
persons died, most of them Iranians.
   Saudi Arabia set a limit this year of one pilgrim per thousand
population for each country. Iran is boycotting the pilgrimage in
protest while continuing anti-Saudi invective, calling the Saudi
royal family a U.S. ``lackey'' and not fit to be custodian of the
Moslem holy places.
   Saudi Interior Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel Aziz said a small
number of Iranians came for the pilgrimage among about 750,000
Moslems from all over the world.
   The prince said in an interview published Wednesday that Iran
might take advantage of Shiite Moslems from other lands. Shiites
are the majority sect in Iran, but a minority in the Moslem world.
   Saudi security forces ``are vigilant and ready to confront any
Iranian plots,'' he said.
</TEXT>
