<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoarkRelease     07-20 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roark Release,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roark Released From Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Mike ``Mad Dog'' Roark
walked out of federal prison Wednesday after serving five months of
a cocaine possession sentence.
   Roark, 42, nicknamed for his flamboyant exploits as a
prosecutor, was whisked past reporters and photographers shortly
before 8 a.m. at the Federal Correctional Institute in Petersburg,
Va.
   Warden J.J. Clark said Roark refued to sign forms that would
have allowed him to be interviewed and prison officials to comment.
   A federal grand jury indicted Roark last July on 27
cocaine-related counts and three obstruction of justice counts.
   The one-time assistant U.S. attorney and Kanawha County
prosecutor pleaded guilty to six counts of cocaine possession Nov.
17 as part of a plea bargain and resigned as mayor Nov. 24, seven
months after he was elected to a second four-year term.
   He was sentenced to 179 days in prison and fined $5,000.
   Roark entered prison Feb. 12 and was scheduled for release Aug.
8. He was a model inmate, which enabled the early release, a prison
official said.
   ``Obviously, he's presented no problems to us,'' Clark said,
adding that Roark worked as a clerk in the prison's education
department.
   Roark is to meet Aug. 1 with the State Bar Association, which is
trying to revoke his license to practice law.
   Roark earned the nickname ``Mad Dog'' for various reasons,
including an incident in which he donned a camouflage jacket and
sidearm for a drug raid.
</TEXT>
