<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--N.Y.Democrats     07-20 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--N.Y. Democrats,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo: No Easy Win For Dukakis In New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Wednesday, just
hours before Michael Dukakis' nomination, that it won't be easy for
the Massachusetts governor to carry the Empire state in November.
   ``We must win New York or we can't win the presidency and people
are taking New York for granted,'' Cuomo said during an impromtu
news conference as he arrived at The Omni convention hall. ``I
don't think it'll be easy. I think we'll win, but it won't be
easy.''
   Reminded that he had been predicting a national landslide for
Dukakis and had previously said Dukakis would have big wins in
every region of the country, Cuomo insisted Wednesday that he
wasn't changing his tune.
   ``I think he's going to win a landslide nationally, but that's
not going to be easy either. You have to work for landslides,''
said Cuomo, who defined a landslide as more than 52 percent.
   Meanwhile, top aides to the New York governor said they would
begin discussions soon after the convention ended with Hulbert
James, Jesse Jackson's New York campaign manager, to work out what
role the Jackson forces would play in the campaign for the state's
36 electoral votes.
   Andrew Cuomo, the governor's son and chief political adviser,
also said that, unlike 1984, when the Cuomo camp had almost total
control over the New York campaign, the 1988 Dukakis effort would
be controlled more by the Dukakis camp.
   ``It's their campaign. It's their decisions,'' said Andrew
Cuomo. ``They are running the campaign. We'll help.''
   The elder Cuomo said he would do whatever he could for Dukakis
in New York and elsewhere ``consistent with what I do as governor,
and we're very busy, as everybody knows.''
   Cuomo hoped to meet later Wednesday with both Dukakis and
Jackson. Neither could find time to sit down with the New York
governor on Monday.
</TEXT>
