<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash-Alcohol     07-20 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Alcohol,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Examiner Says Alcohol in Blood of Four Children in Church
Bus Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four children who were among 27 people
killed in a church bus crash had alcohol in the blood, the state
medical examiner said, but some survivors of the accident sharply
disputed that contention.
   ``I don't think it's a contributing factor at all'' in the
youths' inability to escape the burning vehicle, medical examiner
Dr. George Nichols told the Lexington Herald-Leader of the alcohol
finding.
   Neither the names of the four children nor the blood-alcohol
levels were available. Full autopsy results on all victims of the
May 14 crash were to be released Friday. The medical examiner has
said previously that all 27 died of smoke inhalation.
   The Radcliff First Assembly of God bus, returning to Hardin
County with 67 passengers after an outing at Kings Island amusement
park near Cincinnati, burst into flames after colliding head-on
with a pickup truck traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71 near
Carrollton.
   All but two of the 24 young people killed in the crash were 15
or younger. Three adults, including the driver, also died.
   Police said the driver of the pickup, Larry W. Mahoney, was
drunk. Mahoney, 35, has pleaded innocent to 27 counts of capital
murder.
   In another development, the law firm that negotiated most of the
out-of-court settlements resulting from the crash apparently will
receive a $4.5 million fee, The (Louisville) Courier-Journal
reported Wednesay.
   The firm negotiated payments totaling $35.9 million for 60
families, The Courier-Journal said. Ford Motor Co., one of the bus'
principal manufacturers, has reached settlements with 65 of the 67
families involved in the crash.
   Some of the crash survivors disputed the medical findings.
   ``Nobody was drinking,'' said Jamie Hardesty. ``I don't think
it's true. John Pearman wouldn't let nothing like that on the bus.''
   Pearman, an associate pastor of the Radcliff First Assembly of
God and the bus driver, was among the victims.
   Sandra Glover, 17, another survivor, said three coolers aboard
the bus contained only soft drinks. She said Nichols' contention
was going to hurt the church.
   ``All that stuff about Larry Mahoney drinking and driving, and
now they're going to say, `The kids were doing it, too,''' she
said. ``John Pearman told us when we left that morning that there
was to be no alcohol, either on the bus or at the park.''
   Bill Mefford, manager of marketing and communications for Kings
Island, said the park sells beer to those 21 and older, but only
after a check of identification.
   ``We absolutely check IDs,'' Mefford said. ``We have some
complaints because we card everybody, even those as old as 60.''
</TEXT>
