<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mica-Cuba     07-20 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mica-Cuba,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mica Accuses Castro of Blocking Cuban Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NAN HERLIHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidel Castro personally revoked the visa of Rep.
Dan Mica, D-Fla., just hours before he was to fly to Havana to
inspect the U.S. diplomatic post there for security breaches, the
congressman charged Wednesday.
   ``I'm convinced this had to be personally revoked by Castro _ no
desk officer would do this,'' said Mica, a candidate for his
party's nomination to fill the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by
Lawton Chiles.
   Mica, who is also chairman of the House subcommittee charged
with overseeing safety and security at U.S. embassies abroad, said
that he had never been denied entry to a country, including
communist countries.
   ``This is a major violation of diplomatic protocol,'' Mica said.
He said that he and a ``crack team'' of congressional and U.S.
State Department officials were specialists in securing U.S.
diplomatic posts.
   The visas for the group were issued on July 14, he said. Cuban
officials said that they were revoked to protest an American
diplomat's guest list for a party in Havana on July 15.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that Cuba's
foreign minister, Isodoro Malmierca, called ``non-establishment''
Cubans who attended the party ``unacceptable.'' Human rights
activists were among the party guests, she said.
   ``The U.S. is protesting this incident, which was a great
discourtesy to a congressman and an example of Cuban government
intimidation of human rights activists,'' she said.
   Mica said he had planned to investigate charges that security at
the oceanfront U.S. post in Havana had been compromised. He said
the growing number of Cuban employees _ 102 versus 26 Americans _
was a potential threat to security.
   ``We have to maintain a large support staff there. We're
wondering if it's too big _ and who is on it,'' said Robert K.
Boyer, a senior staff member of the House Committee on Foreign
Affairs.
   Mica said that he would also investigate allegations that U.S.
Marines assigned to guard the post may have fraternized with Cuban
women, compromising security.
   A third concern is that an unspecified number of Cubans
reporting to U.S. intelligence officials may be double agents, and
have been for up to 20 years, Mica said.
   The congressman from Lake Worth insisted he had planned to
maintain a low profile in Cuba and had not sought media coverage of
the trip until it was blocked.
</TEXT>
