<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DrugTraffic     07-20 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Traffic,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Talking To Soviets About Joint Moves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is trying to work
out a cooperative approach with the Soviet Union in the struggle
against drug traffickers, the State Department said Wednesday.
   The discussions began in Moscow in April and ``both sides are
currently evaluating potential productive areas for future
cooperative activity,'' Phyllis Oakley, a department spokeswoman,
said.
   These include Soviet proposals to swap information on techniques
for intercepting drug shipments and ways of identifying the source
of narcotics through their ``signature,'' Catherine Shaw, a public
information officer, said.
   ``The proposals are very, very modest,'' Ms. Shaw said, and
reflect an admission, but not the first, by the Soviets that they
also have a drug problem.
   John C. Lawn, the U.S. drug enforcement administrator, will send
a delegate to Moscow for further discussions to pave the way for
more formal talks in Washington later in the year, the U.S.
official said.
   ``We are evaluating various proposals and we simply do not have
any definitive word on what those proposals are right now,'' Mrs.
Oakley said.
   The U.S. official said cooperation in the fight against
narcotics was ``a potentially fruitful area for improved bilateral
cooperation.''
</TEXT>
