<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RightsHearing     07-20 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rights Hearing,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Officials Ignore Commission Subpoenas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navajo judges and lawyers boycotted a
U.S. Civil Rights Commission hearing Wednesday, contending
commission subpoenas illegally infringed on tribal sovereignty.
   A commission subcommittee is holding hearings to determine if
federal courts should be allowed to enforce civil rights laws on
Indian reservations. Wednesday's session was to examine what impact
a dispute between the current and former heads of the tribe is
having on the Navajo judiciary.
   The commission lacked authority to even inquire about tribal
court enforcement of the federal Indian Civil Rights Act because a
1978 U.S. Supreme Court decision gives tribal courts final say on
the law, said David Nash, an attorney for the tribe.
   The ``subpoenas demonstrate an appalling disregard for the
integrity of the Navajo tribal court system'' and attorney-client
privilege, Navajo Attorney General Michael Upshaw added in a
written submission.
   ``We resent the Commission's intrusion into a tribal judicial
proceeding and its attempt to require us to re-litigate the case
before the Commission, particularly while it is pending before the
Navajo courts,'' he said.
   Commission Chairman William Allen said a decision would be made
later on how to enforce the subpoenas.
   The dispute began earlier this year when tribal Chairman Peter
MacDonald sought control over the Navajo Education and Scholarship
Foundation, which former Chairman Peterson Zah believed he had been
given authority over.
   Zah, locked out of his office, got a tribal judge to issue an
order barring his eviction. The tribe got another judge, and police
shut down the entire building.
   Brian Miller, the commission's deputy general counsel, said his
agency's interest was ``not one (of) merits and not one of who is
right and who is wrong but one of due process and civil rights.''
   Allen said the subcommittee was holding the hearings because the
Supreme Court ruled in 1978 that tribal enforcement of the Indian
Civil Rights Act was not subject to federal court review.
   ``Commission staff has received allegations that the
independence of the judiciary of the Navajo Nation has been
recently threatened,'' he said.
   ``Part of the court's reasoning was that `tribal forums are
available to vindicate rights created by the ICRA,''' Allen said.
``Put simply, the question this subcommittee has been examining is
whether the court's assumption is true.''
   The commission also discussed adoption cases involving Indian
children.
   Relatives, attorneys, social workers and would-be adoptive
parents in cases involving the Navajo and White Mountain Apache
tribes were called to testify.
   The Indian Child Welfare Act passed by Congress gives tribes
exclusive control over adoption in cases where the mother is living
on the reservation.
   The law stemmed from repeated complaints from tribal members
that non-Indian courts were too quick to allow non-Indians to adopt
an Indian child.
   But the commission wanted to see whether the rights given to the
tribe as a whole infringed on the rights of the individual parties.
   One case gained national attention recently when Rick and Cheryl
Pitts, a San Jose, Calif., couple, obtained a baby from a Navajo
woman outside the reservation.
   The tribal court demanded jurisdiction from a California court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
