<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     07-20 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zia Sets Elections for November; Opponents Blast Delay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq
announced on Wednesday that elections will be held on Nov. 16, but
the opposition demanded August elections and called his action a
delaying tactic and unconstitutional.
   Gen. Zia said in an address to the Senate that the elections
will be for both the National Assembly and for the four state
legislatures of Punjab, Sind, Baluchistan, and the North West
Frontier.
   His foes insisted that under Pakistan's Constitution, polling
must take place by Aug. 27, when a 90-day deadline expires
following Zia's May 29 dissolution of the National Assembly.
   The assembly and the Senate comprise the federal legislature.
   Zia said election arrangements cannot be completed before
November.
   Benazir Bhutto, head of the strongest opposition group, the
Pakistan's People's Party, called Zia's decision ``yet another
attempt to subvert the constitution and the political process of
transfer of power.''
   She said Zia would never have announced any poll date had it not
been for the opposition.
   Bhutto's father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, was overthrown as prime
minister by Zia in a 1977 military coup and was hanged in 1979
after conviction on a conspiracy to murder charge in a
controversial trial.
   Zia dismissed Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo, the National
Assembly and four state legislatures in May, accusing them of
corruption, incompetence, and failure to ``Islamize'' Pakistan and
prevent a breakdown of law and order.
   Junejo denied the charges and accused Zia of violating the
constitution by ``arbitrarily dissolving the assembly and
disrupting a democratic system which was operating smoothly.''
   The former premier told a news conference Wednesday, ``The
constitution clearly demands elections within 90 days after the
dissolution of the assembly. We need elections straight away. Nov.
16 is very late.''
   He said his Pakistan Moslem League Party had ``already
established a committee of constitutional experts to examine ...
(whether to challenge the delay in court) as well as the legality
of disolving the assembly.''
   Former Air Marshal Asghar Khan, president of the centrist
Tehril-e-Istiklal (Movement for Solidarity), said:
   ``We wanted these elections to be held within 90 days. His
(Zia's) credibility is already low. What is going to happen between
now and November, and whether polls will, in fact take place, no
one knows.''
</TEXT>
