<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Convention-Quotes     07-20 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention-Quotes,350</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some quotes from Wednesday's activities
at the Democratic National Convention.
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, speaking to a reception in honor of his wife of
25 years, Kitty: ``I'm a very lucky guy.'' His only regret, he
said, was that, ``When I was a senior at Brookline High School
nobody told me about a freshman named Kitty Dickson. If they had
this might all have started even earlier.''
   
   DUKAKIS, recalling the words he told his wife when he arrived
Sunday in Atlanta: ``This is a kick. ... I think it's for real, I
mean it's happening.''
   
   ANN RICHARDS, the Texas state treasurer who delivered the
keynote speech to the convention Monday night, speaking to a
fund-raising network for women Democratic candidates: ``Lloyd
Bentsen has been a friend to women in Texas. ... I think he gives
us a real shot at this election in November.''
   
   KITTY DUKAKIS, talking to a group of children and recalling her
26-year addiction to amphetamines: ``I couldn't stop using them and
I became addicted. The words I want to say to you are, `Don't
start.'''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, on having his campaign continue through the roll
call for nomination for president: ``It will be a great feeling
personally. But really, it's my name put into nomination for the
people who voted for me, but also for the people who made it
possible. ... It's fulfilling the prayers of people who fought
hard. It's a steppingstone for progress for the future.''
   
   DUKAKIS, telephoned Jackson to commend him on his address to the
Democratic National Convention on Tuesday night and said, ``I
thought the speech was terrific.''
   
   Illinois Gov. JAMES THOMPSON, part of the Republican ``truth
squad'' sent to Atlanta to comment on the proceedings of the
Democrats: ``Michael Dukakis has tied Jesse Jackson to this ticket
rather firmly. ... With Bentsen whispering in one ear and Jackson
whispering in his other ear, who is Dukakis going to listen to? ...
I think that's the question the American people need to have
answered.''
   
   Vice President GEORGE BUSH, the certain Republican nominee,
commenting in Warren, Mich. on the criticism of him from the
Democrats: ``It might show a little desperation. Why don't they run
on what they're for? Why respond to a bunch of frantic
name-callers?''
</TEXT>
