<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EGermany-Springsteen     07-20 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EGermany-Springsteen,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 100,000 East German Fans At Springsteen Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGOMAR SCHWELZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American pop star Bruce Springsteen thrilled about
160,000 cheering fans at a concert in East Berlin, and the
communist press on Wednesday hailed him as a friend of the working
class.
   It was the largest gathering of rock fans that ever in East
Germany.
   ``I am not here to support or oppose whatever government,''
Springsteen told the crowd during the Tuesday night concert in East
Berlin. ``I came here to play rock 'n' roll.''
   But he added, ``I hope that some day all the barriers (between
East and West) will be torn down.''
   Fireworks streaked through the sky during Springsteen's concert,
and his fans sang along to ``Born in the USA,'' ``Dancing in the
Dark,'' ``I'm On Fire,'' and other hits.
   Hundreds of people in the audience waved handmade American flags
during the four-hour concert, which was staged at a bicycle-racing
track in the East German district of Weissensee.
   Springsteen had asked East German officials if he could play in
the communist country as a part of his ``Tunnel of Love Express''
world tour, and they complied.
   The East German news media portrayed the American singer as
someone who fights against social injustices and as a friend of
workers.
   ``He attacks social wrongs and injustices in his homeland,''
wrote Neues Deutschland, the official newspaper of the East German
Communist Party.
   ``He wants to give hope to youths who are threatened with
joblessness in the capitalist world,'' the newspaper said.
   Fans came from all over the country to see Springsteen, waving
banners announcing that they were from Leipzig, Magdeburg, Dresden
and other places in East Germany.
   ``We Love You, Boss,'' said one of the banners.
   A concert ticket cost about $10.
   Springsteen said to his appreciative East German fans at the end
of the concert, ``I hope to play here again real soon.''
</TEXT>
