<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-20 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Falls in Wide Swath From Texas to New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers fell the length of a slow-moving cold front that
stretched from southern New England to north of the Ohio Valley and
southwest into Texas Wednesday, while the Far West continued to
bake in three-digit temperatures.
   The rain fell in torrents in some places. In northeast Kentucky,
1.20 inches of rain fell in just 15 minutes in the afternoon. Two
inches fell in four hours near Washington, Pa. Lamar, Texas,
reported 3.64 inches of rain during the morning, while Houston
logged up to 2 inches.
   Scott Air Force Base near Belleville, Ill.; Langley Air Force
Base near Hampton, Va.; Cincinnati; Indianapolis; Louisville, Ky.;
and Huntington, W.Va., all received more than an inch of rain in
the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m. EDT.
   A pocket of intense thunderstorms formed by an upper-level low
pressure system moved over Minnesota and into western Wisconsin
Wednesday, bringing heavy rain and hail over the Twin Cities.
Roseville, Minn., north of St. Paul, reported 2- to 3-inch drifts
of marble-size hail.
   Flash flood watches were issued for parts of southeast and
south-central New Mexico. Northeast Arkansas and southeast Missouri
got widespread rain for a second day Wednesday. The Cache River was
expected to spill over its banks near Patterson, Ark., causing
minor lowland flooding.
   West of the Rockies, readings were expected to climb to between
115 and 120 degrees in northern parts of the Sacramento Valley.
Temperatures topped 100 degrees over interior California and the
desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61
degrees at Fort Ord to 108 degrees at Redding, both in California.
The nation's low Wednesday morning was 34 degrees at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms to
continue to push slowly eastward and southward, extending from
northern Arizona and the southern Rockies across central and
southern Texas, the lower Mississippi, Tennessee and Ohio valleys
to the East Coast. The showers should be heaviest from Mississippi
and Tennessee across the Appalachians to the mid- and northern
Atlantic states.
   Highs should be in the 70s and 80s in most of the nation from
the Rockies to the East Coast, rising into the 90s along the
southern Atlantic Coast and Gulf Coast. Readings should range into
the 90s and to 105 degrees west of the Rockies, and to 115 in
interior California and the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
