<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MotoristSlain     07-20 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motorist Slain,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sentencing Delayed in Former Highway Patrolman's Murder Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sentencing of a former state highway patrolman
convicted of a motorist's murder was delayed Wednesday to allow the
defense to appeal one aspect of the case, but the judge refused to
grant a new trial.
   Superior Court Judge Richard Huffman postponed until Aug. 3 the
sentencing of Craig Peyer, 38, who was convicted in his second
trial of first-degree murder in the strangulation of a San Diego
State University student.
   Peyer's first trial ended in a deadlocked jury in February.
   Huffman said the postponement gives the defense time to seek
appellate review of a ruling Monday in which he said a reporter
didn't have to answer questions about how he obtained results of
the defendant's lie-detector test.
   The judge rejected all other elements in a defense motion
seeking a new trial for the former California Highway Patrol
officer, as well as a motion to reduce the jury's first-degree
murder finding to second-degree murder.
   Huffman said he rejected the argument by defense attorneys
Robert Grimes and Diane Campbell that the killing may have been an
impulsive act.
   He said the evidence supported the jury's finding that the Dec.
27, 1986, strangulation of Cara Knott, 20, involved premeditation.
Knott was driving from Escondido to her El Cajon home when she was
stopped and directed down an isolated ramp of Interstate 15 and
then killed.
   ``Mr. Peyer had to get a rope,'' Huffman said. ``There's no
reason in this evidence to make me believe that he walked around
with a rope attached to his belt. He had to engage in a conscious
decision _ finding that rope _ and wrap it around that youngster's
neck.''
   As part of their motion for new trial, the attorneys claimed
Huffman erred in several evidentiary rulings involving the
exclusion of potential defense witnesses and the limiting of
testimony by other witnesses. But Huffman said all of his rulings
were justified.
   However, the judge admitted he shared the defense's concerns
about the publication of Peyer's lie-detector test. The test, which
is inadmissible as evidence, reportedly showed Peyer attempted
deception when questioned about Knott's death after his arrest.
   Grimes and Campbell argued the publication of the polygraph
information may have affected Peyer's right to a fair trial.
   The attorneys also said the information may have been leaked to
San Diego Union reporter Jim Okerblom by police or a member of the
prosecution.
   Huffman has said that if that proves to be the case, he would
have to consider granting Peyer a new trial or dismissing the
charge altogether on grounds of prosecutorial misconduct.
   Okerblom's story appeared in The Union during jury selection for
Peyer's second trial. It prompted unusually extensive jury
questioning.
   Okerblom was called to the witness stand Monday but cited
constitutional protections and the state's Shield Law in refusing
to answer questions about the polygraph material, mailed to the
Union anonymously.
   The Shield Law prohibits the state's judges from holding a
reporter in contempt for refusing to identify anonymous sources.
   Grimes said he would petition the 4th District Court of Appeal
to determine the applicability of the Shield Law in the Peyer case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
