<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RKOSettlement     07-20 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-RKO Settlement,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Approves Sale Of Two RKO-Owned Broadcast Stations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission approved
the sale of two broadcast stations owned by RKO and took a major
step in resolving a legal dispute that has lasted more than two
decades.
   The FCC approved a settlement agreement calling for RKO, a
subsidiary of GenCorp. to sell KHJ-TV in Los Angeles and WHBQ-AM
radio in Memphis, Tenn.
   The Los Angeles television station is being sold to Walt Disney
Co., and 70 percent of the Memphis radio station is being sold to
Flinn Broadcasting Corp.
   ``The approval will put the stations in the hands of
indisputably qualified licensees and avoid countless years of
continued litigation before the FCC and the courts,'' the
commission said.
   GenCorp., RKO's parent company, two years ago announced its
desire to get out of the broadcasting business, but its attempt to
sell its stations have been locked in a legal dispute over whether
RKO actually should have the broadcast licenses involved.
   A legal battle dating back to 1965 revolves around the fitness
of RKO to operate the broadcast stations. The FCC in 1980 refused
to renew RKO's license for WNAC-TV in Boston, saying the company
was unqualified to run the station.
   Since then RKO's licenses in other cities have been under
challenge.
   In approving the proposed sale of the Los Angeles television
station and the Memphis radio station, the FCC said, ``The
commission concluded that strong public interest considerations
favored settling these two cases, which are part of the most
burdensome proceedings in the FCC's history.''
   Gen. Corp., which is based in Akron, Ohio, said in a statement
that it welcomed the FCC's decision and that it hoped it would
serve as a model in the sale of RKO's other broadcast stations.
   ``This marks a giant step toward a constructive resolution of 23
years of litigation involving the RKO licenses,'' said GenCorp
chairman A. William Reynolds.
   Under the agreement, RKO receives roughly two-thirds of the
revenue from the sale of KHJ-TV in Los Angeles and WHBQ radio in
Memphis with competing applicants receiving one-third.
   In the case of KHJ-TV, Walt Disney Co., will pay RKO $218.6
million and pay a competing license applicant, Fidelity Television
Inc., $105.4 million. Fidelity ultimately is to be merged into a
subsidiary of Disney.
   In the case of WHBQ in Memphis, Flinn Broadcasting will pay RKO
$525,000 and pay a competing license applicant, First City
Communications Inc., $225,000. First City will then assign the
license of WHBQ to Flinn.
   The same formula is hoped to be used in future FCC approval for
the disposal of 12 other RKO broadcast stations, said GenCorp.
spokesman Rip Tilden.
   Tilden said agreement already has been reached with buyers to
sell two radio stations in Boston (WRKO-AM and WROR-FM) and two
radio stations in the Washington DC area (WGMS-AM and FM) await FCC
approval.
   RKO's other broadcast holdings are a television station, WHBQ-TV
in Memphis, and seven radio stations in New York City (WOR-AM and
WRKS-FM), Los Angeles (KHJ-AM and KRTH-FM), San Francisco
(KFRC-AM), Chicago (WFYR-FM) and Fort Lauderdale, Fla., (WAXY-FM).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
