<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-Riots     07-20 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Riots,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Riots in Southern City, Mobs Destroy Shops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobs destroyed shops and other buildings
late Wednesday in new violence in a southern city after weekend
riots killed one person and injured six others, official state
radio reported.
   The radio gave no casualities, arrests, or other details on the
latest rioting in Prome, about 180 miles north of Rangoon.
   The weekend rioting broke out after a teashop owner and customer
quarreled. The unrest died down Monday after Buddhist monks
appealed for calm.
   On Tuesday, state radio reported that 41 people arrested during
March 18 riots and packed into a prison van died during a two-hour
ride to jail. It said the victims were cremated March 19 and that
the government had delayed release of the news to avoid possible
spread of unrest.
   The victims died from tear-gas exposure and the long period
spent in the overcrowded prison van, the radio said.
   Home Minister U Min Goung took responsibility for the deaths and
resigned, according to the announcement.
   The 41 victims were among 71 people arrested during student
riots in Rangoon.
</TEXT>
