<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     07-20 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Official Says Aquino May Allow U.S. Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino has the
right to allow U.S.nuclear weapons in the country despite a
constitutional provision against such arms, her justice secretary
said in an opinion released Wednesday.
   The legal opinion set the stage for a confrontation between Mrs.
Aquino and Filipino legislators, many of whom oppose the presence
of both nuclear weapons and U.S. military bases.
   In the 19-year-old war with rebels, authorities said at least 17
people were killed in the previous 48 hours in several clashes
across the archipelago.
   Justice Secretary Sedfrey Ordonez said in a four-page opinion
the constitutional provision against nuclear weapons ``must be
viewed as an instrument, rather than an objective, in
treaty-making. If such a policy is not in keeping with the national
interest of the Philippines ... the president may defer from it.''
   The 1986 constitution, written by a commission Mrs. Aquino
appointed, says the nation, ``consistent with the national
interest, adopts and pursues a policy of freedom from nuclear
weapons in its territory.''
   Last month, the Senate overwhelmingly approved a bill banning
nuclear weapons. A similar bill is pending in the House of
Representatives.
   The United States refuses to confirm or deny whether keeping
such weapons at its six bases in the Philippines.
   In April, the United States and the Philippines began a review
of the 1947 Military Bases Agreement, whose current term expires in
1991.
   ``It is my opinion that the president of the Philippines may
negotiate a modification or extension of the military bases
agreement with the U.S., regardless of the provisions therein
pertaining to nuclear weapons,'' Ordonez said in his opinion.
   He presented it Tuesday to a closed meeting of a
legislative-executive panel advising Filipino negotiators in the
bases negotiations.
   His decision means Mrs. Aquino ultimately may have to decide
either to permit nuclear weapons in the face of growing opposition
or risk a confrontation with the United States.
   Washington is her government's major source of military and
economic aid. The United States provides $180 million annually in
economic and military aid in exchange for the bases, but the
Philippine demands have ranged to more than $1.2 billion.
   U.S. officials have said they accept the constitutional
provision but oppose the Senate bill, which they claim would
cripple military operations at Subic Bay naval base, Clark Air Base
and four smaller facilities.
   Sen. Wigberto Tanada, chief sponsor of the anti-nuclear bill and
a prominent opponent of the bases, said the Ordonez opinion ``gives
the president the unconscionable option which is not hers _ to risk
the lives, property and future of our people and our country.''
   Majority floor leader Orlando Mercado, who supported the bill,
told reporters the opinion was not binding on the legislature and
the Supreme Court might ultimately decide the meaning of the
constitutional provision.
   In a report on the war, Press Secretary Teodoro Benigno quoted a
military report as saying at least 1,934 people _ 483 civilians,
904 rebels, and 547 police and soldiers _ had been killed in the
first half of 1988.
   The report was issued two days after leaders of the New People's
Army, the Communist rebel group that began fighting in 1969,
rejected a call by the nation's Roman Catholic bishops for
resumption of peace talks, which broke down in February 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
