<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--Dukakis-ClintonText 1stadd   07-20 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis-Clinton Text, 1st add,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: Andrew Jackson.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The other day a friend of mine back home asked me if I were
really excited about the prospect of Michael Dukakis becoming
president. When I said I was, he said, ``Bill, I can understand why
you think he should be president, but how can you get excited about
a guy who's so clean he squeaks when he walks and who mows his yard
with a hand-powered mower?''
   Well, I thought about it. And I decided that's one reason I was
excited.
   He's old-fashioned all right: he's the kind of man who plays it
straight, keeps his word, and pays his bills.
   In Arkansas, we say he's the kind of man you can ``tie to.''
   Don't misunderstand me. He's not perfect. I have to confess
right here in The Omni, home of the Atlanta Hawks, that he loves
the Boston Celtics. During the playoffs, he even watched them while
making campaign phone calls.
   Still, I think Michael Dukakis should be president because he
has the character, the record, and the vision America needs at this
moment in our journey. And Michael Dukakis should be president
because he is the right man for our times.
   His character is steadfast and consistent. He wakes up in the
same world every day, a trait of no small importance in a president.
   I have found him self-confident, but willing to listen to other
people. That's a lesson he and I learned the hard way _ we got beat
over the head with it. Both of us were elected, defeated, then
given a rare second chance by our people. That does wonders for
your sensitivity to others and their views.
   Mike and I met after our defeats. He was teaching at the Kennedy
School and I was the youngest ex-governor in American history. I
was struck even then by his lack of bitterness, his eagerness to
learn, and his continuing, genuine commitment to public life, in or
out of office.
   As someone who's worked with him on hard issues in the National
Governor's Association, who's hammered out compromises with him,
disagreed with him, and fought battles by his side, I can tell you
one thing: when he needs to be, Michael Dukakis is tough as nails.
   Of course, if he hadn't been tough, he never could have come
back from his defeat. When that happens to most people, they pull
the shades, rip the phone off the wall, and pack it in. Not Mike
Dukakis. He hangs in there.
</TEXT>
