<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Airliner, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0823,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Expresses `Distress' Over Airliner Downing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Iranian ambassador not
satisfied, says US must pay Tehran, hints at legal action; edits to
conform and delete extraneous material. PICKS up 15th graf pvs
bgng, Diplomats said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council unanimously adopted a
mild resolution on Wednesday expressing ``deep distress'' over the
U.S. downing of an Iranian airliner, which killed 290 people.
   The council also urged that a U.N. cease-fire and peace plan
quickly be put into effect in the Iran-Iraq war, which began in
September 1980.
   After days of negotiations, the 15-member council adopted a
watered-down document that would satisfy both America and Iran and
not provoke a U.S. veto.
   But Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati later told
reporters, ``I am not satisfied. We expected the resolution would
play a more important role in bringing security to civil aviation.''
   He added there were ``some positive elements'' in the
resolution, citing the call for stricter observance of
international regulations on safety of civil aviation.
   Mahallati also objected to the U.S. offer of compensation to
families of the victims of airliner incident. The United States has
said no payment will go to Tehran, with which it has no diplomatic
relations.
   ``The United States is obliged to pay compensations, not only to
the families but to the government,'' Mahallati said in answer to a
question. ``I don't think we shall accept anything which is below
what the United States is obliged to do.
   He said that if the United States fails to pay Tehran, ``there
are other measures the United Nations should consider.''
   It could take the case to the International Court of Justice.
   The USS Vincennes shot down the Iran Air Airbus over the Persian
Gulf on July 3. The United States said the missile cruiser mistook
the passenger jet for an attacking Iranian warplane.
   The Security Council action came one year to the day after it
unanimously adopted Resolution 598, demanding an immediate
cease-fire and troop withdrawal in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Iran had requested the council session after boycotting the body
for eight years. It returned to urge condemnation of the downing of
the airliner and demand withdrawal of all U.S. forces from the
waterway.
   But Iran was unable to muster enough votes to condemn the United
States.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters said the resolution puts the
Airbus disaster in ``proper perspective'' and said the conflict in
the gulf must end. He told the council: ``The Airbus accident is
only part of a much larger human tragedy: the Iran-Iraq war.''
   He said the United States welcomes Iran's announcement that it
fully accepts Resolution 598 and said, ``Now a large obstacle has
been overcome.''
   Walters said, ``We intend to stick with our effective gulf
policy ... Once tensions decrease and the treat to Western
interests dissipates, then the level of our naval presence will
naturally be reduced.''
   He said the U.S. naval presence ``is a force for peace ... in
support of regional states whose interests and those of the West
face a very real threat.''
   Diplomats said the council deleted controversial passages to
ensure passage of the brief resolution. It erased a sentence
proposed by Iran calling on foreign naval forces to reassess their
presence in the gulf and eliminated a U.S. call for freedom of
navigation. It deleted strong language of condemnation to avoid a
U.S. veto.
   The resolution said the council ``expresses its deep distress at
the downing of an Iranian civil aircraft by a missile fired from a
U.S. warship and profound regret over the tragic loss of innocent
lives.''
   It urged all parties to the Chicago Convention of 1944 on
international civil aviation to fully observe all rules and
practices concerning safety of civilian aircraft.
   The resolution also said the council ``stresses the need for a
full and rapid implementation of its resolution 598 of 1987, as the
only basis for a comprehensive, just, honorable and durable
settlement of the conflict between Iran and iraq.''
   It reaffirmed support for Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar in implementating the resolution, which calls for a
cease-fire, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange, impartial body to
determine the aggressor and a comprehensive peace settlement
   Council members are the United States, the Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China _ the five permanent members with veto
power _ and Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Japan, Nepal,
Senegal, West Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
