<HEAD>Deaf Church Janitor Arraigned On Kidnapping Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 graf to UPDATE with arraignment, higher bail,
comments from prosecutor, charge changing from attempted kidnapping
to kidnapping in third case. Picks up 4th graf pvs `Officers
found...' Subs next-to-last graf with one graf to conform.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deaf church janitor who was ``more
at ease with kids than with adults'' was arraigned Wednesday on
charges of kidnapping three young girls and keeping one in a dirt
crawl space for as long as six weeks.
   Kenneth Alvin Michel, 32, did not enter a plea after Municipal
Court Judge John Stroud advised him of the charges and appointed a
public defender to represent him.
   Michel, using sign language and head nods to speak through an
interpreter, said he had only $1,400 to pay legal fees.
   The judge set bail at $1 million and said he would consider a
motion by the district attorney's office to deny bail at an Aug. 9
hearing.
   Deputy District Attorney Ken Peterson said Michel could face
more than 35 years in prison if convicted. He said his office was
still evaluating evidence to determine whether to file additional
charges.
   Michel was arrested Monday at the United Methodist Church in
suburban Elk Grove, where he was a part-time custodian. Police said
they traced the license plate on a car that was allegedly involved
in a kidnapping incident earlier in the day.
   Officers found two missing girls at the church. Five-year-old
Muey Han Saefong was kidnapped Monday in Sacramento and was found
in the back of Michel's car, her mouth taped and legs bound, police
said.
   Four-year-old Candi Talarico, who was kidnapped June 4 while
playing outside her apartment, was found in an L-shaped space under
the altar, police said.
   Officers said the space had a dirt floor, concrete walls and a
wooden ceiling. It was furnished with blankets, stuffed animals,
books, food, lights, a television and newspapers that contained
articles about the kidnapping, which was featured on Fox
Broadcasting Co.'s ``America's Most Wanted'' TV program.
   Muey and Candi were examined at a hospital after their rescue
and returned to their parents.
   At a news conference Tuesday, the church's pastor, Linda Inlow,
said it was doubtful anyone would have heard Candi if she had
yelled for help.
   She said that Candi was kept in a 7-by-9-by-3 foot space under a
crawl space floor. She said Michel apparently cut a hole in the
floor to gain access to another space that extended three or four
more feet below.
   Friends and relatives have described Michel as a gentle man who
loved children but was lonely and had trouble communicating because
of a speech handicap.
   ``He was very, very protective of kids,'' said H.F. Frost, who
lived next door for several years. ``If one of my grandkids got out
in the street, he'd run out and grab them. He was more at ease with
kids than with adults. He took to them. He played with them by the
hour.''
   The Rev. David Delaplane, an adviser to Inlow, said Michel was
placed on leave of absence last spring by a day care center where
he also worked.
   Delaplane said that some children had teased Michel because of
his disabilities and that Michel ``reacted out of frustration'' and
pinched them. The day care center leased space from the church.
   Michel is accused of kidnapping Muey, Candi and 6-year-old Daisy
Jones, who was abducted Monday morning in Elk Grove but escaped
moments later. Peterson said prosecutors felt Daisy had been in
Michel's possession long enough to warrant filing charges of
kidnapping instead of attempted kidnapping.
   Sgt. Bob Burns said a witness got the license number of the car
used. The witness said he was driving to work when saw a man
running down a busy street with a screaming child in his arms. The
girl broke free.
</TEXT>
