<2ND_LINE>AM-Inmate Escapes,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Escapes in Superintendent's Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted police killer escaped
Wednesday from a prison by driving away in the prison
superintendent's car armed with the superintendent's shotgun,
authorities said.
   Earl R. Jacobs, 51, was discovered missing from the Chillicothe
Correctional Institution during a prison count shortly before 11
a.m., said Lynn Goff, personnel officer at the prison.
   She said Jacobs entered Superintendent Arthur Tate Jr.'s
unoccupied and unlocked home on the prison grounds, then took the
car keys and a shotgun owned by Tate before escaping in Tate's car.
   The car was parked outside his house at the time it was taken.
Ms. Goff said Jacobs was not supposed to be in the area around the
house and that officials were alarmed by the discovery that he has
a weapon.
   ``We're really, really concerned about that,'' she said.
   Jacobs had been in jail since he was 25, when he was sentenced
to life in prison for killing a police officer in Logan County in
1962. He was classified as a minimum-security prisoner, Ms. Goff
said, which means he was allowed to work unsupervised on the
prison's honor farm outside the prison compound.
   ``He was a minimum-security prisoner, so he was obviously not
considered a real threat,'' said Ms. Goff. ``But any escaped felon
should be considered dangerous.''
</TEXT>
