<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-USMissiles     07-20 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-US Missiles,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors Count U.S. Missiles in Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to restore paragraph indentation between 1st and
2nd grafs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENHAM COMMON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet inspectors counted U.S.
nuclear missiles in Britain Wednesday under the historic superpower
treaty to eliminate an entire class of such weapons. But they want
to see the Tower of London, too.
   ``At the beginning of the inspection they requested a
sight-seeing visit to London,'' Defense Ministry spokesman Martin
Helm said Wednesday.
   ``Clearly there's no provision in the INF (intermediate-range
nuclear forces) Treaty for the inspectors and air crew to move off
base. But we will be pleased to arrange a trip to make the visit
enjoyable,'' he added.
   So Thursday will be sight-seeing day for the 20 Soviet
inspectors.
   The inspectors flew in Tuesday from Moscow to make their checks
at Greenham Common airbase, 50 miles west of London; and at
Britain's other cruise missile base, Molesworth, near Cambridge.
Both bases are run by the U.S. military.
   The checks are part of a 60-day period of inspections that
started July 1 to verify whether each side told the truth about
deployments. The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States
and five Western European countries. U.S. inspectors are visiting
133 sites in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe. No violations
have been reported thus far.
   A group of 20 U.S. missile experts on Wednesday ended their
inspections of installations in East Germany, the official East
German news agency ADN said.
   It said the Americans split into two groups to inspect four
former Soviet missile sites in Waren, Bischofswerda, Wokul and
Koenigsbrueck, East Germany.
   Also Wednesday, the official Czechoslovak news agency CTK said
the government granted permission for U.S. experts to inspect a
former missile base at Hranice, central Czechoslovakia, under the
INF treaty. It said the 10 Americans will arrive Thursday.
   The INF treaty, signed in December, provides for elimination
within three years of all land-based missiles in Europe with ranges
of 300 to 3,000 miles. The Soviet inspectors began their checks in
Britain at noon Wednesday, splitting up into two teams to visit
both bases.
   Under the U.S.-Soviet treaty, which provided for unprecedented
review of each other's facilities, each inspection can last up to
24 hours, with a possible eight-hour extension.
   The Soviets, who gave the required 16 hours notice of arrival
and declared formally Wednesday morning what they wanted to see,
may take four hours to write their reports after inspections.
   The inspections at Greenham Common, with 96 working missiles,
and Molesworth, with 16, are the first in Britain.
   The ground-hugging, difficult-to-detect cruise missiles, which
provide a vehicle for the warheads, and their 55-foot mobile
launchers are housed in bunkers. The Soviets will not see the
warheads, which carry the explosive material, because the warheads
do not have to be destroyed under the treaty.
   The Soviet inspectors were staying in specially converted
barracks.
   Entertainment to date consisted of a bus tour of the Greenham
base Tuesday evening and a visit to an on-base gift shop, the U.S.
military said.
   But on Thursday, after being cooped up under tight security with
geiger counters, tape measures, missiles, and mobile launchers, the
Soviets will do some fancy sight-seeing.
   The Defense Ministry said that among the tourist attractions the
Soviets will view is the Royal Tournament, held each summer at the
Earls Court Exhibition Center in west London _ a spectacular
display by Britain's armed forces of massed bands, gymnastics and
show-jumping.
   U.S. and British military officers will accompany them.
   The Soviet inspectors were expected to return to Greenham for
the night before leaving Friday, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--Dukakis-ClintonText 4thadd   07-20 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis-Clinton Text, 4th add,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: our party.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   But at this time in our history, Michael Dukakis is THE man for
America.
   The post-World War II era, when America dominated the world,
economically, politically, and militarily, is over. For the rest of
our lives we will have to compete with people in other countries
for new jobs, new business opportunities, and technological
breakthroughs. As we have learned painfully in the last decade, we
won't win if we're not prepared.
   The Republicans' main claim to the White House this year is that
in the face of competition and adversity, the administration
produced a five-year recovery. Well, that recovery left a lot of
people and places behind, was financed by a sea of borrowed money,
and ignored or aggravated, some harsh realities: the rise of huge
budget and trade deficits; the loss of our competitive position in
low-wage, low-skill, and import sensitive industries, in
agriculture, energy and mining, and in some high-tech areas too;
the growth of a vast new class of poor people, most of them young
women and their little children; an epidemic of social problems;
and a decline in real wages.
   Left unattended, these difficulties could threaten not only our
children's future, but our own.
   In the first half of the 1980s, for the first time in my
lifetime, only 40 percent of our people had an increase in their
incomes, while 20 percent stood still, and 40 percent actually
suffered a reduction in real wages. We used to believe a rising
economic tide lifts all boats. Today's tide is drowning four in 10
of our people who have fallen off the boat, and the Republican crew
won't even throw a life raft to the women and children.
   There are those who see these developments as evidence that our
nation is in decline. Best-selling books predict a downhill slide
that we either cannot or will not stop.
   Michael Dukakis doesn't believe that for a minute. He believes
America's best days lie ahead. He reminds us that we've faced even
greater challenges in the past. He is an apostle of hope.
   Last night when Jesse Jackson gave that awesome, wonderful
speech, many of you waved signs with his slogan: ``Keep Hope
Alive.'' In his own way, Mike Dukakis will never let us forget that
admonition. We all must be apostles of hope. As the scripture says:
Let us not grow weary in doing good, for in due season we shall
reap, if we do not lose heart.
</TEXT>
