<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--Dukakis-ClintonText 5thadd   07-20 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis-Clinton Text, 5th add,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: lose heart.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is a builder who wants to build a bridge to
tomorrow: Strong enough to carry our heaviest load; wide enough for
all of us to walk across together; long enough to take us into the
2lst century.
   He's got a big job to do. And we have to help him. His economic
challenge is to reduce our debt; to nourish our entrepreneurs and
small business people who create most of our jobs; to promote new
relationships between business and labor in which risk, loss, and
gain are shared; to reduce the scandalous waste of money consumed
by hostile mergers and takeovers that cost jobs; to get much more
cooperation from our major competitors in Europe and Japan in
making economic and defense policies; to fight for a fair trading
system that gives us the chance to sell more as well as buy more;
and to reduce the debt of the developing nations in Latin America
whose futures are so tightly bound to our own.
   This is an ambitious agenda, but Michael Dukakis has great
ambitions for America.
   Yet, even if he carries it off, America still could be in
trouble.
   Why? Because compared to all the world's major economic powers,
we do the worst job of developing our most precious resource _ our
people.
   We let more babies die than others do. A child born in Costa
Rica has a better chance of living to be a year old than one born
tonight in our nation's capital.
   We stand by while more of our children have children than others
do, swelling the number of our ``truly disadvantaged.''
   We accept far more adult illiteracy than others do, though we
know 80 percent of the work force in the year 2000 will be composed
of people who are already working and that sooner or later our
workers' inability to read will catch up with them and catch up
with us.
   We tolerate more homeless children than others do, degrading the
most blameless among us.
   We live in the only advanced country that's still in the Dark
Ages when it comes to child care.
   Our school dropout rates are more than twice those of our major
competitors.
</TEXT>
