<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--Dukakis-ClintonText 6thadd   07-20 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis-Clinton Text, 6th add,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: major competitors.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   When our kids do get out of school, they have about two years
less learning than young people in Germany and Japan who are
competing for those good jobs Mike Dukakis wants them to have.
   A lot of our young people want to go on to college, but can't
afford to, so they go right to work in a tough world economy that
pays young unskilled workers 25 to 40 percent less than 15 years
ago.
   What's all this got to do with you if you're not poor, your kids
are in college, you have a job, and your company's doing fine?
   I'll tell you what _ all these people in trouble are growing as
a percent of our population. If they can't do the jobs of today and
tomorrow, we'll all be in trouble.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he knows we don't
have a single person to waste.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he cares that one
in four of our children under 5 is living in poverty and that
without good child health programs and preschool for those who need
it, we are cheating their future _ and ours.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he understands
that today it costs a middle-class family much more of its income
to send a child to college than it did when he and I went a
generation ago, and that government has to help make up the
difference.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he knows one big
reason hundred of thousands of parents and children are homeless is
that this administration has cut government housing starts by 800
percent since 1980.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president because he feels the pain
of a mother who leaves for work every day worried sick about her
children not being in a good affordable day care center, partly due
to the government's feeble efforts in child care.
   I want Michael Dukakis to be president, not just because he
knows and cares about these problems, but because he's tackled them
in his state, and he's proved _ time and again _ that he can make a
difference in people's lives.
   When the Republicans gather in New Orleans next month, they'll
talk about these family problems too. They'll feature some of their
good governors. Just remember, they had the White House for eight,
long years and did nothing.
</TEXT>
