<HEAD>Arizona Delegates Complain About Cartoon Depiction of Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona delegates to the Democratic National
Convention reacted angrily Wednesday to what they said was a racist
political cartoon in the Phoenix Gazette making fun of Jesse
Jackson's presidential bid.
   The cartoon showed a miniature likeness of Jackson, dressed in
the garb of an Old South stable hand and holding out a ring used
for tethering horses. Jackson is poised in front of
plantation-style White House where Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis is telling his wife: ``Well Kitty, I think we've found a
spot for Jesse.''
   Sixty members of the Arizona contingent, including 53 of the 55
delegates and alternates, had signed a letter to the editor by the
time the convention resumed Wednesday night. The letter said the
cartoon portrayed Arizona as a ``haven for racism'' and demanded an
apology from the newspaper.
   Larry Ferguson, a Gazette editorial writer who approved the
cartoon, defended it as ``reasonable comment for a cartoonist'' and
said no apology was warranted.
   Stanley Lubin, a Dukakis alternate from Phoenix who drafted the
petition, called the cartoon an ``insensitive piece of journalism.''
   ``If they politically don't like what we're doing, that's
fine,'' he added. ``If they don't like Jesse Jackson, that's fine.
But to depict Jesse Jackson as slave in front of a plantation is
disgusting.''
   Ferguson said cartoonist Len Borozinski is given a great deal of
latitude in what he draws and that ``all cartoonists have weird
minds.''
   ``He put himself in Dukakis' place,'' Ferguson said. ``He sees
Dukakis as having slighted Jesse and that Dukakis would really like
to see the Reverend Jackson someplace other than his present
position.''
</TEXT>
