<HEAD>Lawyer: Bible College Enrollment Down 72 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Enrollment at the Bible college named
for defrocked Assemblies of God minister Jimmy Swaggart will drop
72 percent this year, but the school will proceed with plans to
open a theological seminary, an attorney said.
   Enrollment at Jimmy Swaggart Bible College on Aug. 29 will be
about 400, compared with 1,451 students last year, attorney William
Treeby said Wednesday. The estimate is based on the number of
students who have registered and the inquiries from potential
students.
   The seminary will open with 12 students.
   ``We've just started to promote the Bible college through the
television program and have received a lot of calls,'' Treeby said.
``We'll have room for more. We'll know more when classes start.''
   Some faculty and students left the school after Swaggart was
defrocked following his confession to unspecified sins. Debra
Murphree, an admitted prostitute, said she posed naked for Swaggart
in a New Orleans-area motel.
