<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IrishCourtShooting     07-20 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish Court Shooting,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Serving Life for Mountbatten Killing Fires Gun in Courthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA man serving life for the 1979
assassination of Earl Mountbatten fired a gun in a Dublin
courthouse Wednesday _ hitting no one _ and then won a damage suit
against his prison warden.
   Police said Thomas McMahon, 40, pulled out a gun while being
held in a second-floor cell in Dublin's High Court and fired one
shot that struck a wall before two guards overpowered him.
   McMahon was later escorted to courtroom No. 1 for the hearing of
his suit against the warden of Portlaoise Prison. The prisoner
asked for compensation for what he said was a broken wrist suffered
during a strip search in 1983.
   After 1{ hours deliberation, the jury found for McMahon and
awarded him $5,950. McMahon showed no emotion as he was rushed out
of the courtroom and back to jail.
   The suit was against the warden in his capacity as an employee
of the Irish state.
   A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it
was not clear how McMahon acquired the weapon. Screening of the
public was abandoned at the court years ago, he said.
   McMahon, of Carrickmacross in County Monaghan, has been serving
a life term at the high-security prison since his conviction in
November 1979.
   Mountbatten, a World War II hero, cousin of Queen Elizbaeth II
and the last British viceroy of India, was killed Aug. 27, 1979, in
a bomb blast aboard his yacht off northwest Ireland. Three other
people also died in the bombing.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army said it carried out the
killing as part of its campaign to oust the British from Northern
Ireland and reunite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
