<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--CarterParty     07-20 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Carter Party,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Party Brings Out Old Friends And Memories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Carter threw a party for his former White
House staffers Wednesday, and 400 of them showed up to eat, drink
and talk about old times on the Potomac.
   ``It's not everyday you can get Jimmy Carter to buy you a
drink,'' said former press secretary Jody Powell, who now works for
an advertising agency in Washington.
   The lavishly catered reception was held at the Carter
Presidential Center, some four miles east of the site of the
Democrats National Convention.
   ``We're just here to have a good time, not talk politics,''
Carter told reporters who attempted to gauge his feelings about
events at the convention, where Michael Dukakis was being chosen as
this year's nominee. Carter received a warm response when he
addressed the convention Monday night.
   ``It's so great to see all these people,'' said Rosalynn Carter
as she and her husband circulated separately through the crowd.
``I've talked to people I haven't seen in years.''
   Others those who showed up to munch and mingle were former Sen.
Edmund Muskie of Maine, who served an eight-month stint as
secretary of State under Carter and former budget director Bert
Lance.
   Walter Mondale, Carter's vice president, didn't attend the
party. Neither did Hamilton Jordan, his former chief of staff,
whose mother reportedly is seriously ill.
   Muskie recalled his tenure in the Carter administration with
mixed emotions.
   ``It was a damned good time,'' said the former Maine senator,
who now practices law in Washington. ``But my outstanding memory is
of the Iranian hostage crisis; I just wish we could have gotten the
hostages out earlier, even a few days sooner might have made a
difference in the 1980 election.''
   But those who did come, including dozens of fellow Georgians,
showered the Carters with affection. The former president obviously
was delighted as he hugged, kissed and chatted with the small army
of friends and well-wishers, some of whom proffered photographs and
copies of his new trout fishing book to be signed.
   ``This is great,'' he said repeatedly.
   Muskie smiled as he watched Carter circulate through the crowd.
   ``It's evident his star is on the rise,'' he said. ``From now
on, I think, `you'll see a different attitude about his presidency
and about him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
