<1ST_LINE>u p BC-CVN--Dukakis-ClintonText 9thadd   07-20 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CVN--Dukakis-Clinton Text, 9th add,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ATLANTA: children's tomorrow.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   I had a college professor who taught me that the key to
America's success over more than 200 years is that our people have
always believed the future can be better than the present, and that
each individual has a personal, moral responsibility to make it so.
He said we were in college because our parents preferred our future
to their own present. He said, ``As long as the American people
prefer their children's future to their present, we're going to be
all right, but if we ever reach the point where they don't, we've
had it, and don't you ever forget it.''
   Michael Dukakis won't ever forget it. His whole life is a
tribute to the enduring strength of the American dream. He knows
that unless that dream is real for all our children, it is not
secure for any of them. And he'll help us seize the future and make
it ours.
   In November, when Michael Dukakis is elected president, we will
observe the 25th anniversary of President Kennedy's death.
   But Mike's victory will be a tribute to the life and legacy of
John Kennedy, to the boundless optimism, the grace, the courage,
and the sheer joy with which he urged us forward.
   The great Israeli statesman, Abba Eban, began his memorial
tribute to President Kennedy with this simple, stirring statement,
``Tragedy is the difference between what is and what might have
been.''
   Michael Dukakis has spent his entire public life closing the gap
between what is and what might have been. That is why he should be
president of the United States.
   And so my fellow Democrats, I proudly place into nomination the
name of the man who will become the 4lst president of' the United
States, Michael Dukakis.
</TEXT>
