<HEAD>Widow of Civil Rights Leader Praises Jackson, Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. told
Democrats Wednesday night they have made real the dreams her late
husband voiced in the civil rights march on Washington 25 years ago.
   ``This is what the dream is all about,'' Coretta Scott King told
more than 4,000 cheering delegates to the Democratic National
Convention _ nearly 30 percent of them supporters of former King
aide Jesse Jackson.
   ``Jesse, Martin would be proud of you and we are proud of you,
by the way you have broadened and expanded the base of political
power in America,'' she proclaimed. ``So many who were formerly
locked out are now locked in.''
   But Mrs. King said many of the dreams her husband voiced in his
1983 speech remain unfulfilled.
   ``Something is still wrong when 32 million Americans are living
in poverty in the richest nation on the face of the earth ... when
nearly 13 million of them are children,'' she said.
   Appealing to Democrats not to abandon them, she said it would be
a tragic mistake to ``attract the haves to any party at the expense
of the have nots.'
   Mrs. King also praised Michael Dukakis for conducting his
campaign for the party's presidential nomination on a
``consistently high plane and spirit.''
