<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-HowardBaker     07-20 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Howard Baker,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says He Wouldn't Refuse No. 2 Spot On GOP Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House chief of staff Howard
Baker said Tuesday he doesn't want to be vice president, but he
would accept the Republican nomination for the job if asked.
   The idea of returning to Washington as vice president ``sounds
like somebody trying to revoke my parole,'' Baker told the
Asheville Citizen. He resigned his White House job earlier this
year.
   But Baker said he wouldn't turn down an offer from Vice
President George Bush to take the No. 2 slot on the ticket.
   ``If he caught me and asked me point blank to do it, I would do
it,'' Baker said. ``But before he caught me, I would make an
athletic effort to escape. ... I really don't want to be the vice
presidential candidate.''
   Baker met with reporters briefly after addressing about 400
institutional investors at a seminar at a local hotel. His speech _
for which he reportedly received $30,000 _ was closed to the press.
   Before coming to the White House, Baker served as minority and
majority leader during his 18 years as a U.S. senator from
Tennessee.
   ``I really think that Vice President Bush has some awfully good
men to choose from,'' Baker said. ``He certainly hasn't asked me
and I don't expect he will.''
   Other nominees who might be available to Bush include Illinois
Gov. Richard Thompson, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
former United Nations Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick, Baker said.
   Baker rejected arguments that Bush should choose a Southerner to
join him on the ticket because Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis picked Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as his running
mate.
   ``I think politics is not a chess game; you don't move and
countermove,'' Baker said. ``I think instead, Vice President Bush
needs to find somebody ... he's compatible with, somebody who's a
good campaigner, somebody who will bring something to the ticket.''
   Although he had high praise for Bentsen, Baker said his
selection will not make a major difference in the presidential
campaign.
   ``I think it's good from the Democratic side. I think that Lloyd
Bentsen is a very capable person, very attractive person,'' Baker
said.
   ``It's a pretty obvious strategy by Governor Dukakis to reach
out to the South and also to give the impression of moving to the
middle, but I don't think it's going to matter much,'' Baker said.
   ``People don't vote for the vice presidential candidate, they
vote for the presidential candidate,'' he said. ``How the South
responds to Michael Dukakis is going to depend almost entirely on
what Dukakis says, not what Bentsen says.''
</TEXT>
