<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0775 07-20 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0775,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Plans to Watch Nomination on TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 3 grafs new with nomination; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
``Dukakis had xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael S. Dukakis and his family watched on
television from their hotel room as he was nominated for president
Wednesday night, and then awaited the roll call that would award
him the Democratic prize.
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, declaring Dukakis has ``the
character, the record and the vision'' to be president, formally
nominated his friend and fellow Democratic governor in a speech to
delegates at the Democratic National Convention.
   ``He hasn't just played with issues, he's wrestled them to the
ground,'' said Clinton.
   Dukakis had the delegate strength to assure his nomination on
the traditional roll call of the states.
   ``I'm a very lucky guy,'' Dukakis said during a surprise
appearance at a luncheon honoring his wife, Kitty.
   He recalled how, when he and his wife arrived in the convention
city Sunday, he turned to her and said, ``I think it's for real.''
   Also on his schedule for the day of his nomination were a check
of the podium from which he will deliver his acceptance speech
Thursday, a discussion of drugs with children, a luncheon at the
Georgia governor's mansion and a meeting with his only remaining
rival, Jesse Jackson.
   Nineteen Democratic governors, including the host, Gov. Joe
Frank Harris of Georgia, attended the luncheon. Among those who
couldn't be there was Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas, who was to
deliver the speech placing Dukakis in nomination. Clinton's wife,
Hilary, attended the lunch.
   Ron Brown, Jackson's convention manager, said the meeting with
Jackson was at Dukakis' request and was to discuss Jackson's role
in the fall campaign against Vice President George Bush, the
Republican nominee-to-be.
   After the meeting, Jackson said it was ``a get-acquainted
session for staff and key policy advisers, most of whom do not know
each other, but now must work together since we are in the same
boat with a common objective _ that is, to win in November.''
   Dukakis began his day of triumph with a telephone call to
Jackson to congratulate him on his speech to the convention Tuesday
night.
   He told the luncheon that, ``I thought when I watched Jesse
Jackson and I watched those five incredible kids of his ... how
lucky we are for the families we have.''
   Aides said Dukakis told Jackson he thought his speech was
``terrific.''
   The Kitty Dukakis luncheon was under way in the Fox Theater in
downtown Atlanta when her husband showed up.
   Mrs. Dukakis looked genuinely surprised when he walked on stage.
She turned to him and the couple hugged.
   ``I don't have to tell you, I'm blessed with a wonderful,
wonderful spouse,'' he told the crowd.
   He joked about how many people told him they supported him for
president, but liked her better.
   He said a woman in North Carolina told him she had his support
``because your wife smokes,'' a habit of which the governor openly
disapproves.
   He added, ``I don't have to tell you what kind of first lady
she's going to be _ a non-smoking first lady.''
   Standing in shortsleeves in the dusty playground of the Conyers
and Gwinett County Boys Club, Dukakis told children ranging from
elementary school to high school age that ``I don't have to tell
any of you, one of the most serious problems we face is drug and
alcohol abuse.''
   Mrs. Dukakis told the children of her 26-year addiction to diet
pills, which she started taking on the advice of a physician.
   ``The words I want to say to you are, `Don't start,''' she said.
   When the Boys Club official who introduced Dukakis thanked the
governor for taking time away from his busy schedule, Dukakis
responded, ``The problem with being a candidate is they never let
you out of the hotel room. So this is a joy to me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
