<HEAD>ATLANTA: short years.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   He has forced new issues, and new ways of thinking about old
issues, into public view and the political dialogue.
   He rejects economic violence in favor of an economic bill of
rights for all, not just the privileged few.
   He condemns corporate merger maniacs and extols the virtues of
corporate accountability and responsibility not only into the
community, but the nation as well.
   He champions worker rights as an individual human right.
   He would replace wage discrimination with comparable worth.
   He sees collective bargaining as indispensable to industrial
democracy.
   His brilliant industrial policy _ both domestic and global in
purpose and vision _ includes a fair labor standards policy.
   And not since Hubert H. Humphrey has a presidential candidate
elevated the aspirations of workers and championed their quest for
worker rights to such heights in the mainstream of the political
dialogue.
   I have personally witnessed his intelligence, his skills, his
courage in confronting the challenge of labor and corporate
conflict.
   He was there in Wisconsin at Cudahy with the packinghouse
workers.
   And he was there with the members of my own union at Rome Cable
in the bitter cold of an early upstate New York winter.
   He has supported the struggle of Eastern Airline workers against
Texas Air and Frank Lorenzo.
</TEXT>
