<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--Kerry     07-20 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Kerry,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Senator Scores GOP on Ethics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Kerry condemned the ``moral darkness of
the Reagan-Bush administration'' Wednesday and told delegates to
the Democratic National Convention it was time for ``a government
of laws and not of law-breakers.''
   Kerry, a freshman senator from Massachusetts, the home state of
Michael Dukakis, promised that in a Dukakis administration, ``the
government that makes the laws will not break the law.
   ``And in the America of Jesse Jackson,'' he said, ``the
government that says no to drugs will not say yes to General
Noriega.''
   ``It is time that we once again had a government of laws and not
of law-breakers. It's time we had an attorney general of the United
States who is an agent of justice and not the target of criminal
investigation,'' Kerry declared.
   The liberal Democrat raised the ethics issue two days after a
special prosecutor released a long-awaited report on Attorney
General Edwin Meese III saying the nation's top law enforcement
official ``probably'' violated federal law in his personal finances
but committed no crimes in the Wedtech scandal.
   Kerry also scored the Reagan administration _ and, by
implication, Vice President Bush _ for allowing a ``two-bit
dictator'' like Panama's Gen. Manuel Noriega to peddle drugs, for
planning an ``illegal war'' in Central America and for plotting to
sell arms to Iran.
   Kerry made no mention of ethical questions encountered by some
prominent Democrats. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, Dukakis' choice
for a running mate, backed off a plan to invite lobbyists to pay
$10,000 each to have breakfast with him. And House Speaker Jim
Wright is under scrutiny by the House Ethics Committee because of
questions about royalties on a book.
   The invitation to speak on ethics was a political plum for
Kerry, who served as lieutenant governor under Dukakis until his
election to the Senate in 1984. Kerry, 44, now chairs the
Democratic Senate Campaign Committee, the party's fund-raising arm
for the 1988 Senate races.
   Kerry was originally to have delivered the speech Tuesday night,
but the proceedings were running late and so it was rescheduled for
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
