07-20 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Sealed Convention, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0946,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention Hall Closed Shortly Before Candidate Nominations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th graf pvs bgng, `A delegate,' to
UPDATE with congressman listing some colleagues who were kept out
of Omni</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities closed the overcrowded Omni
convention arena for the second straight night Wednesday as
Democrats prepared to nominate Michael Dukakis as their 1988
presidential candidate.
   ``This building has been closed by order of the fire marshal,''
state police Officer L.J. Robinson announced at 9:03 p.m. More than
a dozen police officers stood in front of one entrance to enforce
the closure.
   The Democratic National Committee said in a statement that it
concurred with the decision ``in the interest of safety of all
those in the hall.''
   Several delegates were caught outside the hall, including Ann
Richards, the Texas state treasurer who delivered the convention's
keynote speech Monday night, and some members of Congress: Reps.
Peter Rodino of New Jersey, and Les Aspin and Gerald Kleczka of
Wisconsin.
   ``There was no hassle at all,'' said Ms. Richards. ``I came late
and the hall was full. No they'll do the count, and we'll see what
we'll see. If I don't get in, we'll watch it on television.''
   ``It's a little bit of a consternation,'' said Rodino.
Chuckling, he added, ``And I'm a super delegate.''
   Aspin said being kept out of the hall was ``no big deal. I
wouldn't worry about it. I think Dukakis will make it without me.''
   Kleczka commented, ``I'm not upset, but we're going to have to
talk to a supervisor here because I'm an at-large delegate and an
alternate can't vote for me. If I don't get in, Wisconsin is one
vote short.''
   Also caught on the outside were Bert Lance and his wife,
LaBelle, and former Wisconsin Gov. Pat Lucey. Lance, who was
director of the Office of Management and Budget under President
Carter, has been a key adviser to Jesse Jackson in this year's
campaign
   ``If Pete Rodino and Les Aspin are on the outside, I'm with
them,'' Lance said.
   A delegate walking by him muttered, ``If he can't get in, nobody
can.'' The delegate declined to give her name.
   Rep. Robert Garcia of New York said he barely made it into the
hall, but that a number of his colleagues did not, including Sen.
J. Bennett Johnston of Louisiana and Reps. Paul Kanjorski of
Pennsylvania, Jim Slattery of Kansas and Brian Donnelly of
Masssachusetts.
   Although there were some chants at one gate of ``Let the
delegates in'' and ``We shall overcome,'' the mood generally was
good-natured, unlike Tuesday night when some tempers had flared.
   Mrs. Lance spent the time outdoors buying a convention button
from a vendor.
   The vendor, Tony Lyons, said, ``It's a great tribute to the
Democratic process that senators and congressmen are waiting out
here with the common man.''
   Atlanta Fire Chief William H. Hamer had said earlier Wednesday
that officials would not hesitate to seal the Democratic convention
arena again if it were crowded beyond capacity.
   Democratic National Committee officials said Wednesday night
that they had two counters at each entrance to monitor the flow of
traffic in and out of the building.
   Up to 1,000 angry convention-goers confronted security officials
Tuesday night when The Omni reached capacity just before Jesse
Jackson's speech, spurring fire officials to seal the building.
   Asked about the potential of closing the hall again during
Wednesday's session, Hamer was clear that he wouldn't hesitate to
do so.
   ``We have to, that's the law. ... The only thing we're going to
do is basically the same thing,'' Hamer said. ``We will try to be
as lenient as possible and as flexible as we can, but it's a matter
of life and death.''
   The interior of the convention hall was redesigned to present a
more pleasing television appearance. Seating was reduced to an
estimated 11,000. Hamer said that number can be expanded to about
12,500.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young blamed much of the overcrowding on
the hordes of journalists in the hall. Most news organizations have
their working areas at the adjacent Georgia World Congress Center.
   ``What we had was a lot of people (reporters) who normally would
be working in the Georgia World Congress Center or would be on
assignment in other places deciding that that (The Omni) was the
place they wanted to be last night,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
