<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Prison 2ndLd-Writethru a0914 07-20 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Prison, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0914,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Die in Prison Riot; Situation Reported Under Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD total number of prisoners in
facility, picks up graf 3 pvs ```It's still...'
^By JAVIER PICHARDINI</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A riot broke out in Michoacan state
penitentiary Wednesday and officials said at least 10 people were
killed and 15 injured before it was brought under control. One
report said 14 people died.
   A preliminary report by the state government described the
violence at the prison in Morelia, the state capital, as ``an
attempt at a mass breakout.''
   The prison houses about 2,000 prisoners, but it was not
immediately clear how many took part in the riot.
   ``It's still very hot,'' the duty officer at the state judicial
police said by phone from Morelia, 150 miles west of Mexico City.
He refused to give his name and said no details were available.
   However, Andres Rencillas Mejia, news editor for La Voz de
Michoacan newspaper, said in a phone interview that his reporters
confirmed 11 people died and 18 were wounded in a one-hour shootout
between prisoners and guards.
   He said prisoners destroyed virtually all files of pending court
cases. The penitentiary includes six state courtrooms.
   The national news service of the Excelsior newspaper said state
Attorney General Jose Franco Villa provided casualty figures of 14
guards and prisoners killed and 20 wounded.
   The government figures of 10 killed and about 15 hurt came from
Isauro Gutierrez, chief of the social work office at the Michoacan
state attorney general's office.
   Alfredo Gonzalez, an aide in state government's information
office, said the riot ``already has been controlled.''
   All state officials reached said detailed reports were not yet
available.
   The Excelsior report from Morelia said all inmates were taken to
holding areas in the prison yards while their cells were searched
and that at least 30 weapons were found.
   The riot started at about 10 a.m. _ noon EDT _ according to all
accounts.
   Excelsior's account quoted Franco Villa as saying the riot began
when two prisoners being taken to trial disarmed their guards, that
other prisoners seized advantage of the situation to join in and
disarm other guards, and that a shootout started between prisoners
and watchtower guards.
   The report said prisoners held 15 secretaries and eight nurses
hostage while the shootout lasted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua     07-20 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Civilians, 11 Rebels Reported Killed In Nicaraguan Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry said Wednesday
that 11 rebels and seven civilians were killed in attacks this week
which violated a cease-fire between the Contras and the leftist
Sandinista government.
   Also Wednesday, Foreign Ministry representatives requested a
visa for Ambassador Carlos Tunnerman to travel to the United
States, days after the Reagan administration expelled him. He
returned from Washington Saturday.
   A ministry statement said seven civilians died, including two
children aged 7 and 9, and five were wounded Tuesday when a rebel
band ambushed two vehicles in which the victims were riding near
Juigalpa, 55 miles east of Managua.
   It said nine rebels were killed Monday when Sandinista troops
fought off their attack near Muelle de los Bueyes and Muhan,
neighboring villages in southern Nicaragua near the Caribbean coast.
   The statement gave no details and made no mention of government
casualties.
   It said two rebels were killed and one was wounded in an attack
Tuesday on troops near San Rafael del Norte, 110 miles north of the
capital city of Managua. It said the troops repelled the attack by
the U.S.-supported rebels.
   President Daniel Ortega announced on Tuesday that his government
was unilaterally extending to Aug. 30 a cease-fire scheduled to
expire at the end of July.
   The Contras have not said if they will agree to the extension.
   Both sides have charged frequent violations in the cease-fire
that began March 21 and has been extended repeatedly. No talks have
been scheduled to negotiate a lasting peace agreement since the
last round broke off in June.
   State-run radio Voice of Nicaragua said Tunnerman needed to
travel to the United States to take part in an international
education contest and functions related to his job as ambassador to
the Organization of American States.
   U.S. Embassy officials refused to comment Wednesday night.
   The United States on July 11 ordered Tunnerman and seven other
Nicaraguan diplomats to leave, in retaliation for Nicaragua's
expulsion of U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and seven American
diplomats.
   The U.S. Embassy stopped issuing tourist visas to Nicaraguans on
July 13, one day after Melton left, citing a shortage of personnel.
The measure does not affect diplomatic visas.
   Nicaragua argued that Tunnerman did not have to leave the United
States because he also represented his country in the OAS.
Tunnerman left Washington just ahead of a State Department deadline
for his departure, assailing his expulsion as ``unjustified and
illegal.''
   The OAS charter says attendance at OAS meetings shall ``not
depend on bilateral relations'' between any member state and the
United States, the host country.
   But the Reagan administration said a separate agreement between
the United States and the OAS authorizes the U.S. government to
order any OAS diplomat home.
   An Interior Department spokeswoman said Wednesday in another
development that 40 people arrested for an anti-government
demonstration on July 10 will be tried in criminal courts on
charges of criminal association and causing injury.
   Patricia Orozco, director of the department's press office, said
evidence would be presented Thursday.
   Special police courts earlier revoked the maximum six-month
sentences they imposed in 36 of the cases last week so the cases
could be transferred to criminal court.
   Human rights groups have described the police courts as
arbitrary and unconstitutional.
   Critics of the government had complained bitterly about the
sentences arising from the demonstration in Nandaime, a town 40
miles south of Managua. The Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, a
coalition of political parties, business and labor groups opposing
the Sandinistas, organized the demonstration.
   Fighting broke out between police and thousands of demonstrators.
   Among those arrested were Carlos Huembes, the coordinate's
president; Roger Guevara, its secretary; Miriam Arguello,
secretary-general of the Conservative Party, and Agustin Jarquin, a
leader of the Social Christian Party.
   The government closed down the Roman Catholic radio station and
suspended publication of the opposition newspaper La Prensa for 15
days for their reporting on the demonstration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
