<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Taiwan-Cabinet     07-20 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Cabinet,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Shakes Up Taiwan Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Lee Teng-hui announced a major
Cabinet shake-up Wednesday that suggested a gradual approach to
fulfilling his promise of further liberalizing Nationalist Party
rule over Taiwan.
   Lee kept Premier Yu Kuo-hwa, the government's leading
conservative, but brought eight new officials into the 25-member
Cabinet and transferred seven to new Cabinet posts. Several
reform-minded Nationalist lawmakers had called for Yu's resignation.
   The reshuffle came one week after the landmark 13th Nationalist
Party congress retired several Chiang Kai-shek era conservatives
while promoting a younger generation of party leaders, including
many native Taiwanese.
   The Nationalists, led by Chiang, set up their authoritarian
government in Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to communist
forces on the Chinese mainland. Those born on the mainland have
long dominated the party's top ranks although native Taiwanese
comprise 85 percent of the island's nearly 20 million people.
   Lee, a 65-year-old native Taiwanese, was acclaimed Nationalist
chairman by the party congress July 8. He received approval for the
new Cabinet at a Wednesday meeting of the party's policy-making
Central Standing Committee. Officials said the changes take effect
next Monday.
   The average age of the Cabinet fell from 62 to 58 and the number
of native Taiwanese rose from eight to 11 as they picked up the key
posts of foreign minister and finance minister.
   Shirley Kuo, 58, deputy governor of the Central Bank, becomes
the first woman minister as head of the Finance Ministry, replacing
Robert Chien, 59, named the Cabinet's secretary-general.
   Lee has pledged to continue democratic reform and other
liberalization begun by his predecessor Chiang Ching-kuo, the
eldest son of Chiang kai-shek.
   Chiang Ching-kuo lifted martial law and ended a ban on
opposition parties in the months before his death Jan. 13.
   Many of the new Cabinet members are viewed as technocrats,
including several groomed by Yu and other party conservatives from
mainland China. But some observers believe the new line-up should
speed liberalization of the state-dominated economic system.
   Lin An-lo, chief economist at the Chunghwa Institute for
Economic Research, said, ``Premier Yu has been under tremendous
pressure to reform. We hope he can do better with the cooperation
of the younger Cabinet members.''
   Lee called for reform of the economic and financial system, but
economists say the government has moved slowly so as not to
irritate powerful vested interests.
   The party controls Taiwan's banks and many other large
enterprises. Conservative party members generally oppose
privatization of banks and other businesses and reform of the tax
system, steps many people say are needed to modernize the economy.
   Vice Premier Lien Chan, 52, replaces 64-year-old Ding Mou-shih
as foreign minister.
   Frederick Chien, 54, Taiwan's representative in Washington,
replaces Chao Yao-tung, 73, as head of the Council for Economic
Planning and Development.
   Chen Li-an, 51, chairman of the National Science Council,
replaces 69-year-old Lee Ta-hai as economic affairs minister.
   The youngest Cabinet member is Ma Ying-jeou, 38, appointed head
of the Research, Development and Evaluation Commission.
   Lee also said Wednesday that parliamentary reforms should be
implemented this year to ``make us more fit for constitutional
democracy.''
   Taiwan's parliamentary bodies are now dominated by aging
Nationalists elected on the Chinese mainland before 1949 and frozen
in office to support the Nationalists' claim to be the rightful
ruler of all China.
   The Nationalist Party proposed increasing the number of locally
elected seats while allowing aging mainlanders to retire.
   But the opposition Democratic Progressive Party wants all seats
in the Legislative Yuan, the highest lawmaking body, and the
National Assembly electoral college to be contested in next year's
elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
