<1ST_LINE>a i PM-China-Bookstore Adv28   07-20 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Bookstore, Adv 28,0681</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs July 28 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Private Bookstore in Beijing Struggling to Stay Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just two months after it opened, a private
bookstore that specializes in translations of Western works is in
danger of closing _ a victim of the cold, hard world of economics.
   ``We've got problems. We owe everybody,'' said Liu Yuanshang, as
she sat recently in a cluttered storage hall behind her Three
Flavors Bookroom. ``But we have a lot of people supporting us so we
have hope.''
   Ms. Liu, 48, opened the store May 18 in a one-story wood and
stone house in western Beijing. Her husband, Li Shiqiang, 44, and
her former husband, Yu Chen, 58, are her main partners.
   Named after a short story by the famous early 20th-century
writer Lu Xun, Three Flavors is a special bookstore, filled with
Chinese-language books on American law, capitalist economics,
modern art and psychology.
   These subjects were taboo during China's ultraleftist Cultural
Revolution of 1966-76 and still are not completely accepted by the
state.
   ``We are a bookstore for intellectual adventurers,'' said Ms.
Liu. ``We want to help open the minds of the Chinese people.''
   Unlike government-run stores where books are locked in glass
cases, the Three Flavors puts its books on open shelves and
encourages customers to browse.
   One recent day, an elderly gentlemen in T-shirt and shorts sat
in a corner and fanned himself slowly, reading a Shakespeare play
in Chinese.
   Nearby a young woman sat at the edge of a red bench, lost in the
poetry of Robert Louis Stevenson.
   ``My school is very far away, but I often come here to read,''
said Li Yin, 18, looking up from her poems. ``It is wonderful to
read here because they make you feel at home.''
   Ms. Liu said she and her partners opened the store because they
were disgusted by the selection offered in other Beijing stores.
   ``Too many stores these days are selling bad books, just
designed for quick excitement. They're dirty books or detective
books,'' Ms. Liu said. ``But we want to sell books that will give
our readers more knowledge. China is backward and we need to learn
more.''
   The store had to be privately owned, said Ms. Liu, to be as free
as possible in the selection of stock.
   ``I didn't want anyone leading us around by the nose.''
   More than half the books are translations of Western books
recently published in China. On one shelf a collection by French
philosopher Jean-Paul Sartre sits next to ``Goodbye, Colombus'' by
Philip Roth. On another, Friedrich Nietzsche vies with ``The Agony
and the Ecstasy,'' Irving Stone's biography of Michaelangelo.
   Ms. Liu said she was branded a ``rightist'' at age 18 in 1958,
and was unable to get a job for 20 years.
   ``And after that the job I got was no good. They made me an
English teacher but I had forgotten all my English.''
   China's recent reforms, allowing limited private industry, gave
Ms. Liu a way out. She and her partners pooled their life savings
and last year bought the building for $21,000.
   ``Ah, what a mess it was,'' she recalled.
   Relatives and friends helped renovate the building for free, but
the new pipes, lights, roof and windows cost money.
   Ms. Liu and her partners raised some from friends. Then they
turned to a bank, but China's state-run banks are not accustomed to
floating loans to private enterprises.
   ``We were forced to borrow from private lenders at high
interest,'' she said.
   As of mid-July, the store was in debt $6,760.
   ``Everything you see in this room isn't really ours,'' Ms. Liu
said waving her hands at stacks and stacks of books. ``We still
have no money to pay.''
   But, she said, ``We have this house. And we have our friends.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs July 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
