<1ST_LINE>a i AM-LifeAbroad-India'sMonsoon Adv29   07-20 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Life Abroad-India's Monsoon, Adv 29,0507</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, July 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: New Delhi's Monsoon _ A Time for Rejoicing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on people, places and things in
other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI,India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the dusty days of summer, when
temperatures hover above 100 degrees for days on end, New Delhi
rejoices at the coming of the monsoon and its cooling rains.
   ``In the West, the rains are depressing. In India they are a
time of great joy, release, beauty and romance,'' says Khushwant
Singh, a noted author and journalist.
   As the rains come, the dust settles. Parched gardens suddenly
turn green. Temperatures come soothingly down and so do tempers.
   But the monsoon has its sad side.
   The rains that started early in July ended two years of drought
in northern India, promising good crops at last, but they also
unleashed floods that left scores of people dead.
   For New Delhi, the downpour broke the stifling heat, but
telephones went dead, potholes multiplied or grew deeper, and
disease became a danger as tainted water seeped into pipes and
wells.
   At the first delicious moment of the monsoon, though, the
nourishing rain kept such troubles distant.
   ``The monsoon ... for most Indians ... is not only the source of
life, but also their most exciting contact with nature,'' says
author-journalist Singh.
   When the clouds first burst open over New Delhi, dozens of
half-naked children danced gleefully in the downpour and splashed
in puddles in one impoverished neighborhood along the Yamuna River.
   ``It's always like this,'' said Gulab, an elderly woman watching
the fun. ``The children love to play in the rain, but they
invariably get sick.''
   More than 5,300 people have been treated this year for
gastro-enteritis and cholera in New Delhi. At least 75 have died,
most of them children.
   Maya Rao, a university teacher who has lived in New Delhi for
many years, described New Delhi's monsoon this way:
   ``There is muck and mud all over, mosquitoes attack you in
hordes, diseases spread like vice. It's impossible to get to places
on time, given the state of the roads, and calling people on the
phone is such a nuisance _ half the phones are dead.''
   Then, she added, there's the humidity.
   ``The moment the rain stops, you sweat to death.''
   Even so, Ms. Rao went on, she can't imagine life without the
monsoon.
   ``What could be more delightful than eating `bhutta' (roasted
corn-on-the-cob) on your terrace as the grey-purple skies melt into
rain?''
   One city official, who insisted on anonymity, said he could do
no work during the monsoon.
   ``It's too beautiful just to relax, sit and watch the rain,'' he
said, as he sat watching the rain stream down his office window.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs July 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-20 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0548</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have retreated after Monday's
brief surge as traders grew skeptical that a possible cease-fire in
the Iran-Iraq war would soon reduce the world oversupply of oil.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude oil, fell 47 cents to settle at $15.23 a barrel Tuesday
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   On Monday, the August contract for West Texas Intermediate had
jumped 84 cents a barrel after news of a possible cease-fire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beretta, the Italian arms manufacturer, has sued
General Motors Corp. for $250 million, claiming its reputation for
fine workmanship will be ruined if the carmaker continues producing
a four-wheeled Beretta.
   Fabrica D'Armi P. Beretta SpA, maker of firearms since the late
15th century, charged GM Tuesday with trademark infringement and
unfair competition in a federal lawsuit.
   Beretta said it warned GM about using the Beretta name a year
before the automaker unveiled the Chevrolet model in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Digital Equipment Corp. has extended its war on
International Business Machines Corp. by announcing a major new
thrust in the field of transaction processing.
   Digital President Kenneth Olsen on Tuesday called transaction
processing ``the fastest-growing part of the business computer
market'' and vowed to grab a bigger part of it. Analysts said the
goal was realistic.
   Transaction processing is the kind of computing done by bank
tellers, airline reservation clerks and other people who need to
interact closely with computers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng has met with farmers in Ohio
and Indiana at the outset of a 10-state inspection of drought
damage.
   As much as 2{ inches of rain fell in the two states on Monday
and Tuesday. But at some stops along the way, cornfields were still
bone dry only a half-inch below the surface.
   Lyng said his department has received all the crop data required
to assess requests for disaster declarations, but gave no
indication what assistance would be offered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal industry officials predict that the
nation's coal companies will have record production this year, as
some utilities turn to coal-fired generators to replace
hydroelectric power in this summer of drought and searing heat.
   In a midyear production forecast, the National Coal Association
said Tuesday that production of bituminous, anthracite and lignite
coal should total 926 million tons in 1988, up 9 million tons from
last year's record.
   The Washington-based group also said consumption of domestic and
imported coal is expected to total 932 million tons, an increase of
15 million tons from last year's record.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction rebounded partially in
June from the sharp slump in May, and economists say rising
mortgage rates likely will curtail home building for the rest of
the year.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that builders started
construction of new houses and apartments at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.45 million units in June, up 5.1 percent from the
previous month.
   But the improvement only partly offset a precipitous 12.6
percent decline in May.
</TEXT>
