<DOCNO> AP880720-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-20 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0566</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has called its first
witnesses in the massive Pentagon bribery investigation, while a
major contractor has fired all its defense-contract consultants and
shook up the management of one division.
   Unisys Corp., whose offices on Long Island, N.Y., have been
searched by federal agents, announced Tuesday that its own,
independent investigation had uncovered activity contrary to
company policy.
   Unisys chairman W. Michael Blumenthal, a former Treasury
secretary, placed a Long Island division under new management, put
some employees on administrative leave and terminated ``all
consulting contracts with those who represented the company before
the federal government on defense-related matters.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic controllers have elected their
first union president since the 1981 strike in which 11,400
controllers were fired and their old union was destroyed.
   In balloting that stretched over several weeks, R. Steve Bell, a
controller from New York, was elected president of the new National
Air Traffic Controllers Association, the union announced Tuesday.
   The union also selected a group of regional representatives and
other officers, all for three-year terms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 240,000 people left the land last
year, reducing the nation's farm population to the lowest level
since before the Civil War, the government has reported.
   According to the results of an annual Census Bureau survey
released Tuesday, 2 percent of the U.S. population of 243.4 million
lived on farms in 1987.
   That compared with 2.2 percent of the national population of
241.1 million in 1986.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Across the country, agriculture scientists have been forced to
abandon their experiments aimed at breeding tastier, healthier
crops and beefier cattle after the drought damaged or destroyed
their efforts.
   But researchers who study drought said Tuesday they hope to
learn lessons from the current dry spell which will help during the
next one.
   Scientists say the severe drought that has covered much of the
Midwest and parts of the South is enabling them to collect
information that they couldn't have gotten otherwise.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Times Mirror Co. reports its profits fell in the second quarter
from the same period last year, while Time Inc., Tribune Co. and
Media General Inc. report profit gains.
   Times Mirror reported a 4.8 percent drop in after-tax profit to
$79 million on Tuesday, down from $83 million. Time said its profit
rose 7.7 percent in the second quarter to $84 million, from $78
million.
   Tribune Co. reported a 31 percent climb in profits to $63.6
million from $48.6 million. And Media General reported a profit of
$16.2 million, a 28 percent gain from $12.7 million.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slumped against major foreign currencies Tuesday
after central banks intervened to force the U.S. currency lower.
   Gold prices rose sharply in response to a rally in the silver
market.
   The stock market skidded lower. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials fell 20.63 points to close at 2,097.26.
   Prices for some corn and soybean futures contracts closed down
their permissible limits on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Bond prices drifted higher in a quiet session after trading in a
narrow range most of the day.
</TEXT>
