<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     07-20 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Starts Partially Rebound; Oil, Grain Prices Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated with Commerce Department report on personal
income for first quarter, scheduled for 9 a.m. EDT release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many economists expect rising mortgage rates to crimp home
building for the rest of the year, despite a government report that
housing construction partially rebounded in June from a sharp slump
in May.
   Speculation that interest rates would rise further also hit Wall
Street, overriding Tuesday's flurry of favorable corporate earnings
reports. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down more than 11
points Monday, dropped another 20.63 to close at 2,097.26.
   But in the bond market, interest rates declined in speculation
that inflation would not heat up, following drops in oil and
commodity futures prices. The yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond
fell to 9.20 percent from 9.23 percent late Monday.
   Oil futures prices retreated as traders grew skeptical that a
possible cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war would soon reduce the
world oversupply of oil, while corn and soybean futures plunged
again as rain continued in the parched Midwest.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August-delivery
contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
fell 47 cents to settle at $15.23 per barrel.
   In its housing report, the Commerce Department said builders
started construction of new houses and apartments at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.45 million units in June, up 5.1 percent
from the previous month.
   But the improvement only partly offset a 12.6 percent decline in
May.
   ``The June numbers are just a technical correction. They don't
really signal a rebound in housing,'' said Thomas M. Holloway,
senior economist of the Mortgage Bankers Association of America.
   The hot, dry weather of June, bad for farming but ideal for home
building, also contributed to the uptick.
   And mortgage interest rates, which had climbed by three-quarters
of a percentage point from post-stock crash lows in early March,
eased slightly in June, falling by nearly a quarter of a percentage
point.
   But interest rates began edging up again in July and most
analysts expect the slump in housing, one of the weakest sectors of
a growing overall economy, to continue through 1988.
   In other economic news on Tuesday:
   _Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng began a 10-state inspection
of drought damage. The Agriculture Department, in a drought-related
measure, said growers of hybrid corn for seed will have the option
of planting their crop and not have it counted as a feed grain
under 1988 acreage programs.
   _The government reported that an estimated 240,000 people left
the land last year, dropping the nation's farm population to the
lowest level since before the Civil War.
</TEXT>
