<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-20 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall Back As Doubts About Cease-fire Results Grow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have retreated, amid
skepticism that a possible cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war would
soon reduce the world oversupply of crude.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude oil, fell the most sharply Tuesday, settling 47 cents
lower at $15.23 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Traders said the contract for August delivery, which expires
Wednesday, was depressed partly by plentiful inventories of oil at
U.S. terminals. The September contract, which is less sensitive to
short-term inventories, fell 26 cents at $15.63 a barrel.
   ``The market took a more realistic view today,'' said Andrew
Lebow, an analyst at E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc. in New
York. ``Based on real fundamentals, there still is a short-term or
maybe even intermediate-term oversupply of crude.''
   On Monday, the August contract for West Texas Intermediate had
jumped 84 cents a barrel after Iran said it would accept a United
Nations resolution calling for an immediate cease-fire in its
nearly 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   The news raised the possibility that members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries would be able to set aside their
differences and agree to production cutbacks that would prop up
prices.
   But Lebow said, ``There's a lot of work to be done to get from
the end of the war to OPEC production cutbacks.''
   ``I think that yesterday's rally was totally overdone,'' said
William Byers, an analyst at Bear, Stearns & Co.
   Also depressing oil prices Tuesday were reports that Iraqi
warplanes raided an unfinished nuclear plant and other Iranian
industrial targets. War communiques from Tehran said Iranian
warplanes retaliated by raiding a dam in Iraq.
   Another factor hurting prices was an unconfirmed report that
Saudi Arabia was selling oil from Caribbean inventories to
non-contractual customers at prices near the spot price, Lebow said.
   The contract for August delivery of No.2 heating oil, up 2.15
cents on Monday, fell .37 cent to 42.90 cents a gallon on the New
York Merc. The contract for August delivery of unleaded gasoline,
up 1.38 cents on Monday, fell .46 cent to 50.65 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
