<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomicOutlook     07-20 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economic Outlook,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financial Managers Expect Little Change In Economy Through Year
End</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate financial managers surveyed by a trade group generally
expect the economy to remain stable through the year's end, with
moderate inflation and rising interest rates, but a substantial
number expect things to get worse.
   Some 41 percent of the corporate controllers responding to the
survey by the National Association of Accountants said they
expected the economy to remain the same during the next 12 months,
while 37 percent predicted it would get worse, the association
reported today.
   Some 22 percent said they believed the economy would improve.
   The association said 28 percent of its 3,200 corporate
controller members responded to the survey, which was conducted
during the fourth week of June.
   Most respondents, 59 percent, expected inflation during the
second half of the year to rise to the 5 percent to 6 percent
range, while 62 percent said they foresaw higher interest rates.
Consumer prices, one measure of inflation, were up by 4.4 percent
through May of this year, the Labor Department has reported.
   Some 8 percent of the respondents said they expected a minor
recession this year with most anticipating at least a slight
downturn in the economy by 1990.
   The accountants group, based in Montvale, N.J., asked survey
participants to rank the top three factors they believed would have
the greatest impact on the economy during the next six months.
   Interest rates were chosen by 62 percent, followed by the budget
deficit, 49 percent. Some 38 percent said inflation would have a
big impact and 37 percent pointed to the November general election.
   Survey participants overwhelmingly expected strong growth for
their companies in the next six months compared with 1987, with
some 73 percent expecting higher sales and 64 percent predicting
higher profits.
   Capital expenditures were expected to remain the same during the
second half of the year, according to 48 percent of the respondents.
   The controllers also said they expected their companies'
employment picture to remain stable. Some 54 percent said they
forsaw no change in their company's employment level, while 13
percent said they expected declines.
   Among other responses:
   _58 percent said there should be increased federal regulations
for mergers and acquisitions.
   _56 percent said they expected a recession in 1990, with 20
percent predicting a major downturn and 80 percent saying it would
be minor.
   _31 percent expect continued fluctuations in the dollar.
</TEXT>
