<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-20 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold and Silver Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major currencies in early
European trading today amid fears dollar selling by central banks
would continue.
   Gold prices jumped $9 an ounce in Zurich and $8 in London and
silver prices also surged.
   Dealers said fears that European central banks again would
intervene to sell dollars and the belief that the dollar's recent
rise was overextended dampened bullish dollar sentiment in the
market.
   ``The U.S. trade imbalance is certainly improving, but everyone
knows a rapid rise in the dollar will only break that process,''
said a dealer in Milan, Italy.
   He predicted the dollar would continue to trade within a narrow
range.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.80 Japanese yen to a closing 133.05
yen. Later, in London, it edged up to 133.22 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7110 from $1.6937 late
Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's
quotes, included: 1.8475 West German marks, down from 1.8640;
1.5320 Swiss francs, down from 1.5475; 6.2325 French francs, down
from 6.2845; 2.0825 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1010; 1,368.50
Italian lire, down from 1,383.60; and 1.1960 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2011.
   The sudden leap in precious metals prices apparently was sparked
by a combination of a lower dollar and a miner's strike in Peru,
they said.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $444.25 a troy ounce, up
from $437 bid late Tuesday. At mid-morning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $445.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $445.50, up from $436.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $7.86 to close at a bid of
$446.84 a troy ounce.
   Silver bullion jumped in London to a bid price of $7.64 a troy
ounce, up from $7.13 bid late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
