<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-20 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rebound, Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rebounded sharply today with the main
market index making its largest one-day gain of the year, while the
dollar slipped for the second consecutive day against the Japanese
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which took its
biggest plunge of the year, 513.09 points, on Tuesday, regained
404.95 points, or 1.49 percent, to close Wednesday at 27,553.98.
   It was the largest single-day gain for the Nikkei, the most
widely followed barometer of the exchange, since Nov. 13, 1987,
when the index jumped 901.75 points.
   After opening at 27,330.72 points, the Nikkei index declined
further in the morning because of additional selling by investors
who held onto their shares yesterday during the sudden plunge,
brokers said.
   But the market rebounded in the late morning with brokers buying
electronics and high-tech shares instead of their old favorites,
steel and shipbuilding. The ``export-oriented'' shares led the
market in the afternoon as it ragained most of what it lost Tuesday.
   ``Today's market trends indicate goodbye to steels and
shipbuildings and hello to electronics and high-techs,'' said
Ichitaro Watanabe of Nikko Securities. ``With the yen's slight
depreciation, investors found export-oriented electronics shares
worth betting on. It seems as though most of those who sold steel
shares yesterday bought electronics today.''
   Electronics shares soared in today's trading with Hitachi,
Toshiba and Mitsubishi Electric shares reaching new highs. Sony
Corp. Matsushita Electric and NEC shares also gained significantly.
   ``A new direction seems to have emerged in the market,''
Watenabe said.
   Volume traded in the first section of the exchange was estimated
at 1.3 billion shares, of which 800 million were traded during the
afternoon session.
   The dollar closed at 133.05 yen, down 0.80 yen from Tuesday,
when the currency lost 1.30 yen. After opening at 133.05 yen, it
moved in a range of 132.90-133.35 yen in a slow trading.
   Exchange dealers said the dollar was on the way up in early
morning trading after a 1.36 yen drop in New York overnight. But
profit-taking prevented the currency from rising.
   ``Many players were holding up on selling dollars until it moved
up to upper 133's,'' said a dealer at a U.S. investment bank in
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``But it never got that
high.''
</TEXT>
