<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SamuraiSolution     07-20 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Samurai Solution,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventor Thinks Wheel Extenders May Curb Safety Problem in Samurai</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inventor Russell Emanis believes he has a solution
to the Suzuki Samurai's reported instability problem that caused
sales to plummet and forced the company to cut its price to dealers
by $2,000 to revive sales.
   Emanis, 26, a Samurai owner, said that for $195, he can expand
the Samurai wheelbase to make the vehicle safer.
   He is manufacturing a 5-stud steel ``doughnut'' that bolts to
the hub. The vehicle's regular tire and wheel then bolts to the
doughnut.
   Emanis claims his device improves the Samurai's stability and
all but eliminates what he says is the vehicle's characteristic
``skitter'' on moderate-speed turns.
   ``We're not trying to tell Suzuki what to do or how to run its
business, but we can't see anyone there is doing anything to
help,'' Emanis said.
   ``What we've done is make the vehicle handle better and feel
more solid. It makes steering tighter. It adds unsprung weight
below the center of gravity.''
   National sales of the four-wheel-drive Samurai dropped 70.6
percent in June from a year earlier after Consumer Reports magazine
claimed the vehicle was prone to roll over if a driver swerved back
and forth to avoid an accident.
   Suzuki officials say their vehicle is at least as stable as any
other four-wheel-drive rig in similar situations.
   Jennifer Astle of Rogers & Associates, Suzuki's public relations
firm, said she was unaware of any plans by Suzuki to improve
stability or of any accessory on the horizon that would do so.
   Last week, Brea, Calif.-based American Suzuki Motor Corp. told
dealers it would cut $2,000 off the price they pay for Samurais
sold through Sept. 2, and allowed dealers to decide how to use the
money.
   Most are passing the cuts on to consumers through price
reduction, rebate or using it as a down payment. The Samurai has a
suggested base retail price of $8,235.
   Emanis, who plans to have his invention tested when new vehicle
``outriggers'' are made, said the package of four disks weighs a
total of 62 pounds and extends the car's track 3 inches to 54.6
inches.
   The Dodge Raider has a factory wheel track of 54.1 inches. The
Ford Ranger truck's is 54.6 inches, and the Isuzu Trooper's is 54.7
inches, he said.
   Emanis, of Morrison, Colo., said he and his partner, Gretchen
Born, developed the product when his primary Suzuki accessory, a
hard top, came onto the market the day the bad publicity started
for the Samurai. He has also developed a roll bar for the Samurai.
   ``We're not trying to make a fortune,'' he said, ``but we are
trying to help the market, obviously, so our mainline business can
get back to work.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880720-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Chemical     07-20 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Chemical,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Doubles Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co.'s second-quarter earnings
doubled because of strong demand and increasing prices for
chemicals and plastics combined with little change in raw material
costs, the company said Wednesday.
   Dow reported record net income of $624 million, or $3.29 a
share, up from $312 million, or $1.62 a share, in the second
quarter of 1987. Revenue rose 25 percent to $4.25 billion from a
restated $3.41 billion a year earlier.
   Net income for the first six months of the year was $1.13
billion, or $5.96 a share, on sales of $8.23 billion, up from $558
million, or $2.90 a share, on sales of $6.42 billion in the first
half of 1987.
   ``Continued strong demand for our products resulted in tight
supply-demand balances, high operating rates and positive price
movement,'' said Enrique Falla, financial vice president.
   ``Feedstock costs were relatively flat, and the combination of
these factors allowed margins to expand,'' Falla said.
   Dow reported across-the-board sales growth, in its basic
chemicals and plastics, consumer specialties such as
pharmaceuticals and agricultural products, and industrial
specialties such as Styrofoam insulation, spokeswoman Sarah
Opperman said.
   ``Based on industry and global economic expectations, we
anticipate a record 1988 and sustained growth into 1989 and
beyond,'' Falla said.
</TEXT>
