<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0348</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved higher today as traders
gave a sigh of relief that the Japanese market recovered from its
worst decline this year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 7.11 at 2,104.37
in the first half hour of trading.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 11 to 7 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
555 up, 359 down and 484 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.93 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said there was a sense of relief that Tokyo's key
Nikkei index of 225 selected issues closed about 400 points higher,
nearly erasing Tuesday's 500-point drop, its largest decline this
year.
   ``Japan has been on a lot of people's minds,'' said Larry
Wachtel, a first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
Many traders have been anticipating a crack in the Japanese market,
which has had the most impressive recovery from the October market
crash.
   Wachtel said the stock market is continuing to ``meander
around.'' The Dow fell about 20 points on Tuesday amid a confusing
backdrop of robust second-quarter earnings reports, lower oil
prices and a firm bond market.
   But Wachtel noted that equities do not always perform in accord
with what is happening in other markets.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, IBM was up | at 124|;
AT&T was up [ at 26|; GAF Corp. was up } at 45\, and Tandem was
down ] at 18.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.35 to 152.15. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.22 at 308.61.
   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 20.63 to
2,097.26.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about than 9 to 5 on
the NYSE, with 517 up, 918 down and 492 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 144.11 million shares, against 156.21 million in the
previous session.
