<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices bounced higher Wednesday, boosted by
the stronger British pound.
   Sterling's rise relieved pressure for an increase in interest
rates, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks
was up 10.5 points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,855.3 at midday. Volume
was a slim 192.5 million shares, compared with 271.1 million shares
at the same time Tuesday.
   The market shrugged off a report that showed Britain's broad
measure of money supply, M-4, rose an estimated 1.9 percent in
June, compared with a 0.9 percent rise in May. Increases in money
supply are viewed as inflationary.
   The report was ``disappointing but ignored,'' said one equity
salesman, explaining that the figures seemed to contain a lot of
``caveats and special circumstances.''
   Another dealer said the market had prepared itself for ``really
horrendous'' money supply figures.
   When the slightly worse-than-expected numbers were revealed, in
combination with a stronger pound, the market was relieved that the
likelihood of an immediate interest rate hike was averted, he said.
</TEXT>
