<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher today in quiet trading
as the market rebounded from a sharp decline in the previous
session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 4.45 at 2,101.71
in the first hour and a half of trading.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by about 7 to 6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
613 up, 527 down and 544 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 41.88 million shares as of 11
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said there was a sense of relief that Tokyo's key
Nikkei index of 225 selected issues closed about 400 points higher,
nearly erasing Tuesday's 500-point drop, its largest decline this
year.
   ``Japan has been on a lot of people's minds,'' said Larry
Wachtel, a first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
Many traders have been anticipating a crack in the Japanese market,
which has had the most impressive recovery from the October market
crash.
   In addition, a stable dollar and a steady bond market helped to
``restore short-term confidence,'' said Michael Metz, a vice
president and technical analyst at Oppenheimer & Co.
   Metz called the Dow's 20-point drop on Tuesday ``overdone'' and
noted it was exacerbated by computer-driven sell programs. The drop
came amid a confusing backdrop of robust second-quarter earnings
reports, lower oil prices and a firm bond market.
   Traders have been hesitant to respond to the favorable earnings
reports because of the specter of higher interest rates down the
road. Metz noted that higher interest rates would diminish the real
value of those earnings gains.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, IBM was up [ at 124[;
AT&T was unchanged at 26{; McGraw Hill was up 1~ at 62}.
   Polaroid was up 2 at 36. Shamrock Holdings offered to acquire
the company for $40 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.18 to 151.98. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 0.26 at 308.65.
