<HEAD>Soybeans Open Sharply Lower; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most soybean futures opened sharply lower today
on the Chicago Board of Trade as scattered showers brought relief
to the drought-stricken Farm Belt for the fifth day in a row. Grain
prices were narrowly mixed.
   The opening drop in soybean prices followed two days of steep
declines and reflected a growing feeling among traders that the
drought has been broken, analysts said.
   ``There's a possibility we won't see a return to hot and dry
conditions any time soon,'' said Walter Spilka, grain analyst in
New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``It's a mixed call right now, but there's a possiblity we might
see more showers later on in the weekend and that's got a lot of
people thinking the markets have topped and will head lower,''
Spilka said.
   The rain came too late to revive the corn crop in most states
but it's just what the soybeans needed as that crop enters a
critical growth stage, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 2\ cents lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.75{ a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to 2 cents higher with July at $3.08 a bushel; oats were
2 cents to 4 cents lower with September at $2.90{ a bushel;
soybeans were 29{ cents lower to 5{ cents higher with July at $8.68
a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .37 cent lower to .05 cent higher with August
at 63.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent to .45 cent
lower with August at 75.65 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with July at 46.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .07 cent lower to .53 cent higher with July at 36.20
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday.
