<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1600EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Banks     07-20 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Banks,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three More Big Banks Report Second-Quarter Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers Trust New York Corp., First Interstate Bancorp and Bank
of Boston Corp. _ three of the nation's largest banking companies _
said Wednesday they earned profits in the second quarter after
reporting sharp losses a year ago due to the Third World debt
crisis.
   Bankers Trust, the eighth largest bank holding company in terms
of assets, said net income for the quarter totaled $174.1 million,
or $2.18 a share, compared with a $554 million loss in 1987.
   For the first half of 1988, the company earned $300.1 million,
or $3.79 a share, vs. a loss of $429.7 million a year earlier.
   First Interstate, ranked No. 9, earned $97.23 million, or $2.09
a share, in the second quarter, compared with a $510.26 million
loss last year.
   Earnings for the six-month period totaled $199.8 million, or
$4.29 a share, vs. a $429.72 million loss a year ago.
   Twelfth-ranked Bank of Boston had a second-quarter profit of
$76.1 milion, or $1.10 a share, compared with an $83.7 million
loss. For the first half it netted $160.4 million, compared with a
$13 million loss in the first half of 1987.
   All three banks were among several banking companies to suffer
huge losses or profit declines last year after making hefty
additions to their loan-loss reserves for potentially uncollectible
loans to developing nations.
   The additions followed Brazil's decision to suspend interest
payments on most of its foreign bank debt, and the rise of
concessionary debt repayment plans negotiated by several Third
World countries.
   Brazil has since repaid some of the interest owed, and this year
most major banks have substantially curtailed their loan-loss
provisions.
   Bankers Trust's provision for credit losses during the second
quarter of 1987 had totaled $700 million. The latest provision for
credit losses amounted to $5 million.
   Los Angeles-based First Interstate said that in the second
quarter $84.7 million was provided for possible loan losses, vs.
$795.3 million in 1987.
   Bank of Boston's provision for credit losses was $36 million for
the quarter compared with $325 million last year.
</TEXT>
