<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Airlines     07-20 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Airlines,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines' Profit Up 53.4 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parent of American Airlines
reported Wednesday that its earnings jumped 53.4 percent in the
second quarter from a year earlier, helped by strong passenger
traffic.
   AMR Corp. said its second-quarter earnings rose to $141.4
million, or $2.36 a share, from $92.2 million, or $1.51 a share, a
year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 18.1 percent, to $2.16 billion from
$1.83 billion in the year-earlier period.
   ``This is our best second quarter ever, with the exception of
1985, when we carried unusual amounts of traffic as a result of a
strike at a major competitor,'' AMR Chairman Robert L. Crandall
said in a press statement.
   In 1985, United Airlines pilots were on strike, and American's
passenger share was boosted by the disruption in its competitor's
service.
   In addition to strong traffic, AMR's performance in the latest
quarter also was boosted by continuing efforts to control costs,
Crandall said.
   While it was pleased with the results, Crandall said AMR was
disappointed by the performance of two of its aircraft suppliers,
McDonnell Douglas Corp. and Airbus Industrie. He said the two
manufacturers failed to meet commitments for aircraft deliveries,
which caused AMR's capacity to fall below expectations, increased
its unit costs and reduced its revenue.
   Airbus, an aircraft manufacturing consortium, is financed by the
governments of France, Britain, West Germany and Spain. It competes
intensely with U.S. rivals McDonnell Douglas and Boeing Co.
   In the first half of the year, the company's profit soared 87.2
percent _ to $209.8 million, or $3.47 a share, from $112.1 million,
or $1.88 a share, in the first six months of 1987.
   First-half revenue rose 23.6 percent, to $4.13 billion from
$3.34 billion a year earlier.
   American, based in Fort Worth, is the nation's second-largest
airline.
</TEXT>
