<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pratt&Whitney Bjt   07-20 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pratt & Whitney, Bjt,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pratt & Whitney Eliminates 1,000 Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pratt & Whitney Aircraft said
Wednesday it is eliminating more than 1,000 white-collar jobs in a
move that will eventually save $100 million a year and enhance its
competitive position in the jet engine market.
   The company said 283 employees, ranging from engineers and
purchasing agents to vice presidents, would be laid off over the
next 18 months, including 158 who were let go immediately.
   The rest of the jobs, including 314 currently vacant positions,
will be eliminated through attrition and not renewing 181 personnel
contracts.
   Two more rounds of job reductions among the company's 19,370
salaried employees will be announced next month, said Curtis Linke,
a Pratt & Whitney spokesman.
   The first round of reductions will eventually save the company
an estimated $100 million a year, he said.
   ``Cost reductions are difficult but eliminating unnecessary
tasks and the reduction of staff are steps we must take to ensure a
healthy future for Pratt & Whitney and all our people,'' company
president Arthur E. Wegner said in a statement.
   Pratt & Whitney, a subsidiary of United Technologies Corp. of
Hartford, Conn., has said a number of times over the past year that
it needed to lay off employees to remain competitive with its chief
rival, General Electric Co.
   Pratt & Whitney has about 45,700 salaried and hourly employees
worldwide, compared to 44,720 in 1982.
   ``It's nothing dramatic,'' said David Franus, an analyst at
Forecast International in Newtown, a market research firm that
follows the aerospace industry. ``It is part of an ongoing attempt
by Pratt & Whitney to pare its staff down, just to be leaner and
meaner and more cost effective with GE.''
   Philip Friedman, an analyst with Drexel Burhnam Lambert Inc. in
New York, said: ``The company for some time has been cutting costs
and restructuring. ... Certainly it will make them more competitive
in the jet engine market.''
   Also on Wednesday, another UTC division, Hamilton Standard of
Windsor Locks, announced Wednesday that about 200 hourly workers
and 20 salaried employees are being laid off. Hamilton Standard
makes space systems.
   Once the world's dominant jet engine builder, P&W saw its share
of the commercial market drop from 100 percent in 1974 to about 40
percent in 1987. General Electric's share grew during the same
period from nothing to 45 percent to 50 percent.
   Similar declines have occurred in Pratt & Whitney's military
business.
   General Electric's pre-tax profit margin on engines is about 16
percent compared to 8 percent for P&W, analysts have said.
   Pratt & Whitney said it is rebounding, however, with orders this
year running double the rate of last year.
   The first round of job reductions, announced Wednesday, affects
the company's commercial business in East Hartford, Linke said. The
government engine business in West Palm Beach, Fla., and
manufacturing operations in Connecticut, Columbus, Ga., and
Berwick, Maine, will be affected in future job reductions, Linke
said.
   The salaried employees laid off Wednesday will receive two
weeks' pay, plus one week of severance pay for every year of
service and a $3,000 lump-sum payment.
   Pratt & Whitney used retirement and severance incentives last
year to reduce its white-collar work force by about 2,000.
   Wegner told analysts late last year that further reductions in
the work force were planned in order to bring the size of the
company in line with a reduced production volume.
   Pratt & Whitney attempted last year to reopen contract
negotiations with the Machinists union so it could offer retirement
incentives and improved severance pay for workers laid off in the
future.
   Workers rejected the idea. Linke said Wednesday that there was
no evaluation of blue-collar staff now going on. The Machinists'
current contract expires in December 1988. The union represents
18,000 workers at Pratt & Whitney and Hamilton Standard in
Connecticut.
   George Almeida, grand lodge representative of the Machinists
union, said all of the approximately 500 hourly workers who have
been laid off by Pratt & Whitney in the past year have been called
back.
   Earlier this week, UTC announced that net income for the second
quarter increased 26 percent to $196.2 million, or $1.50 per share,
from $156 million, or $1.19 per share, a year earlier.
   Robert Daniell, UTC chairman and chief executive officer,
predicted that the company would end 1988 with record results.
</TEXT>
