<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelPrices     07-20 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Prices,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Raises Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. announced price
increases Wednesday ranging from 3.5 percent to 5.5 percent on
several types of widely used flat rolled steel.
   USX Corp., the nation's largest steelmaker, declined comment,
meanwhile, on rumors that it recently alerted customers to similar
price increases.
   Analysts said the Bethlehem move reflects tight supplies of
hot-rolled steel sheet and the prospects of continued strength in
general steel markets.
   ``It's part and parcel of what I see as a sharply improved steel
market,'' said J. Clarence Morrison, securities analyst for Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Bethlehem said the increases take effect Jan. 1, giving
customers time to plan for the higher prices.
   Bethlehem said the per ton price of hot rolled sheets will rise
by $15, or 3.5 percent, to $445, while the prices of cold rolled
and coated sheets will rise by $30 per ton, or up to 5.5 percent,
to as high as $651.
   Flat rolled steel is used in a variety of manufactured goods,
including office furniture and appliances. Automakers, major users
of sheet steel, negotiate prices with the producers.
</TEXT>
