<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-20 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0649</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted gains Wednesday in a
dull session dominated by program trading and activity in a handful
of takeover issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell about 32
points in the previous two sessions, climbed 13.34 to close at
2,110.60, its highest level of the day.
   Advancing issues outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
851 issues up, 597 down and 503 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 151.99 million shares,
up from 144.11 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
178.88 million shares.
   The Dow remained in plus territory and above the psychologically
important 2,100 mark throughout the session.
   While bargain hunters were lured to the market after two days of
declining stock prices, analysts noted that a lot of cash remains
on the sidelines.
   ``Basically what happened most of the day is program-related,
and that keeps institutions on the sidelines,'' said Philip Puccio,
a senior vice president at Dillon, Read & Co.
   In addition to computer-triggered buy programs, a handful of
issues that are the subject of takeover bids and those rumored to
be takeover targets accounted for a substantial amount of trading
volume. Trading strategies designed to capture dividends also drove
up volume, analysts said.
   ``When you take out the dividend rolls and the takeover plays,
we're not really running at an institutional pace,'' Puccio said.
   Edward Nicoski, a technical analyst at Piper Jaffray & Hopwood
Inc. in Minneapolis, said the session was ``kind of blah.'' He
noted that the while blue-chip issues managed to post gains, ``the
secondary stocks were weak all day long.''
   Traders again were hit with a flurry of mostly favorable
second-quarter earnings reports, but they remained hesitant to
respond for fear the gains will be canceled out by higher interest
rates down the road.
   Analysts also said there was a sense of relief at the opening
after Tokyo's key Nikkei index of 225 selected issues finished
about 400 points higher, nearly erasing Tuesday's 500-point drop,
its largest decline this year.
   Many traders have been braced for a crack in the Japanese
market, which has recovered impressively from the October market
crash.
   Among actively traded issues, Polaroid jumped 6 to 40. Shamrock
Holdings offered to acquire the company for $40 a share.
   McGraw-Hill was up 3} at 64|. The company, which has been
mentioned as a potential takeover target, had no comment on the
rise in its stock.
   Maytag was up 2{ at 24|. The appliance company had no comment on
the rise, but rumors circulated in the market that the company may
be the target of a leveraged buyout.
   Travelers Corp., the Big Board's most actively traded issue,
rose [ to 36\; Columbia Gas was up { at 32], and Chase Manhattan
Bank was up { at 30. Each was the subject of dividend trading
strategies.
   Elsewhere, IBM was unchanged at 124; Honeywell was up 2 at 65];
Digital Equipment was down 1 at 107|, and AT&T was up ] at 26~.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market gained $11.37 billion, or 0.42
percent, in value.
   The NYSE index was up 0.76 at 152.56.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 1.85 to 312.03,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.53 at 270.00.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.79
to 309.18. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 391.63, up 0.35.
</TEXT>
