<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Ralston     07-20 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Ralston,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ralston Purina Reports 39 Percent Increase In Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralston Purina Co. on Wednesday announced its
third-quarter earnings jumped 39 percent on a modest increase in
sales.
   The company, which makes food products and batteries, said net
income for the quarter ended June 30 totaled $77.2 million, or
$1.13 per share, compared with net earnings of $55.7 million, or 78
cents a share a year ago.
   Revenue increased 4 percent to $1.47 billion, from $1.40 billion
in the third fiscal quarter of 1987.
   For the year-to-date, Ralston-Purina reported net earnings of
$302.9 million, or $4.38 a share, on sales of $4.52 billion,
compared with net earnings of $426.1 million, or $5.83 a share, on
sales of $4.36 billion for the first nine months of the last fiscal
year.
   The St. Louis-based company attributed the earnings increase for
the nine-month period partly to lower tax rates and improved
operating results, especially in human and pet foods operations.
   Eveready Battery profits also increased on a strong
international performance, with improved volumes reported primarily
in Asia and Europe, the company said. For the third quarter,
however, operating profit for battery products declined slightly
from the previous year because of increased consumer and trade
promotion spending in the United States.
</TEXT>
