<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GeneralDynamics     07-20 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-General Dynamics,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports 47 Percent Drop In Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. on Wednesday reported a
47 percent decrease in second-quarter earnings, due in part to
costs in its Electric Boat Division.
   For the second quarter, its profit amounted to $66.7 million, or
$1.58 a share, on net sales of $2.34 billion, compared with net
earnings of $125.1 million, or $2.92 a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter sales fell to $2.34 billion from $2.41 billion
last year.
   For the first half of the year, the company reported net
earnings of $172.4 million, or $4.10 a share, on net sales of $4.74
billion, compared iwth net earnings of $230.5 million, or $5.37 a
share, on net sales of $4.66 billion for the same six months in
1987.
   Earnings for both periods were boosted by $20 million from tax
law changes resulting in reductions of deferred taxes, the defense
contractor said.
   The second-quarter results included a charge of $33 million
after taxes associated with the SSN 688-Class Attack Submarine
program at Electric Boat Division, the company said.
   The company said costs of operations at Electric Boat Division
have been rising since the first quarter of 1987, mostly because of
problems associated with the installation of a new integrated
combat system in the attack submarine and to higher overhead rates
because the company did not win any submarine awards in fiscal 1987.
   The company said the division's second-quarter charge reflected
losses from resolution of the company's request for equiptable
adjustment associated with the design and installation of the new
combat system, from higher costs of rescheduling work into future
periods and from the strike by 10,000 shipyard workers at the
Groton, Conn., facility, which is now in its third week.
</TEXT>
