<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-20 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Prices Plunge For Third Day As Rain Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain in the Farm Belt sent soybean futures prices plunging the
permissable limit again Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade but
analysts said a new forecast for a return to hot, dry weather could
end the slide at three days.
   In other action on the Board of Trade, oat futures fell sharply,
wheat was lower and corn was mixed.
   On other markets, sugar prices plummeted; silver rose while gold
fell; livestock and meat were mostly lower; and energy futures
advanced.
   Prices for some soybean contracts and nearly all oat contracts
fell their permissable limits as scattered rain fell in parts of
Indiana, Illinois and Arkansas, marking the fifth straight day that
showers had touched some part of the Midwest.
   The precipitation came too late to save much of the corn crop
but for soybeans, ``the rains came right at the right exact time
and in areas where they needed it,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   He said soybean farmers in the South finished planting last week
while the Midwestern soybean crop has begun forming pods.
   The most critical period for soybean growth will occur from
mid-August through early September, when the pods fill with beans,
said Mario Balletto, soybean analyst in New York with Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets Inc.
   ``The pod-filling is really like the last chance,'' Balletto
said ``That's when you've got to have the weather if you've got any
chance of getting decent yields.''
   Hot, dry weather will return to most of the Midwest by the
middle of next week, the National Weather Service predicted in a
6-to-10-day forecast issued after the close.
   Balletto said the forecast could have a bullish impact on crop
futures on Thursday.
   Corn futures fell sharply in early trading but recovered to
close mixed on news that the American Farm Bureau had reduced its
corn-production estimate to 4.5 billion bushels from 4.8 million.
   Wheat futures prices were pressured by disappointment that some
expected export business with China and India had failed to
materialize, Spilka said.
   Wheat settled 4 cents to 11 cents lower with July at $3.65 a
bushel; corn was 16 cents lower to 5 cents higher with July at
$2.92{ a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 20 cents lower with July at
$2.70 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 45{ cents lower with
July at $8.29 a bushel.
   Soybean prices are limited to moves of 45 cents a bushel and
oats are limited to 15 cents a bushel except for the July
contracts, on which the limits have been removed pending the
expiration of those contracts at noon on Thursday.
   World sugar prices collapsed on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa
Exchange on unconfirmed rumors that the Soviet Union would not make
any additional sugar purchases before their October harvest, said
Judith Ganes, an analyst in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   The Soviets are believed to have purchased as much as 200,000
metric tons of sugar last week, she said. Traders expected them to
buy another 500,000 metric tons before October.
   The contract for October delivery settled 1.13 cents lower at
14.17 cents a pound.
   Fears that a two-day miners' walkout in Peru could become an
indefinite strike propelled silver futures prices sharply higher on
New York's Commodity Exchange.
   The strike began Monday night and the government has refused to
budge on the workers' demands for higher wages, said Bernard
Savaiko, metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York.
   Peru is the world's second-largest silver producer behind Mexico.
   Gold settled $1.30 to $1.80 lower with August at $445.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 9.3 cents to 10 cents higher with July at $7.827
a troy ounce.
   Lower cash prices and lower soybean futures prices pressured
most livestock and meat futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
analysts said.
   Hog futures were hit particularly hard on expectations that the
Midwestern rains and cooler temperatures would prompt increased
marketings.
   Live cattle were .63 cent lower to .33 cet higher with August at
64.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .53 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with August at 75.57 cents a pound; hogs were the limit 1.50
cents lower to .55 cent higher with July at 47.20 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 1.15 cents lower to .05 cent higher with
July at 35.75 cents a pound.
   Oil futures advanced in volatile trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 4 cents to 47 cents higher
with August at $15.60 cents a barrel; heating oil was 1.20 cents to
1.75 cents higher with August at 44.65 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .10 cent lower to .20 cent higher with August at 50.85
cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
