<DOCNO> AP880720-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 1840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid-Disney     07-20 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Disney,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walt Disney's Nephew: Low-Key King of Magic Financial Kingdom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Polaroid-Shamrock Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy E. Disney, who followed his famous
uncle Walt in making cartoons and nature shows, is the low-key king
of a magic financial kingdom of stocks, broadcast companies and a
big stake in the family fantasy business.
   The $2.64 billion offer Disney made Wednesday for Polaroid Corp.
through his Shamrock Holdings Inc. is his most ambitious gambit yet
as a financial gamesman, but has ample precedent.
   Shamrock, an investment vehicle for Disney and his family, has
traded in companies as diverse as an Indiana soybean processor, a
Los Angeles record store chain and a Hawaii television station.
   Disney himself, son of Walt's brother and business partner Roy
O. Disney, is credited with creating the management team that has
brought off a Cinderella-style corporate turnaround at Walt Disney
Co.
   Associates describe Disney, 57, as an unassuming family man who
can make hard-nosed business decisions.
   He goes to work in the Shamrock office building near Disney in
Burbank in deck shoes and short-sleeved shirts and lives in a house
in the nearby Los Angeles suburb of Toluca Lake.
   Disney spends his spare time with his wife, Patricia, and four
grown children, and as the hands-on skipper of his 70-foot racing
sloop, Pyewacket.
   Disney is a regular entrant in the Trans-Pacific sailing race
from California to Hawaii, finished third this year in the Memorial
Day California Cup race and is a respected competitor, said Frank
Gleberman, commodore of the California Yacht Club in Marina Del Rey.
   ``There are owners who go along for the ride and there are
owners who are competitors, and he is one of the latter,''
Gleberman said. ``He's thorough and aggressive.''
   Disney has spent his working life at the family's company, in
general management and producing television cartoons and the
trademark Disney nature shows.
   In 1984, disenchanted with the management of the company by Walt
Disney's son-in-law, Ronald Miller, Roy Disney quit the company's
board, brought in the investing Bass brothers of Texas as allies in
fending off two outside takeover attempts and ended up in control
of the Disney empire.
   Working with his attorney and associate Stanley Gold, Disney
installed Michael Eisner and Frank Wells as chairman and president
and has helped the company rebound with renewed vigor at its
amusement parks and its wildly successful new movie studio,
Touchstone.
   A decade ago, Disney formed Shamrock to diversify his
investments, though his family's 4 million shares of Disney _ worth
$251.5 million based on Wednesday's closing price _ form Shamrock's
backbone.
   Shamrock owns television stations KITV in Honolulu, KEYT in
Santa Barbara, Calif., and WTVQ in Lexington, Ky. and 14 radio
stations. In addition to a large investment portfolio and extensive
real estate holdings in the West and in Hawaii, the company owns 22
percent of Enterra Crop., a Houston-based oilfiled services company.
   Shamrock officials will not disclose the closely-held company's
value, but a slick publicity brochure says its revenue ``would rank
it comfortably in the top half of the Fortune 500.'' Forbes
magazine estimated Shamrock's net worth at $400 million in 1986.
   With Disney as chairman and Gold as president and chief
executive officer running the day-to-day operations, the company
takes an active hand managing its investments and in seeking new
ones.
   Shamrock said in 1987 it made $125 million on the sale of
Central Soya Co. Inc. of Fort Wayne, Ind., to an Italian company.
Shamrock had bought Central Soya two years earlier for $303 million
in a leveraged buyout.
   Shamrock has scored gains on short-term investments in the likes
of Mobile Communications Corp. of America and Orion Capital Corp.
Its most recent acquisition was Music Plus, a 56-outlet chain of
record stores in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
