<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankMerger     07-20 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Merger,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDIC Allows Merger of Two Texas Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM LOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal insurors Wednesday gave preliminary
approval to a merger of two giant Texas bank holding companies,
promising $475 million worth of assistance in the deal.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said it will help two
Minnesota companies invest in the merger and recapitalization of
Fort Worth-based Texas American Bancshares Inc. and San
Antonio-based National Bancshares Corp.
   Stanley J. Poling, director of the FDIC's Dallas office, said
existing shareholders in the two Texas companies would initially
own five percent of the equity interests of the new firm, which has
not yet been named.
   The two Minneapolis-based companies, MEI Diversified Inc. and
Bank Shares Inc., led by Carl R. Pohlad, will invest $200 million
in the merger.
   Pohlad said the new company would become the fourth largest bank
holding company in Texas, with about $8 billion in assets and 63
banking offices.
   Insurors chose Pohlad over two Texas investor groups to help in
the merger.
   Pohlad thinks the merger will be completed by the end of the
year.
   ``I think the Texas economy has bottomed out,'' Pohlad said at a
press conference. ``I really think it's going to get better.
   The 72-year-old Pohlad also owns baseball's 1987 world champion
Minnesota Twins.
   Texas American lost $195 million in 1986 and 1987 and $17.8
million in this year's first quarter. National Bancshares lost $96
million in the two years and $11.4 million in the first quarter.
   As of March, problem loans at the two companies had reached
nearly $900 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
