<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Times     07-20 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Times,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Times Reports Profit Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times Co. on Wednesday reported a 2
percent increase in its second-quarter net income, which was
adversely affected by lower advertising volume and labor problems
at its flagship New York Times.
   Net income for the quarter ended June 30 totaled $45.1 million,
or 55 cents a share, up from $44.1 million, or 54 cents a share, in
the year-ago period.
   Revenue for the quarter increased 7 percent to $456.4 million
from $426.3 million in the second quarter of 1987.
   Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, chairman and chief executive, said in a
statement that although second-quarter operating results were
``adversely impacted by lower advertising volume and job actions by
the Newspaper Mail and Deliverers Union, we have continued to
invest heavily in the development of many of our properties.''
   Operating profit generated by the company's newspaper group,
which is comprised of The New York Times, 35 regional papers and a
one-third interest in the International Herald Tribune, declined 17
percent to $64.6 million on revenue of $360.1 million.
   Higher newsprint prices affected the papers. Advertising linage
at The Times was off 3.4 percent during the quarter, while 32 of
the regional papers posted a 4 percent gain in advertising.
   Job actions by the mail and deliverers union have stopped, but
no agreement has been reached, the company noted.
   Profit increased about 4 percent in the magazine group to $5.8
million on revenue of $68.7 million. Strong performances by Family
Circle and Golf Digest had a favorable impact on the group.
   Broadcasting and cable operations reported a 7 percent gain in
profit, which totaled $4.8 million on revenue of $27.6 million. The
company reported that an increased number of subscribers to its NYT
Cable TV helped offset continued softness in national spot
television advertising.
   For the first six months, the company reported net income of
$90.6 million, or $1.11 a share, up 6 percent from net income of
$85.2 million, or $1.04 a share, a year earlier. Six-month revenue
totaled $886.7 million, up 6 percent from $835.3 million a year ago.
</TEXT>
