<FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-88 2252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HardRockSold     07-20 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hard Rock Sold,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hard Rock Cafe Owner Agrees To Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard Rock International PLC, owner of seven Hard
Rock Cafe restaurants in six countries, has agreed to a $107
million buyout by Pleasurama PLC, a British leisure industry
holding company.
   Pleasurama agreed to acquire Hard Rock's class A restricted
voting shares for 1 pound a share, or about $1.70 at current
exchange rates. Hard Rock stock traded in this country as American
Depositary Shares, each equalling five class A shares, would be
bought for 5 pounds per ADS.
   Pleasurama also will acquire all of Hard Rock's regular common
shares through a cash tender offer in the United Kingdom, the
company said. That offer does not apply to class A shares or ADSs.
   The overall buyout was conditioned on completion of that tender
offer, a planned $216.5 million rights offering to fund the buyout,
and approval by Hard Rock shareholders and British regulators. Hard
Rock's board of directors already has approved the takeover.
   Hard Rock is most famous for its string of restaurants, which
offer American-style food accompanied by blaring music and an
eclectic decor featuring rock 'n' roll artifacts. It also
merchandises the Hard Rock name on souvenirs, t-shirts and other
items.
   Hard Rock International owns Hard Rock Cafes in New York;
London; Dallas; Tokyo; Reykjavik, Iceland; Cancun, Mexico; and
Stockholm.
   Hard Rock co-founder Isaac Tigrett was expected to remain in
charge of the restaurant business, according to a spokesman.
   Tigrett founded the business in 1971 with former partner Peter
Morton, and after a split several years ago retained rights to the
Hard Rock name everywhere but the United States west of Chicago and
in Australia and Brazil.
   Pleasurama is the holding company for a diversified British
leisure group that includes hotels, vacations, casinos, property
development and amusement machines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
