<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0272 07-20 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0272,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Down, Dollar Up In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closings, quotes. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices dipped during morning trading Thursday
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar gained ground
against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 404.95-point
winner Wednesday, retreated 135.11 points to finish the morning
session at 27,418.87.
   Stock brokers attributed the turnaround of the market's most
widely followed index to profit-taking following the major gain on
Wednesday.
   ``The environment is not poor,'' said a broker at Nikko
Securities Co, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``I don't see
many negative factors today. Shares should regain strength after
absorbing the profit-taking.''
   Brokers said electronics shares, most of which soared Wednesday,
were weak Thursday morning.
   The dollar, which lost 0.80 yen Wednesday, opened up 0.60 yen at
133.65 yen following the strong showing of the U.S. currency
overnight in New York, and was changing hands at 133.80 yen by late
morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
